<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DodgerBlues     10-07 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dodger Blues,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Dodgers Are Coming Back _ To Queens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been 31 years since ``Dem Bums'' became
beach bums, since Walter O'Malley moved the Brooklyn Dodgers to Los
Angeles.
   The wounds have yet to heal.
   Today, the Dodgers return _ to Shea Stadium, not Ebbets Field _
to play the New York Mets for the National League pennant. But to
many Brooklynites, this homecoming to the borough of Queens will be
happy only if the Dodgers go down in defeat.
   ``The old Brooklyn Dodgers were a very special team, in a very
special time, in a very special place. The Los Angeles Dodgers are
not really the Dodgers,'' said Brooklynite Frances Macrillo.
   ``They don't look like the Dodgers, they don't sound like the
Dodgers,'' she continued. ``It's very easy to root for the Mets.''
   Ms. Macrillo's cheers are echoed by the many Brooklyn fans who
swore off the Dodgers on Oct. 23, 1957, when O'Malley moved the
team of Jackie Robinson, Pee Wee Reese and Duke Snider closer to
Catalina than Coney Island.
   Boxing publicist Irving Rudd describes ``Dodgeritis'' as a
borough-wide lethargy brought on by the shift; state Sen. Thomas
Bartosiewicz spent years trying to get support for an ``Ebbets
Dome'' and a new team; New York Post columnist Pete Hamill writes
of his vow to ``never forgive, never forget'' the late O'Malley.
   ``They abandoned us, they left us. I feel no compunction to root
for the Dodgers,'' said Marty Adler, founder of the Brooklyn
Dodgers Hall of Fame. ``When they left us, I was angry. ... When
they left, they took the soul. The soul left Brooklyn.''
   Ebbets Field, home of Brooklyn's beloved Bums, was razed in
1960. As far as many younger fans know, the Dodgers have always
played in California's Chavez Ravine.
   ``I think a lot of this is passe now and over with,'' said New
York Knicks public relations man Dennis D'Agostino, a die-hard Mets
fan who wrote a book about the team's history. ``I don't read as
much into this as other people do.
   ``If you were 15 when the Dodgers left, you're 46 now. What do
you remember about the Dodgers? They've been gone 31 years. The
Mets have been playing for 26 years.''
   Try telling that to Hamill, who welcomed the Dodgers to the
playoffs with a vitriolic column in which O'Malley's name was
preceded each time with an epithet.
   ``Some wounds never heal,'' wrote Hamill, who broke a
three-decade boycott of Dodgers home games this week to root for
the Mets (who, by the way, have eight native Californians on the
roster).
   ``I go to the enemy camp'' _ Dodgers Stadium, that is _ ``as a
hostile witness,'' he wrote. ``And the vow still holds. Never
forgive. Never, ever forget.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
