<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Disruption 4thLd-Writethru a0764 10-07 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Disruption, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0764,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Disrupts Reagan Appearance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 10th graf pvs bgng, `He just,' to
UPDATE with Secret Service questioning McKnight, releasing him</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man claiming he had been the subject of
government mind control experiments disrupted an appearance by
President Reagan before a Republican fund-raising dinner Friday
night.
   The man made a long and rambling argument that he had been
mistreated, while guests at the $1,000-a-plate event attempted to
drown him out with applause. The disruption occurred just after
Reagan concluded his address to the crowd.
   Reagan, standing just behind the lectern he'd used for his
speech, seemed puzzled as he strained to hear the man.
   Secret Service agents on the scene made no attempt to approach
the man, who identified himself as William McKnight, 58, of
Inkster, Mich.
   But after several moments of yelling toward Reagan, who was
approximately 150 feet away on the podium, the president
interrupted him.
   Reagan went to the microphone and said that he was having
difficulty hearing the man, although he said the protester seemed
to ``feel strongly'' about what he was saying.
   But the president, showing increasing impatience and anger,
shouted that ``I don't think it's fair to subject the people to all
of this. Why don't you write it in a letter and send it to me.''
   The Secret Service had arrested the same man in 1985 when he
tried to deliver papers about mind control to former President
Jimmy Carter during a Detroit appearance.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, asked later if Reagan
had felt endangered by the intruder, said, ``No, not at all.''
   ``He just said, `Who was that man and what did he want
anyway?''' Fitzwater said, paraphrasing the president.
   Secret Service Special Agent Bill Corbett said late Friday that
McKnight was interviewed and released. No charges were filed.
   ``He was interviewed. He made no threats against the president.
He meant no harm to him. That's the main thing the Secret Service
was interested in,'' Corbett said.
   Few incidents of this sort have plagued Reagan in recent years
as security surrounding him was tightened substantially following
his shooting on March 30, 1981 by John W. Hinckley Jr. Hinckley
remains confined to a mental hospital in Washington.
   After Reagan told the man to be quiet, the concluding part of
the president's portion of the program proceeded and he left
without incident.
   McKnight did not say how he had gotten into the event, nor
whether he had paid the $1,000 fee. But pressed on that, he said,
``I just walked in.''
   The man stood apart from the dinner tables in an area not far
from the president occupied by a pool of reporters admitted to
cover Reagan's speech.
   It was apparent that Secret Service agents determined the man
was not presenting any physical threat to Reagan, and therefore no
attempt was made to rush him.
   ``I was quiet and let him speak. I was quiet and stood here,''
McKnight told reporters.
   During his tirade, McKnight had asked, ``Why don't you take the
mind control machine off of me, Reagan?''
   ``Why don't you use it on the communists that's here in America,
and why don't you get rid of communism in America?'' he said.
   Several boos emanated from the well-heeled crowd of Republican
donors, many of whom were heard shouting, ``Get out and shut up!''
   McKnight was arrested on April 24, 1985, when he tried to
deliver to Carter a three-page typewritten document saying he was
the victim of a U.S. government mind-control device.
   McKnight, who listed an Inkster, Mich., address on the document,
said the device injured his eyesight and muscles and his ability to
learn and to have sex.
   Two Secret Service agents knelt beside both sides of his chair
after Carter completed his speech. McKnight resisted the agents and
was taken to the rear of the room with his arm behind his back.
   McKnight told reporters Friday night that he was treated for
three weeks at a state psychiatric hospital in Northville, Mich.,
following the Carter incident. He produced a photocopy of what
appeared to be a report from a Northville staffer, who said
McKnight ``rambled'' about the mind-control device.
   A woman who answered the telephone Friday night at the
Northville hospital said state law prevented her from giving any
information about current or former patients. She hung up without
giving her name.
   There were two McKnights listed in the Inkster telephone
directory. Lula Belle McKnight said neither she nor her daughter
were related to William McKnight.
</TEXT>
