<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Mammography-Medicaid     10-07 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mammography-Medicaid,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congresswomen Push for Medicare Payments for Mammography
Screenings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two congresswomen say they will push for
legislation next year to allow full Medicare coverage for elderly
women seeking mammography screenings, the X-ray technique used to
detect early signs of breast cancer.
   ``We need to promote preventive medicine, not just pay for care
once an illness has set in,'' Rep. Barbara B. Kennelly, a member of
the House Ways and Means Committee, said Thursday.
   Mrs. Kennelly said the Medicare Catastrophic Coverage Act,
enacted into law earlier this year, included a $50 reimbursement
provision for the mammograms.
   ``A $50 mammogram is not readily available in the United
States,'' the congresswoman said. ``The average cost for a
mammogram ranges from $80 to $200.''
   Mrs. Kennelly said the only place a woman can receive a
mammogram for $50 is mobile van clinics.
   ``Most women, especially older women, simply will not submit to
being examined by a stranger in a van in the parking lot of a
shopping mall,'' she said.
   ``Not only is a woman more likely to undergo the test when under
the care of someone she knows and with whom she is comfortable, but
doctors are more able to identify changes over time, and are able
to provide the analysis, counseling and follow-up that are
necessary to effectively care for patients,'' she said.
   A bill introduced by Mrs. Kennelly would remove the $50 cap,
making Medicare coverage for mammogram screenings the same as for
mammograms for women already diagnosed with breast cancer.
   The Office of Technology Assessment has estimated that screening
women over 65 could reduce the breast cancer mortality rate by 50
percent after five years, according to Mrs. Kennelly.
   ``Breast cancer took the lives of 45,000 women in 1987, of which
28,000 were over age 65. Many of those lives could have been saved
if mammograms were readily available and affordable to those
women,'' she told a Capitol news conference.
   The American Cancer Society recommends that women over 40
undergo mammography screenings annually.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
