<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Guinness-Johnson     10-07 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Guinness-Johnson,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guinness Weighs Placing Johnson's Time In Record Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Editors of the Guinness Book of Records are
debating whether to list Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson as the
world-record holder for his 9.79-second 100-meter run at the
Olympic Games in South Korea.
   Johnson, 26, was stripped of the gold medal he won in the race
Oct. 24 after testing positive for performance-enhancing anabolic
steroids, banned by the International Olympic Committee. The
committee erased his time from the books.
   The International Amateur Athletic Federation banned Johnson
from competition for two years, while the Olympic committee awarded
the first-place prize to Johnson's U.S. rival, Carl Lewis, who had
finished second with a time of 9.92 seconds.
   ``It would be ridiculous to say he (Johnson) didn't run the 100
meters in 9.79, because he clearly did,'' Stewart Newport, deputy
sports editor of the Guinness records book, said Thursday.
   The annual publication lists world records for everything from
sporting events to the heaviest human to the longest mustache.
   ``There's no denying he did the time,'' Newport said. ``That
cannot be taken away from him. We have to consider him for
inclusion, although it has put us in a difficult position because
of the drugs.''
   Editors of the Guinness Book of Records will hold a series of
meetings to consider the issue, Newport said, but he could not
predict a date for their decision. Events from the Seoul games are
too late for the book's 1989 edition, due on bookshelves Oct. 14.
   The Jamaican-born Johnson already appears in an appendix to the
1988 edition of the Guinness book for his previous 100-meter record
run of 9.83 seconds, set Aug. 30, 1987 in Rome.
</TEXT>
