<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-YugoslaviaQ&A     10-07 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia Q&A,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Problems Complicated By Government Structure</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Yugoslavia, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia's complex, cumbersome government structure and
diversity of nationalities are major factors in its worsening
ethnic and economic problems. Here is some background in
question-and-answer form:
   Q: How does the government work?
   A: Yugoslavia is a federation of six republics and two
autonomous provinces that are administrative parts of the largest
republic, Serbia.
   Power rests in the League of Communists, or Communist Party.
Each republic and province has its own party hierarchy for
political leadership and its own government for administration.
   Each republic and autonomous province sends representatives to
the federal party leadership, headed by a 23-member Politburo, and
the nine-man federal presidency.
   Leadership of those two bodies rotates annually. Only the
premier of the federal government, which is primarily responsible
for overseeing the economy and national defense, holds office for
four years. The premier can be removed by a majority vote of
Parliament.
   Q: Why is the system so complex?
   A: The 23 million Yugoslavs include about 30 nationalities. In
an apparent attempt to prevent ethnic strife after his death,
President Tito approved a 1974 constitution giving broad powers to
each republic and province.
   He decreed that all decisions on major political questions must
be approved by the leaderships of all republics and provinces, and
national leadership posts would rotate annually to keep any
republic from dominating.
   Q: What happened after Tito's death in 1980?
   A: Unanimity is so hard to achieve that federal decision are
weak compromises, and the largely state-run economy has
deteriorated as a result. The foreign debt is $21 billion,
unemployment 15 percent and the annual inflation rate 217 percent.
More than 1,500 strikes were reported in 1987.
   Economic and political differences have grown between the rich
northern region, which looks to the West, and the poorer, more
backward south.
   Q: What is causing the current unrest?
   A: A mixture of ethnic strife, economic crisis and an
ineffective political system.
   One fundamental element is the ethnic dispute in Kosovo, a
backward autonomous province in south that was the heart of
medieval Serbia's great empire.
   Kosovo now is dominated by predominantly Moslem ethnic
Albanians, who have the highest birthrate in Europe and are 90
percent of the province's 2 million people. Minority Serbs, most of
whom are Christian, say they are being harassed and began holding
rallies in July.
   Serbs in Kosovo found a supporter in the Serbian Communist party
leader, Slobodan Milosevic, who is trying to impose more Serbian
control on Kosovo and the other autonomous province, Vojvodina.
   Milosevic's opponents accuse him of using the street protests to
seek greater national power for himself and Serbia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881007-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DelaMadrid     10-07 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-De la Madrid,0774</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Relations With US Difficult But Make Mexico More
Independent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Miguel de la Madrid says the United
States is a difficult neighbor, but living next to such a powerful
country has made Mexico more independent.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, de la Madrid said
that during his six-year term the two countries have improved
understanding on the thorny issue of illegal drug trafficking.
Industrialized countries in general, he said, have begun to
understand that developing nations' foreign debt problems affect
the entire world economy.
   De la Madrid, 54, turns the government over to his successor,
former Budget Secretary Carlos Salinas de Gortari, on Dec. 1, after
presiding over some of the country's most difficult years. Both men
are from the Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has not lost
a major office since it was founded in 1929.
   ``Relations between Mexico and the United States have always
been very difficult, so difficult that we lost half our territory
in the last century,'' de la Madrid said in the interview Wednesday.
   But the challenge of living next to such a wealthy and
complicated country, he said, has made Mexicans more nationalistic.
   ``Perhaps that is one of the great advantages of being a
neighbor of the United States: our desire to continue being an
independent and sovereign nation that rules its own destiny,'' he
said.
   ``I believe the basis of the problems is a lack of knowledge of
each other,'' de la Madrid said.
   Two-thirds of Mexico's trade, tourism and investment are from
the United States and there is a constant flow of citizens back and
forth across the border. The result is continuous problems of
immigration, trade, drug trafficking and foreign policy
differences, particularly on Central America.
   The United States backs rebels fighting Nicaragua's leftist
government and supports the Salvadoran government's war against
leftist rebels there. It has failed to win the support it would
like from Mexico, which opposes the U.S. intervention and has been
more sympathetic to Nicaragua's government and the Salvadoran
rebels.
   ``There are some in the United States who think that because
Mexico is an independent country with its own foreign policy that
it is not a friend of the United States,'' he said. ``I do not
believe that is true. We are friends of the United States but in
some things we do not think alike.''
   Illegal narcotics trafficking through Mexico has been one of the
biggest sources of conflict between the two countries during de la
Madrid's term.
   President Reagan, Secretary of State George P. Shultz and other
top U.S. officials have recognized Mexico's efforts to fight drug
trafficking, de la Madrid said.
   However, he added, ``there are lower-level officials who, to
avoid responsibility, put the blame on Mexico. It seems to me an
infantile attitude.''
   He said he believed U.S. officials have recognized the
importance of demand for illegal drugs in the problem of drug
trafficking.
   ``That is a great advance, since you have to accept the reality
that the United States is the biggest consumer of drugs in the
world and that constitutes an enormous motive to promote production
or transportation from other parts of the world,'' he said.
   He said there were ``slight and tenuous signs'' of understanding
that the developing countries' huge foreign debts have worldwide
implications.
   Mexico's $104 billion foreign debt is the second highest in the
Third World, after Brazil's.
   De la Madrid said both U.S. presidential candidates, Vice
President George Bush and Michael Dukakis, along with European
leaders, have recognized that ways must be found to overcome the
problem.
   ``What is needed now is for that recognition to be converted
into political will and specific formulas,'' he said.
   ``Mexico insists on joint responsibility of debtor and creditor
for the debt,'' he said.
   ``It is not possible that, in the case of the Latin American
countries, we resign ourselves to the economic stagnation of a
growing population with so many needs.''
   He said debtor nations must ``set our house in order
internally'' while demanding ``a fair and realistic deal from
creditors.''
   De la Madrid has maintained Mexico's commitment to keep up with
debt service payments, establishing unpopular austerity measures.
   Subsidies were eliminated, prices went up and workers' salaries
lost more than half their buying power. ``But my concern was to
protect the majorities and to do that we had to defend the
productive sectors and employment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
