<DOCNO> AP881007-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDS-Justice     10-07 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Justice,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gay Rights Group Lauds Decision On Anti-Discrimination Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The executive director of a gay rights group
says the Justice Department is ``finally catching up with legal
reality'' by declaring that anti-discrimination laws extend to
federal employees with the AIDS virus.
   An opinion issued Thursday by the Office of Legal Counsel
concludes that the federal Rehabilitation Act _ which protects the
handicapped in the federal workforce or in programs receiving
federal aid _ also applies to employees with the AIDS virus.
   The opinion is in line with a Supreme Court ruling last year and
the Civil Rights Restoration Act of 1987 passed by Congress.
   The Justice Department is ``finally catching up with legal
reality,'' said Jeff Levi, executive director of the National Gay
and Lesbian Task Force. Many state handicapped laws have already
been changed to protect people infected with AIDS.
   In view of the Supreme Court opinion and other court rulings,
the Justice Department's revised position is ``a little late in
coming; in fact it's a lot late in coming,'' said David Barr, staff
attorney for the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund.
   The opinion says that those with the AIDS virus in whom the
disease has progressed can be excluded from the workplace if they
pose a threat to the health or safety of others or are unable to do
their job.
   Since the available medical information shows that the risk of
infection being transmitted in the normal course of the workplace
is very low, an AIDS-infected employee ``by and large ... should be
treated like any other employee,'' Assistant Attorney General
Douglas Kmiec, head of the Office of Legal Counsel, told a news
conference.
   Kmiec said an AIDS-infected employee ``should be assessed for
his ability to do the job like anyone else.''
   The legal opinion differs sharply from an opinion his
predecessor, Charles Cooper, issued in June 1986, that employers
may discriminate against victims of contagious diseases such as
AIDS based on an irrational fear of contagion.
   The Supreme Court rejected that argument last year, extending
the protection of the federal Rehabilitation Act to people
handicapped by contagious disease, including AIDS.
   The legal opinion adheres to President Reagan's statement of
last August in which he said that federal employers should treat
those infected with the AIDS virus like any other employees, as
long as they don't pose health and safety dangers or performance
problems.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh issued a statement with Kmiec's
opinion saying there are legitimate questions as to whether
existing laws to protect the handicapped can adequately serve AIDS
victims. He noted that the Rehabilitation Act was passed in 1973,
well before the advent of AIDS.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a contagious disease that
affects the body's immune system, rendering it incapable of
resisting other diseases and infections. The virus most often is
spread through contact with blood, blood products or semen. As of
Monday, 74,809 people had been reported as having AIDS since 1981,
of whom 42,142 have died. No one is known to have recovered from
AIDS.
   Sixty-two percent of those with AIDS are homosexual or bisexual
males, according to the National Centers for Disease Control. As
many as 1.5 million Americans are infected with the AIDS virus, the
CDC estimates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881007-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-FloridaSenate     10-07 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Florida Senate,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Longshot Mack Heading Into Final Stretch Against Democratic
Survivor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although Connie Mack III had a major
league name, the Republican congressman was still viewed as a minor
player in Florida politics when he began his challenge one year ago
for three-term, Democratic Sen. Lawton Chiles' seat.
   Today, a well-funded Mack is heading into the final stretch
against the survivor of a bruising Democratic primary, U.S. Rep.
Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay.
   Since the day Mack formally announced his plans _ Oct. 19, 1987
_ the U.S. congressman has watched his fortunes rise with the
decision of each potential opponent.
   The 58-year-old Chiles, chairman of the Senate Budget Committee,
stunned his party in December by deciding not to seek re-election.
Then Democratic front-runner Reubin Askew, the former two-term
governor, abruptly withdrew May 7, citing weariness with the amount
of time spent raising funds.
   The decisions by Chiles and Askew triggered a six-way Democratic
race in which MacKay made a late comeback to finish second in the
Sept. 6 primary, then overtook Bill Gunter, the state's Insurance
Commissioner since 1976, in a runoff on Tuesday.
   Polling by the Mack campaign showed MacKay gaining momentum
prior to the runoff so the Republican candidate went after his
likely opponent with an ad campaign titled, ``Hey Buddy, You're
Liberal.''
   Mack describes his rival as a tax-loving, wild-spending liberal
while portraying himself as a conservative Republican cut from the
same cloth as President Reagan.
   ``I think that Florida is a conservative state and I represent a
conservative viewpoint,'' said Mack, a former bank president and
grandson of his namesake, the famous Philadelphia Athletics and
Hall of Fame baseball manager.
   Mack, who was elected to the House in 1982, has one of the most
conservative records in Congress, scoring 90-plus percent on the
scorecards of conservative rating groups and sometimes zero in
marks from liberal rating organizations.
   Mack has criticized his rival for opposing military aid to the
Nicaraguan rebels, the MX missile and the B-1 bomber, and for
voting for congressional pay hikes.
   ``There is a clear choice between conservative Connie Mack and
liberal Buddy MacKay,'' said Mack, who has stuck to a theme of
``less taxes, less spending, less government, more freedom.''
   MacKay, an attorney from a wealthy central Florida family,
generally shunned big-spending programs, according to his
congressional record, but is more open to government involvement
than Mack.
   While serving in Congress since 1982, MacKay has been active in
deficit-reduction. During his tenure in the Florida Legislature, he
was a leader in civil rights and open government.
   ``We need to talk about each of our records, what we have
done,'' said MacKay. ``The issues remain the same, who can do the
best job for the state of Florida. I intend to talk specifics
during the general election, I don't intend to allow Mr. Mack to
continue talking generalities and philosophies.''
   MacKay, who has said he would consider new taxes to deal with
the escalating national deficit, also plans to make Mack's
environmental record an issue.
   ``The people of Florida are concerned about the environment and
Connie Mack's record on the environment is one of the worst ... not
just in the Florida delegation where it's the worst, but in all of
America,'' said MacKay. ``That's not a Republican issue or a
Democratic issue. Republicans care about the environment as much as
Democrats.''
   While the negative Democratic campaign between Gunter and MacKay
led to predictions of a divided party, Gunter quickly promised to
work for MacKay. MacKay had attacked Gunter's integrity, while
Gunter had charged that MacKay betrayed Israel, senior citizens and
the anti-drug effort with votes in Congress.
   Mack rode the support of his party's hierarchy and a $2 million
campaign warchest to a primary victory over former U.S. Attorney
Robert Merkle.
   Although Merkle entered the GOP primary just 10 weeks before the
Sept. 6 election and without any money, he was able to attract
nearly 40 percent of the vote against the telegenic Mack.
   MacKay, meanwhile, was building momentum. After polls in the
final month before the primary showed him running third, he slipped
past Rep. Dan Mica to make the runoff against Gunter.
   The Republicans have targeted Florida in their hopes of
regaining a majority in the Senate. A strong showing by Republican
presidential nominee George Bush, who is expected to win the state,
could also hurt MacKay.
   And then there is the money factor.
   Mack's campaign has raised more than $4 million, including
$860,000 from the GOP's national Senate campaign committee, and
spent about $3.5 million to maintain his media effort.
   MacKay raised and spent $1.5 million he needed to reach the
general election. The national Democratic Senate Committee is
expected to give MacKay $700,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
