<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle-TheQuestion     10-07 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle-The Question,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Questions Linger on Quayle's Fitness for No. 2 Job, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle missed a once-in-a-campaign
opportunity to bury doubts about his competence to serve as
president if need be, several political analysts say.
   Quayle's halting and at times unresponsive answers at the vice
presidential debate to repeated questions about his readiness to
lead the country left some Republicans shaking their heads.
   ``As a Republican, I sat there trying to pull words out of his
mouth,'' said GOP consultant Tom Edmonds. ``Frankly, I think there
are a lot of family dogs that could have answered the question
better.''
   ``I think he was so afraid of striking out that he never swung
the bat,'' Edmonds said.
   During Wednesday's debate in Omaha, Neb., with Senate colleague
Lloyd Bentsen, Quayle repeatedly cited his 12 years' service in
Congress as his principal qualification for the vice presidency.
   When asked what he would do in the event of a presidential
death, the Indiana senator said he would pray for himself and the
country and then call a meeting of Cabinet members and top
presidential advisers. He said little more, though pressed by
questioners.
   Among those dissatisfied with the response was conservative
direct-mail fund-raiser Richard Viguerie, who said Quayle did all
right on all the questions but those concerning his qualification
and fitness for the vice presidency.
   ``I'm sympathetic to the guy because he was too coached ... and
told, `Whatever you do, don't do this and don't do that,'''
Viguerie said.
   George Bush's campaign chairman, James A. Baker III, denied on
ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America'' that Quayle was overprogrammed
for the face-off. He said he believed there was ``a lot more
spontaneity'' than in the debate between Bush and Democrat Michael
Dukakis.
   ``I think he did make some headway, but I think that public
opinion was so critical of him beforehand that he had nowhere to go
but up,'' said Larry Sabato, a political scientist at the
University of Virginia.
   Patrick Buchanan, a conservative columnist who served for a time
as White House communications director for President Reagan, said
``this whole debate was about Dan Quayle and I think, under
pressure, he did quite well. And I don't think anybody ... is going
to say, ``Well, gee, this fellow's not even qualified to be vice
president of the United States.''
   But Vic Fingerhut, a Democratic pollster, said ``I don't think
he (Quayle) did resolve the question'' regarding his qualifications
for the office.
   ``For the hard-core Democrats and Republicans. this thing meant
nothing,'' he said. ``It was just a reaffirmation of views they
already held. I just think that ... people who are in the middle
(undecided) are as interested as the media are in the question
about his fitness.''
   ``Actually, the people who think Quayle's a jerk will still vote
the ticket if they like George Bush,'' he said.
</TEXT>
