<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PeregrineFalcon     10-07 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peregrine Falcon,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Endangered Bird Spotted In Kansas City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dead quail have been placed at several
downtown locations in an effort to attract and identify an
endangered peregrine falcon that has been spotted flying among
office buildings.
   ``We're not sure when it showed up,'' said Joe Werner, an urban
biologist for the Missouri Conservation Department. ``We had two
last year, December through March.''
   The falcon has an identification band on its leg, but
conservationists will need a closer look to determine where it came
from. One of the birds spotted last year was discovered to be from
the Yukon; the other was hatched at a conservation site in
Rochester, Minn.
   To attract the bird and determine its origin, the Conservation
Department is putting dead quail on a ledge on the 18th floor of
the Commerce Bank Building and in a nesting box atop another
building, Werner said.
   Conservationists think the bird may have come from a falcon
release site in Omaha, Neb., the nearest such site to Kansas City.
Six falcons recently were released there, Werner said.
   If the new falcon was hatched in captivity, it should be
attracted to the quail, the main meal at the release sites.
   Wild falcons generally don't eat killed prey, feeding instead on
live birds they snare as they swoop down at up to 200 mph from
their perches, Werner said.
   Werner said this is the migration season for the birds, which
fly each year to South America.
   Workers downtown hope the birds will stick around awhile.
   ``It's really been the highlight of the fall season,'' said Tom
Noack, a lawyer on the 18th floor of the Commerce Bank Building.
</TEXT>
