<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-EasternEurope     10-07 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Eastern Europe,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz's Deputy Heads For Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead
says that in meetings next week with East European leaders he will
offer improved economic relations with the United States in
exchange for greater respect for human rights.
   ``Eastern Europe is at an important crossroads,'' Whitehead told
reporters Thursday.
   ``Fundamentally, what these (Soviet bloc) regimes want from us
are economic support, trade ties and political recognition,'' he
said. ``We have stated our willingness to be helpful, provided we
see real progress in political and economic reform, and greater
tangible respect for the human rights of the citizens in each of
these countries.''
   He said he had made this point in previous meetings with East
European officials.
   The United States and its European allies ``must work together
to use this historic opportunity to advance peaceful, positive
change in Eastern Europe for the good of all the peoples of Europe,
and of the United States,'' he said.
   Whitehead said he would re-emphasize to the East European
leaders the U.S. policy of ``treating the Eastern European
countries not as a bloc, but as individual states, each with their
own history and culture.''
   Whitehead said his sixth trip to Eastern Europe starting Sunday
would take him to the capital of each of the Soviet allies in the
region _ East Germany, Romania, Poland, Czechoslovakia, Hungary and
Bulgaria.
   He plans to brief officials of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization in Brussels on the trip before he returns to
Washington Oct. 21.
   He said he would meet with ``a wide range of people from all
sectors of society,'' not just government officials. State
Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said his meetings would
include religious leaders.
</TEXT>
