<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Obit-Buehl     10-07 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Buehl,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marine Corps Chief of Staff Dead at 56</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gen. Louis H. Buehl III, the Marine Corps'
chief of staff, died at Bethesda Naval Medical Center after
suffering a stroke, the Pentagon said. He was 56.
   Buehl, who died late Wednesday, had held the No. 3 spot in the
Marine hierarchy since October 1987, behind the commandant and the
assistant commandant.
   He was a combat veteran of the Vietnam war and previously had
served as commanding general of the Camp Lejeune, N.C., Marine
Corps Base, as a deputy chief of staff for reserve affairs and as
the senior military assistant to the deputy secretary of defense.
   A Pittsburgh native, Buehl was a graduate of Miami University in
Ohio and received a master's degree in Asian studies from the
University of Michigan. He won his first of three stars in April
1982 when he assumed command of the 1st Marine Brigade at Kaneohe
Bay, Hawaii.
   Buehl's decorations included the Defense Distinguished Service
Medal, the Defense Superior Service Medal, the Legion of Merit with
Combat ``V,'' the Bronze Star with Combat ``V'' and the Navy
Commendation Medal with Combat ``V.''
   He is survived by his wife, the former Georgia Warwick of
Oxford, Ohio; four daughters and one granddaughter. Funeral
services will be held at Fort Myer, Va., next Tuesday, with burial
at Arlington National Cemetery.
</TEXT>
