<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-07 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Stable, Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held its ground against the Japanese yen
Friday, while share prices edged up on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 133.50 yen, up 0.20 yen from Thursday's
close of 133.30 yen. Opening at 133.62 yen, the currency moved in a
range of 133.45-133.63 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 233.15-point
loser the previous day, regained 85.93 points, or 0.32 percent, to
finish trading at 27,258.27. The index rebounded for the first time
this week.
   ``Trading was thin due to a wait-and-see attitude among
participants ahead of the release of U.S. unemployment figures and
the three-day weekend,'' said an analyst with Nomura Securities,
Japan's largest brokerage.
   The U.S. unemployment figure for September was scheduled to be
released later Friday in Washington.
   U.S. markets will be closed for Columbus Day, while exchanges in
Japan will be closed Monday for Sports Day, a national holiday.
   ``Investors are having a hard time deciding whether they should
sell or buy the dollar'' ahead of the three-day weekend both in New
York and Tokyo, said another dealer.
</TEXT>
