<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     10-07 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Left Announces Presidential Candidate, Guerrillas Attack Town Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the political arm
of the leftist rebel movement plans to run for president during
national elections in March, a leftist coalition says.
   Also Thursday, several hundred guerrillas attacked a southern
civil defense post, killing one soldier and wounding three, the
army said. A rocket grenade struck the National Assembly building
but caused no injuries.
   The Democratic Convergence, a coalition of three small leftist
parties, said Guillermo Ungo, a lawyer, would run for president and
Reni Roldan, a physician, would be its vice presidential candidate.
   Ungo is president of the Democratic Revolutionary Front, which
is allied with the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, the
umbrella organization of four guerrilla groups fighting the
U.S.-backed government.
   The Democratic Convergence represents the left's first
participation in elections since 1977. The left previously
contended the civil war made fair elections impossible.
   Up to 400 guerrillas participated in the pre-dawn attack on the
civil defense post in Zaragoza, 10 miles south of San Salvador, an
army sergeant said. His face was bandaged and his clothes were
still covered with blood from a shrapnel wound.
   ``They hit us hard, but they also have dead,'' said the
sergeant, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``They attacked us
on all sides but we managed to fight them off.''
   He said 12 men were on duty at the time of the attack, which
lasted three hours. He did not elaborate on the guerrilla dead.
   Rebels also destroyed the local office of ANTEL, the state-owned
telecommunications enterprise, and blew up two utility poles with
transformers, causing a blackout of the surrounding area, the
sergeant said.
   At the National Assembly, a rocket-propelled grenade struck the
wall of a stairway leading to the main assembly chamber, National
Police Col. Jose Rodriguez said. Spectators were going up the
stairs to view the morning session when the projectile struck, but
no one was hurt, Rodriguez said.
   No group claimed responsibility for the attack, which knocked
some stones loose and left a small hole in the wall.
</TEXT>
