<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0501EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SavannahRiver     10-07 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Savannah River,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Senators Seeking Safety Review Of Savannah River Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four U.S. senators are seeking an independent
safety review of the Savannah River Plant after disclosures that up
to 30 major mishaps over three decades went unreported and in the
wake of an equipment failure that released radioactive gas into the
air.
   The escape Thursday of less than 0.01 millirems of tritium gas
into the atmosphere posed no health threat, said plant spokeswoman
Becky Craft. A millirem is a measure of radiation; a routine chest
X-ray totals about 20 millirems, according to Ms. Craft.
   Workers at the U.S. government-owned plant, the nation's sole
producer of weapons-grade plutonium and tritium, were not evacuated.
   In Washington, Sens. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., James McClure,
R-Idaho, Bennett Johnston, D-La., and Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., called
Thursday for an investigation by the Advisory Committee on Nuclear
Facilities Safety, which was established by Energy Secretary John
Herrington to give independent assessments of operations at nuclear
facilities.
   At the state Capitol in Columbia, 60 miles to the northeast, a
dozen people held a two-hour vigil to demonstrate their concern.
   But in downtown Aiken, most of the customers at Jeff Scott's
beauty and barber shop said Thursday they were unconcerned about
problems at the nearby plant.
   ``Everybody's nonchalant who comes in the shop. They're more
concerned about jobs than danger,'' he said. ``But I'm concerned. I
want to know if there's any danger to the environment, what kind of
danger there'd be to our health.''
   ``It's been there for 30 years and nobody's died yet,'' said
Aiken Mayor H. Odell Weeks.
   Disclosures about problems at the sprawling plant began last
week, when two congressional committees were told that a number of
serious reactor accidents were kept secret for 31 years.
   An internal Energy Department report released Wednesday
concluded that the plant's management undermines safety and
deviates from ``practices common to well-run nuclear plants.'' The
report also cited the undisclosed accidents.
   The draft report criticized the Energy Department and Du Pont,
which operates the plant under contract, for poor staff training,
poor communications and sloppy operating procedures that it said
have undermined safety.
   The 50-page report made a host of recommendations, including
stepping up oversight so problems can be caught before they become
serious.
   A spokesman for Du Pont said company officials had not seen the
report, but already moved to correct some of the deficiencies it
cited.
   Weeks, who has been mayor of the town of 15,000 people for half
of his 80 years, said: ``We've felt we're living in as safe a place
as we can. I'm not at all concerned about the townspeople's
safety.''
   When Aiken residents talk of the plant, which they call ``SRP,''
they speak of jobs and the economic prosperity the prime employer
has meant to the community of tree-lined streets and the
surrounding area near Georgia.
   Anne Smith, owner of the Four Generations gift and antique shop
on the town's main plaza, said: ``The opponents to SRP are raising
questions that need to be made, but there are some people who
become very negative when you go against what's already there.
   ``They have a secure job with great benefits. People don't
question that after a while.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
