<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0441EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-07 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rebounded on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
today while the U.S. dollar inched up against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 133.50 yen, up 0.20 yen from Thursday's
close of 133.30 yen. Opening slightly higher at 133.62 yen, the
currency moved in a tight range of 133.45-133.63 yen, with spot
trading reaching $2.73 billion.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average finally rebounded by
regaining 85.93 points or 0.32 percent to finish trading at
27,258.27. It was the first time the index rose since Oct. 1, after
falling for five straight days.
   Although share prices lost 22.79 points to move to 27,149.55
shortly after the market opened and fell lower afterwards, the
market reversed the trend in the middle of the afternoon session.
   ``The morning session opened majorly affected by the pessimistic
mood following Thursday's loss,'' said a dealer with Daiwa
Securities in Tokyo, adding, ``but the trend changed as high-tech
issues recovered.''
   When the index hit the 26,000 level, investors began buying in
order to make profits, he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``But trading was thin in a wait-and-see mood ahead of the U.S.
unemployment figure later tonight and a three-day holiday,'' the
dealer added. Volume traded on the first section was estimated at
500 million shares.
   On the foreign exchange, ``the dollar-yen rate was hardly
moving,'' said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, who also spoke
anonymously.
   ``Trading was thin, and the spot trading was almost half of what
the market normally trades,'' he said.
   ``It might have happened regardless of the U.S. unemployment
rate and the three-day holiday, but somehow the rate has been
fluctuating,'' he added.
   Oct. 10 is a national holiday for both Japan and the United
States. For Japan it is Health-Sports Day, while the United States
celebrates Columbus Day.
   Both stock and foreign exchange markets in Tokyo are closed on
the second Saturday every month.
</TEXT>
