<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0545EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Haiti     10-07 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Demonstrate Against Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ About 800 street cleaners and
garbage collectors demonstrated in front of City Hall to protest
their firings by newly-appointed Mayor Carmen Christophe, Radio
Haiti-Inter reported.
   Other municipal employees joined the demonstrators Thursday and
went on strike, saying the mayor had no right to fire poor people
and was incompetent, the radio said.
   Ms. Christophe accused the garbage-truck drivers of being
followers of ousted Mayor Franck Romain, who is reputed to be a
leader of the dreaded Tonton Macoutes, the feared henchmen of the
Duvalier regime.
   Romain is suspected of being a mastermind of the Sept. 11 attack
on the St. Jean Bosco church that left 12 dead and more than 70
wounded.
   Rank-and-file soldiers named the massacre at St. Jean Bosco as
one of the reasons for the Sept. 17 revolt in which they overthrew
Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy. Namphy, now in exile, was replaced by Lt.
Gen. Prosper Avril.
   The flamboyant Ms. Christophe, a money-lender and owner of a
chain of lottery shops, was named to replace Romain by the
rank-and-file soldiers who engineered the coup.
   She accused the garbage collectors Thursday of having stolen
6,000 gallons of gasoline and 50 of the city's 56 garbage trucks,
and of switching old tires for new ones and selling them.
   In another incident Thursday, several hundred demonstrators
briefly blocked traffic on the highway between the capital and the
International Airport. The demonstrators were protesting their
expulsion Tuesday from what they claim to be state-owned lands
abandoned by dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier when he was ousted in
February 1986.
   One person was killed and three wounded when soldiers from the
Presidential Guard expelled the squatters.
   Radio Soleil said five soldiers were seen among the
demonstrators, apparently expressing solidarity with the protest.
   Also Thursday, troops dispersed several dozen people in
Port-de-Daix, a northern port town, who demonstrated against
allegedly incompetent government officials, Haiti-Inter said.
</TEXT>
