<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-US     10-07 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-US,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roh To Meet Reagan During U.N. Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo will meet with
President Reagan in Washington to discuss trade policies between
the two nations and other issues, a government official said today.
   The talks will take place Oct. 20 after Roh addresses the U.N.
General Assembly on Oct. 18, the official said.
   The official, who asked not be identified, said Roh will discuss
ways to improve relations with North Korea and other communist
countries, including the Soviet Union.
   The official said the Reagan and Roh also will discuss trade
between the two nations. U.S. officials have demanded that South
Korea relax restrictions on U.S. imports in South Korea.
   Roh and Reagan last met in September 1987 when the Roh visited
Washington as the presidential candidate of the ruling Democratic
Justice Party.
   Roh won the country's first direct presidential relections in 16
years in December and was inaugurated in February.
   Roh is to leave Seoul on Oct. 12 to address the U.N. General
Assembly for the first time as a chief executive of South Korea. He
will be accompanied on the trip by Foreign Minister Choi Kwang-soo.
   South and North Korea are not U.N. members but the world body
has decided to hear speeches from the two Koreas. It was not known
who would speak for North Korea.
</TEXT>
