<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Medflies     10-07 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medflies,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aerial Spraying Begins Three-Part Attack Against Medfly
Infestation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Overnight aerial spraying to kill a
Mediterranean fruit fly infestation left much of the city's West
Side looking like Christo artwork, as residents wrapped cars,
playground equipment and other belongings in plastic.
   Pesticide-laden helicopters criss-crossed a 35-square-mile area
until early today in the first step of an all-out attack against
the Medfly, an agricultural pest that destroys about 250 varieties
of produce.
   The insecticide Malathion poses no health risk, agriculture
officials said, but they warned residents that the sticky corn
syrup in which it was mixed to attract the flies could damage a
car's paint.
   The alert prompted a run on tarpaulins and plastic wrap at
stores throughout the area.
   ``People say a lot of chain stores are out of the stuff,'' said
Allan Goldman of Culver City Hardware.
   The effect of the protective measures was especially striking at
the Los Angeles County Art Museum, where outdoor sculptures swathed
in black plastic and tape recalled fences and bridges transformed
into artworks through similar wrapping by Christo, the
Bulgarian-born artist.
   The spraying was ordered because 47 Medflies were found in the
Palms area since Sept. 26, agricultural officials said.
   But aerial spraying was only the first step in the three-part
attack against the pest, said Gera Curry, a spokeswoman for the
California Department of Food and Agriculture.
   A quarantine against transporting fruit and vegetables from the
area is expected to go into effect today or Monday, she said.
   The final step will be the release of millions of sterile
Medflies later this month so that the wild Medflies that survived
the spraying will, in effect, breed themselves out of existence.
   Although agricultural production in the urbanized area is
slight, officials termed the infestation serious, saying it would
threaten the state's $15.5 billion-a-year farm economy if allowed
to spread.
   Along with parts of Beverly Hills, the helicopters sprayed
sections of west Los Angeles and the adjacent municipalities of
Culver City and West Hollywood.
   About 100,000 people live in the sprayed area, which includes
middle-class homes and apartments, multimillion-dollar mansions,
swank shops and luxury car dealerships.
   For much of the day, Ms. Curry said, worried residents flooded
hot lines set up by agriculture officials with questions about the
spraying.
   At Paulee Body Shop, president Ken Fleiner assigned four
employees to cover more than 180 mostly high-priced automobiles
parked outdoors. Fleiner said he spent about $500 on plastic and
$200 on masking tape for the job, which took hours.
   At Martin Cadillac in West Los Angeles, a caravan of about 100
shiny Caddies left the sales lot Wednesday night for an underground
parking lot at a bank building six blocks away, sales manager Steve
Mitchell said Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
