<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru a0479 10-07 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diplomats Say Burma is Pariah</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with diplomats saying Burma's
government snubbed by other nations; picks up 3rd graf pvs `Thakin
Soe...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign nations are shunning Burma's
three-week-old military government that has cracked down on a
popular uprising for democracy, diplomats said today.
   The main official contacts have involved notes from several
foreign embassies decrying the bloodshed since Gen. Saw Maung
seized power in a coup.
   The diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said no
nation has sent the standard message of congratulations to the new
leader, which would signify recognition of his government.
Diplomats also said Saw Maung, who also serves as the new foreign
minister, has met no heads of foreign missions.
   Ambassadors of the European Community and Japan last month
presented protest notes citing the killing of unarmed civilians by
troops. Other countries, including the United States, have
expressed concern from their capitals.
   Meanwhile, state radio reported Thursday that two more
opposition groups have registered with the government, bringing to
seven the number of opposition parties that have surfaced since Saw
Maung seized power.
   The newest parties to register with the election commission were
the Unity and Development Party, led by former communist rebel
Thakin Soe, and the Anti-Fascist People's Freedom League, headed by
onetime member of parliament Bo Kya Nyunt.
   Thakin Soe, 80, once led the Red Flag communist rebels who
followed a radical, Trotskyite program but were defeated by the
Burmese military in the 1960s. The People's Democratic Party, which
registered earlier, also is headed by a former communist figure.
   The new military government, which seized power in Sept. 18,
crushed pro-democracy demonstrations but announced that multi-party
elections would be held in about three months.
   Although seven parties have registered with the commission, none
have stated clearly whether they would take part in the elections,
which also will be contested by the government's National Unity
Party.
   Diplomats and other analysts are skeptical that fair elections
can be held given a hardline government that has been willing to
shoot thousands of unarmed demonstrators to stay in power.
   By official count, about 440 people have been killed since the
military coup. Western diplomats here believe the death toll is
much higher.
   Other anti-government groups are the Democracy Party, the
People's Youth Federation, the All Burma United Youths Organization
and the National League for Democracy.
   The patron of an eighth anti-government group _ the League for
Democracy _ is Nu, the former prime minister overthrown by
strongman Ne Win in 1962.
   Western diplomats say they are convinced the National Unity
Party is fully supported by Saw Maung and his military government,
but that the new leaders want their actions to appear legal so as
to subdue strong anti-government feelings among the public.
   Since last fall, Burma has been wracked by bloody protests and a
deteriorating economy. Demonstrators have called for the end of
authoritarian rule and a liberalized economy to pull one of Asia's
most resource-rich nations out of poverty.
   Japan, West Germany and the United States have temporarily
frozen aid to Burma but have refrained from direct interference in
the domestic turmoil.
   In Tokyo, the Foreign Ministry announced today Japan would
provide Burma with $450,000 in emergency food aid through UNICEF
because of serious shortages.
   But Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno stressed at a news conference
that ``This doesn't mean we approve of Saw Maung's military
government.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
