<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthKorea-Protest     10-07 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Protest,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Clash With Riot Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students calling for the
overthrow of President Roh Tae-woo hurled hundreds of firebombs and
rocks at riot police today during a violent demonstration at a
Seoul college.
   In another demonstration in the southern city of Kwangju, about
300 students clashed with riot troopers and 12 troopers were
injured, the Yonhap news agency reported.
   Police reported no arrests or serious injuries during the
90-minute clash in Seoul, the largest in the capital in recent
weeks.
   Some 2,000 students from about 30 colleges took part in the
rally on the outskirts of southern Seoul to denounce the Roh
administration and call for the expulsion of U.S. forces based in
South Korea.
   ``Down with the fascist regime which suppresses the masses,''
the students chanted. ``Yankee go home.''
   The leaders charged that the Roh administration was a front for
military rule and insisted there had been no democratic reforms in
South Korea.
   Roh, a former general who won presidential elections in
December, has helped introduce broad democratic reforms since
taking power. He has pledged to end authoritarian rule and make
South Korea a full democracy.
   The students marched out of the school and clashed on the
highway outside with hundreds of riot police. Police armored vans
with multiple tear gas launchers fired barrages of tear gas
canisters.
   The two-hour riot in Kwangju took place at the Chonam
University, Yonhap reported. The South Korean agency said the 12
troopers were injured by firebombs and rocks.
   The radicals have virtually no public support and their
following on campuses has dwindled sharply in recent months. They
staged a few protests during the Olympic Games which ended Sunday,
but generally were quiet.
</TEXT>
