<DOCNO> AP881007-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0710EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-TreasureHunt     10-07 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Treasure Hunt,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Aquino Inspects Scandal-Tainted Dig</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino visited one
of the country's most historic shrines today to decide whether to
allow an American firm continue a controversial treasure hunt there.
   Mrs. Aquino told reporters she was ``very pleased'' with the
restoration of chambers unearthed by nearly a year of digging at
Fort Santiago, a 16th Century Spanish fortress used by Japanese
troops as a concentration camp for American and Filipino prisoners
during World War II.
   She added that she and her staff need more time to determine
whether to renew for a third time the digging permit given the firm
International Precious Metals, Inc. of Las Vegas, Nev.
   The firm's head, Charles McDougal, and Emanuel Soriano, Mrs.
Aquino's chief security adviser, insist that tons of gold bullion
are buried beneath the fort. They claim core drillings have yielded
gold particles.
   The digging has been dogged by controversy since shortly after
it began secretly in November. The treasure hunt became public in
February when two Filipino workers were killed in a cave-in.
   Last month, the government's anti-graft prosecutor accused
Soriano of accepting payments from the company. Soriano admitted he
deposited a total $110,000 of company funds in his personal bank
account but claimed it was simply entrusted to him pending a
company reorganization.
   Soriano said the funds included $40,000 as a guarantee against
damages to the fort, built by Spanish colonialists at the mouth of
the Pasig River to defend the city.
   Fort Santiago served as prison to Jose Rizal, the Philippines's
national hero who was executed in 1896, and was converted into a
concentration camp and torture center by Japanese soldiers during
World War II.
   Soriano and McDougal told Mrs. Aquino they had maps and at least
two witnesses who have showed them the places where the Japanese
imperial army officers buried tons of gold, silver, diamonds and
other treasures plundered by the Japanese from all over Southeast
Asia.
   Asked by reporters if she was going to renew the permit to dig,
which expired on Sept. 1, Mrs. Aquino replied she was more
interested in the restoration work on the newly unearthed portions
of the fort.
   ``We have not given any extension of the permit yet,'' she
added. ``We are still evaluating all of the different reports that
we have been getting ... so that we can evaluate later on whether
we will grant an extension or not.''
</TEXT>
