<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ShipCollision 1stLd-Writethru a0491 10-07 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ship Collision, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0491,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Ship Collides with South Korean Vessel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with additional details; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese cargo ship sank after it collided with a
South Korean container vessel during a typhoon today, killing the
captain of the cargo vessel, a coast guard official said. Another
person was reported missing.
   Three crew members of the 199-ton Japanese Kannon-maru were
thrown into the sea when their ship collided with the 4,252-ton
South Korean Aurora in Ise Bay about 170 miles southwest of Tokyo,
the official said on condition of anonymity.
   Two of the crewmen were pulled from the sea, but Capt. Tatsuo
Nishibe died in a hospital after he was rescued. Patrol boats and a
helicopter were looking for a missing Japanese crewman, Itaru Chaya.
   Hiromi Hamada, vice captain of the Japanese ship, was injured in
the collision, the official added. No injuries were reported among
the 20 Aurora crew members.
   The Kannon-maru, carrying scrap iron, was heading west and the
Aurora was moving south when they collided in rough seas, the coast
guard official said. But he said visibility was mostly clear at the
time.
   The South Korean cargo vessel, which was damaged on the right
bow, was escorted into Toba port.
</TEXT>
