<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-EditorialReax     10-07 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Editorial Reax,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Editorial Reactions on Bentsen-Quayle Debate</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Following is a roundup of editorial reaction to the vice
presidential debate from newspapers around the country:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>St. Louis Post-Dispatch</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Sen. Lloyd Bentsen accomplished three tasks with the most
memorable line of Wednesday night's vice-presidential debate, when
he told J. Danforth Quayle, `Senator, you're no Jack Kennedy.' With
that remark, he helped establish himself as by far the better of
the two candidates _ and in a close presidential election, he may
have given many Reagan Democrats as good a reason as they need to
come back to the fold next month.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``If (Quayle) had only one decent answer to the question he
faced at least three times _ the one about what he would do if a
tragedy thrust him into the presidency _ we would have been more
reassured. But obviously he either hadn't anticipated the question
or didn't want to answer it. ...
   ``He would say a prayer for himself and the country. Good. He
would call together the Cabinet. Good. But then what? Sen. Quayle
prefered to talk about his qualifications rather than give us a
clue that he had a thoughtful plan in mind.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Star Tribune (Minneapolis)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The `debate' seemed to confirm the awfulness of George Bush's
decision to choose Dan Quayle as running mate. Michael Dukakis'
choice looked better; (Lloyd) Bentsen was more polished, more
experienced, more adept at ripostes like his now-famous slashing of
Quayle's self-comparison with John Kennedy. But the erratic
proceedings Wednesday night offered little basis for solid
comparison. It was an opportunity wasted.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>The Atlanta Constitution</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Nothing in Mr. Quayle's performance provided reassurance that
he is ready to stand on the verge of the presidency or that Mr.
Bush acted with then-unrecognized wisdom in selecting him. ...
   ``Mr. Bentsen _ no surprise _ was the cooler, cannier head, in
part simply because of his greater experience.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Arkansas Gazette (Little Rock)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Quayle, in our view, was mechanical in his responses to the
panel's questions, reverting on several occasions to the same
phraseology about his qualifications regardless of the question
asked _ a reflection of briefings and rehearsals. ...
   ``Bentsen presented a mature and thoughtful figure, drawing a
sharp contrast with Quayle on relative leadership qualities and
experience. Relative ages may have been a factor, perhaps depending
upon the viewer's generation, but Bentsen's broader experience
clearly testified to his benefit.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Charleston (W.Va.) Gazette</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Wednesday's vice presidential debate won't be remembered for
exchanges about Social Security, farm subsidies or foreign policy.
   ``The debate turned on one question: is J. Danforth Quayle III
qualified to be president should anything happen to George Bush?
Three times, Indiana's junior senator was asked how he would handle
such a crisis. Three times, he faltered.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Dallas Times Herald:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Sen. Quayle stood up fairly well to some tough, maybe even
unfair questioning. He did not fall on his face, as some pundits
had expected, but he never gave a satisfactory answer to three
questions about what he would do first if he became president. But
at the same time, Sen. Bentsen proved that he not only is a
knowledgeable, articulate officeholder who has a solid record of
achievement, but that he can be awfully tough in the clutch.''
</TEXT>
