<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MonroeLetter     10-07 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Monroe Letter,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Threatened if Monroe Letter Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of acting teacher Lee Strasberg
threatened to sue if a love letter from Marilyn Monroe to Monroe's
one-time husband Joe DiMaggio is sold at auction.
   The letter, written a few weeks before Monroe's death, surfaced
last week and is now at the Swann Gallery here, where it is
scheduled to be auctioned on Oct. 25.
   But Anna Strasberg claims she is entitled to the letter, arguing
that all personal items Monroe left were willed to her husband,
Lee, of whose estate she is executor, the Daily News reported in
today's editions.
   The letter, originally discovered by a housekeeper in a desk in
Monroe's home the day after she was found dead on Aug. 5, 1962,
reads:
   ``Dear Joe, If I can succeed in making you happy, I will have
succeeded in the biggest and most difficult thing there is, that is
to make one person completely happy. Your happiness means my
happiness.''
   George Lowery of the Swann Gallery said the letter, which is
signed NJ for Norma Jean _ Monroe's real name, carries a minimum
asking price of $10,000.
   Strasberg, an Austrian-born theatrical director, established the
Lee Strasberg Institute of Theater in New York and Los Angeles. He
died in 1982.
</TEXT>
