<2ND_LINE>PM-Koch-Uniforms,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koch Plans for Uniforms in a School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saying it might improve discipline in the city's
public schools, Mayor Edward I. Koch has arranged for a clothing
manufacturer to donate student uniforms as a tryout.
   Koch said he wants to try putting public school students in
uniforms ``comparable to the dress codes in parochial or private
schools with the thought that it might help in the learning process
to have that kind of discipline.''
   The mayor said Thursday that he has asked schools Chancellor
Richard R. Green to pick a school of about 400 students and send
their measurements to the manufacturer, who was not identified.
   An aide to Green said the chancellor would try to locate an
elementary school where the principal and parents would be willing
to participate.
   Robert Wagner Jr., president of the Board of Education,
expressed skepticism at the suggestion, but said he was willing to
give it a try.
   The mayor disclosed the plan at a park restoration project in
Queens.
   ``I don't tell you that just jackets and skirts and pants that
match the jackets is a solution to our education problem, but I
believe that there are lots of things that have to be done,'' he
said.
