<DOCNO> AP881007-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0815EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RadonHome     10-07 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Radon Home,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Radon Levels In Clinton Home Are Highest Ever Found</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLINTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests on a home that had radon
levels about 800 times higher than the federal safety standard have
failed to convince some neighbors that the colorless, odorless gas
could kill them, officials said.
   The test last week on an unidentified home may be the highest
radon levels ever measured in a structure.
   ``We believe it's the highest that anyone's ever found,'' said
Christopher Daggett, acting commissioner of the Department of
Environmental Protection.
   Officials said that 59 of the 74 other nearby homes in the rural
community about 40 miles west of New York City also showed unsafe
radon levels.
   Many homes that have registered high radon readings sit above
the Reading Prong, a belt of uranium that stretches from
Pennsylvania across northeastern New Jersey into New York.
   The federal standard for structures is 4 picocuries, a unit of
measurement for radioactivity.
   Federal officials say exposure to high levels of the naturally
occurring gas may cause up to 20,000 lung cancer deaths a year _
essentially all those not caused from smoking.
   John Van Nuys, an investigator for the Hunterdon County Health
Department, spent the weekend knocking on doors in the sprawling
development, urging residents to place charcoal-filled canisters in
their basements for testing.
   He said he met with some distrustful and suspicious residents _
and several slammed doors.
   Some were only convinced of the urgency because it was important
enough to get a government employee working on a Saturday.
   When a sampling of residents were told Thursday of the state's
findings, some said they didn't know much about radon, some said
they didn't care much, and some said they didn't care to talk about
the levels found in their homes.
   Others said they have had their homes tested or are awaiting
test results.
   Officials said that although a radon test only costs about $10,
and a high level is easily cured with a ventilation system for
about $1,200, apathy is the biggest challenge in fighting the
health problem.
   They also say that many residents may ignore warnings because
they have grown immune to the constant stream of warnings about
environmental problems.
   The announcement about the Clinton Township home comes about two
years after state officials discovered 105 houses with elevated
radon levels in a nearby development.
   Daggett said the barrage of testing here began after a homeowner
did a routine radon test and found a reading of about 200
picocuries. The department confirmed the results and began testing
other homes.
   Daggett said the home with the highest reading registered more
than 3,000 picocuries.
   The federal safety standard of 4 picocuries is the equivalent of
smoking one-half pack of cigarettes a day, or having 200 to 300
chest X-rays per year. It also is the concentration that would
increase the chance of getting lung cancer by 1 percent for a
lifetime resident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
