<DOCNO> AP881007-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0823EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-Transplants     10-07 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Transplants,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Reports First Case Of AIDS From Transplant _ An '84 Bone
Operation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS-Heterosexuals, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal health officials have reported the first
case of AIDS acquired from a transplant operation, but researchers
stressed that the operation was four years ago _ before the advent
of AIDS testing.
   Transplant patients have previously been infected with the virus
that causes AIDS, but Thursday's report from the U.S. Centers for
Disease Control marked the first time AIDS virus has been
associated with a bone transplant, and the first case ever reported
in which any kind of transplant has resulted in AIDS itself.
   ``This is consistent with how we have found the virus to be
transmitted previously _ in blood, bodily fluids and body parts
from another individual. ... It's an expected mode of
transmission,'' said Dr. John Ward, an AIDS specialist with the
Atlanta-based CDC.
   Ward noted that the surgery in question took place before the
advent of antibody testing for AIDS; the donor was an intravenous
drug user infected with AIDS.
   ``It's important for the lay public to understand that this case
occurred in 1984. ... The donor could not be screened,'' he said.
   Since then, AIDS tests have become available, and the Public
Health Service has recommended that all donors of tissue or organs
be tested for AIDS infection.
   This first AIDS-transplant case occurred in a woman with
progressive spinal disease who, in November 1984, underwent a
spinal fusion using bone from her hospital's bone bank. In February
1988, she was diagnosed with AIDS. She was a health care worker,
but there were no indications she had contracted an AIDS infection
on the job, the CDC reported.
   The donor from whom the bone came, a 52-year-old man who had
undergone a partial hip bone removal, turned out to be an
intravenous drug user, and thus at high risk for AIDS. He was
diagnosed with AIDS less than two years after the woman's surgery
and died in 1987.
   The Public Health Service, the CDC's parent agency, recommended
Thursday that living donors of bone be tested for AIDS at the time
the bone is removed, and then again 90 days later to ensure that
any AIDS infection is detected.
   More than 74,000 AIDS cases have been reported in the United
States, with more than 42,000 deaths so far, according to the CDC.
   Some 24 cases of AIDS virus transmission through transplants
have been reported worldwide, in cases such as kidney, liver and
heart transplants, Ward said. None of those patients has been
diagnosed with AIDS itself, but ``undoubtedly, some will develop
AIDS in the future,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881007-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0842EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Williams     10-07 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Williams,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robin Williams Files Suit Against Ex-Lover</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Robin Williams says an ex-lover
who claims he gave her herpes has used ``duress, coercion and
fraud'' since 1985 in an effort to extort money from him.
   Williams filed a complaint in San Francisco Superior Court
Thursday against Michelle Tish Carter of Los Angeles.
   In 1986, Carter filed a $6 million suit against Williams in
Stanislaus County that has since been moved to San Francisco.
   The comedian's suit contends that in November 1985 Carter told
Williams she had contracted herpes, a sexually transmitted disease.
Two medical tests proved negative, the suit said.
   Williams tried to break off the relationship but Carter
``claimed she was pregnant by Williams and demanded $20,000 and a
new car,'' the complaint charged.
   The suit charged Carter with extortion, conspiracy and
intentional infliction of emotional distress. It seeks an
unspecified amount in damages.
   ``Carter intentionally and with extraordinary malice, made these
representations to Williams, threatening damage to his public
persona and damage to his family life in order to extort money and
property from him,'' the suit said.
   Carter's attorney, Adolph B. Canelo, was out of the country and
could not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
