<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reagan-Politics Hold-For-ReleaseLd-Write</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Politics, Hold-For-Release Ld-Writethru, a0456,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at Noon EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>With Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Preaches GOP Gospel in Key Battleground State</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout. For Release at Noon, not 1:05 p.m. EDT, as
indicated in eds note of setup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, campaigning for George Bush in
a key campaign battleground state, told Michigan high school
students today that this year's election is ``a referendum on
liberalism in America.''
   In a speech prepared for students and citizens of suburban
Sterling Heights, Reagan urged every eligible voter to take part in
the Nov. 8 election.
   ``Michigan has voted twice for what we stand for,'' he said.
``But the liberals are now saying that, come January, they will
wipe away all that we have beeen working for.''
   ``From top to bottom, the election this year is a referendum on
liberalism,'' said Reagan, who is Republican presidential candidate
George Bush's best-known campaign surrogate.
   ``Will not only the White House but the Congress and the state
legislatures be filled with people whose only Pledge of Allegiance
is to more government spending?'' he asked.
   Reagan flew to Detroit to hammer away at the GOP theme of
``peace and prosperity'' at a school named for the late Adlai
Stevenson, a prominent Democrat and two-time presidential campaign
loser.
   The trip was part of a series Reagan is making as he seeks to
lure ``Reagan Democrats'' and independent voters to Bush's side in
the vice president's race against Massachusetts Democrat Michael
Dukakis.
   It also was a homecoming of sorts, since it was in Detroit's Joe
Louis Arena that Reagan in July 1980 accepted his party's
nomination for the first time to be its presidential candidate _
and chose Bush to be his running mate.
   Most experts rate Michigan a tossup between Bush and Dukakis.
Reagan felt so strongly about carrying the state during his
re-election campaign in 1984 that he appeared twice in the last
week of the campaign. The president's last appearance in Michigan
was in September 1986, when he campaigned for Bill Lucas, a
Republican who failed in his bid to become governor of Michigan.
   Reagan also was speaking at a luncheon hosted by the Michigan
State Chamber of Commerce and the Michigan chapter of the National
Federation of Independent Business in the northeastern Detroit
suburb of Macomb County.
   His appearance there comes just a week after Bush's visit to
Macomb Community College. Political experts in Michigan say both
stops are part of an organized effort to win over that area's
blue-collar Democrats who crossed party lines to support the
president in 1980 and 1984.
   Reagan in recent weeks has been fond of telling campaign
audiences that Democrats abandoned the so-called ``misery index''
when that party found that inflation and interest rates had
declined during his administration.
   While Reagan seeks to help Bush broaden his electoral appeal to
conservative Democrats and people who do not describe themselves as
either Democrats or Republicans, the president has been raising
millions of dollars for state GOP campaign coffers.
   Reagan was sure to repeat this act with tonight's appearance at
a $1,000-a-plate fund-raiser for the state party and in honor of
Max Fisher, a prominent Detroit-area GOP supporter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
