<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Elections 1stLd-Writethru a0468 10-07 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Likud, Labor Tie In Two Polls; Exchange Barbs In Televised Ads</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with polls released, details, appeal
by rightist party to participate in elections; No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two public opinion polls published today showed
a tie between the dovish Labor Party and the hard-line Likud bloc,
and the two rivals swapped accusations in a series of television
advertisements.
   Results of those questioned in the two polls showed Labor and
Likud would win 42 seats each in the 120-member parliament if the
Nov. 1 election were held today. The results were published in the
Yediot Ahronot newspaper.
   The 1984 elections ended in a stalemate with neither of the
major political blocs able to form a coalition. The result was
shared rule in a national unity government with Labor leader Shimon
Peres and Likud leader Yitzhak Shamir each serving two years as
premier.
   The Likud-sponsored Dahaf poll predicted Likud and its
right-wing allies would win 60 seats in the Knesset, while Labor
and the left secured an equal number.
   The Labor-sponsored Decima poll said Labor and the leftist lists
would gain a narrow majority of 61 seats.
   The Dahaf poll questioned 662 voters, and the Decima poll
encompassed 1,000 voters. The paper did not disclose the margin of
error given, and the offices of both pollsters were closed for the
Jewish Sabbath.
   Also today, American-born Rabbi Meir Kahane appealed to Israel's
Supreme Court requesting it overturn a Central Elections Committee
decision to disqualify his anti-Arab party from running in the
elections.
   The parliamentary committee barred Kahane's Kach Party from
participating in the elections, saying its platform calling for all
Arabs to be expelled from Israel is racist. A new law bars racist
parties from running for government.
   In a third day of televised ads that will continue nightly until
the Nov. 1 vote, the barbed repartee between Labor and Likud came
as close to a televised debate as the campaign has seen so far.
   ``No one in this country is against peace,'' said Benyamin
Netanyahu, the former U.N. ambassador and a rising star in Likud.
``But what Labor wants is peace through retreat (from the occupied
territories).''
   He was referring to Peres' willingness to talk peace with the
Palestinians, even though Labor refuses to negotiate with the
banned Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Immediately after the Likud segment ended, Labor's Nissim Zvili
appeared on the screen.
   ``So, you're scared, huh? They scared the heck out of us, didn't
they,'' Zvili said. ``That's the Likud system: frightening people,
making personal attacks, and frightening again.''
   Labor has outlined the ``generals' peace plan'' it is pushing,
so-called because it was developed with the help of high-ranking
officers in Israel's reserve army.
   The plan calls for withdrawing from certain undefined areas of
the occupied territories, but demanding those territories remain
demilitarized in order to guarantee safe borders.
   Israel expanded its borders in the 1967 Middle East war when it
captured the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from Egypt.
   Shamir has pledged never to return to the pre-1967 borders.
   The nearly 10-month-old Palestinian revolt against Israeli rule
is the top issue in the tight election campaign.
   More than 280 Arabs and six Israelis have been killed in the
violence, which erupted Dec. 8.
   Both parties oppose creation of an independent Palestinian state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
