<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Baltics     10-07 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Baltics,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lithuania Agrees to Activists' Demands on Flag, Language</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of public protests, the Lithuanian
legislature has agreed to make Lithuanian the Baltic republic's
official language and to permit display of religious symbols, an
activist reported today.
   The decision prompted an estimated 100,000 Lithuanians, mostly
Roman Catholics, to gather in their capital, Vilnius, this morning
to celebrate with nationalist songs, flag-waving and dancing, said
activist Vytautas Bogusis.
   Also today, Tass, the official Soviet news agency, reported that
the legislature of Latvia, another Baltic republic, was drafting a
bill to make Latvian the republic's official language.
   Similar measures were adopted earlier in the third Baltic
republic, Estonia, in response to a campaign by nationalists.
   Bogusis, a member of the Lithuanian Freedom League, a group
demanding an end to Soviet control over their republic, said local
newspapers today reprinted decrees of the Presidium, or executive
committee of the legislature. One measure allows display of
religious symbols, and another designates Lithuanian the republic's
official language.
   Many Baltic activists complain that top officials in their
republics do not know the indigenous languages and that Russian and
other tongues are contaminating their language.
   Tass also reported adoption of Lithuanian as the official
language and said Lithuanian flags could now be displayed at
gatherings, sporting events, song and dance festivals.
   The dispatch did not say whether the flag was the one that flew
in Lithuania before it was incorporated into the Soviet Union, or
whether it was the flag of Soviet Lithuania.
   Lithuanians in Moscow said they believed the order applies to
the independence flag, which had been banned.
   The Soviet Union took over Estonia, Lithuania and Latvia in 1940
under a secret pact with Germany. Activists are demanding that the
Soviet Union renounce the pact.
   Bogusis said activists raised the yellow, green and red
independence flag today atop Gediminas Tower on the square where
the demonstration took place.
   Many people singing the nationalist songs and dancing also
carried the flag, he said. Police, who earlier would have torn down
the flag and arrested nationalist demonstrators, did not interfere,
Bogusis said.
</TEXT>
