<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0953EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Waite 1stLd-Writethru a0513 10-07 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Waite, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0513,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports: Waite Will be Released Soon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with magazine also reporting Waite
to be freed, U.S. hostages released before election, other details.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terry Waite, the Anglican church envoy
who has been missing in Lebanon for more than 20 months, will be
freed soon, two Beirut publications reported today.
   One of the publications, the weekly magazine Ash-Shiraa, also
said American hostages will be released before the U.S.
presidential election on Nov. 8.
   Both Ash-Shiraa and the conservative daily Al-Anwar cited
unidentified informed sources for its report. There was no way to
confirm that Waite's release was imminent.
   Al-Anwar said one of its sources reported that Waite ``has been
moved from the Bekaa (valley) to Beirut's southern suburbs and
predicted he will be released in 72 hours.''
   But the newspaper said another source claimed Waite, 48, will be
freed after resumption of British-Syrian relations.
   Ash-Shiraa, based in Moslem west Beirut, said Waite and two
other British hostages will be released ``very soon.''
   The magazine said a recent decision for the restoration of full
diplomatic relations between Britain and Iran ``provided a strong
impetus to efforts currently underway for the release of Waite and
his countrymen.''
   Ash-Shiraa also quoted an unidentified informed security source
as saying Monday's release of hostage Mithileshwar Singh, an Indian
national and legal resident alien of the United States, marked
``the beginning of the release of ... American hostages.''
   ``The source said American hostages would be released before the
U.S. presidential election,'' the report added, without further
elaboration.
   Ash-Shiraa gained fame when it broke the story of secret U.S.
arms sales to Iran in November 1986. But its recent reports on the
hostages have not been accurate. Al-Anwar also has no record of
authoritative reports on the hostages.
   Singh was held by a pro-Iranian underground group calling itself
Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of Palestine. He was kidnapped
Jan. 24, 1987 from the U.S.-affiliated Beirut University College
along with American educators Alann Steen, Robert Polhill and Jesse
Turner.
   London severed diplomatic relations with Damascus in November
1986, after accusing the Syrian government of involvement in a plot
to blow up an Israeli airliner at Heathrow airport. Syria denied
the charge.
   Syria, a strong ally of Iran, has said it was working for the
release of all hostages in Lebanon. Most of captives are held by
Shiite Moslem followers of Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Syria also is the main powerbroker in Lebanon. It has an
estimated 40,000 troops in eastern and norther provinces as well as
west and south Beirut.
   The fundamentalists who are believed to hold the foreign
captives are entrenched in areas under Syrian control.
   Waite disappeared Jan. 20, 1987, after leaving his west Beirut
hotel for a rendezvous with Islamic Jihad, or Holy War, which holds
American hostages Terry Anderson, 40, and Thomas Sutherland, 56.
   Anderson, of Lorain, Ohio, chief Middle East correspondent of
The Associated Press, is the longest-held captive. He was kidnapped
March 16, 1985.
   In all 16 foreigners are missing in Lebanon, including nine
Americans.
   Britain seeks the release of three of its nationals held by
pro-Iranian Islamic fundamentalists _ Waite, journalist John
McCarthy and teacher Brian Keenan, a Belfast man with dual British
and Irish nationality whose release is also sought by the Irish
government.
   The Foreign Office says it also seeks word on Alec Collett, a
New York-based British journalist whose Palestinian abductors have
claimed they killed him. His body was never found.
</TEXT>
