<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Chile 2ndLd-Writethru   10-07 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0453,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Rejects Calls To Resign Early</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 16 grafs to UPDATE casualty report, ADDS
background. Pickup 12th graf pvs, ``The constitution...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet rejected demands
that he resign as president before his term expires in 1990 and
said the military will continue to play a key role in Chile's
future.
   The 72-year-old ruler spoke to the nation after police armed
with clubs fired water cannons and tear gas at crowds who swarmed
the streets Thursday to celebrate Pinochet's defeat in a national
referendum.
   Police said today that two people were killed in the
demonstrations, including a 14-year-old boy shot by unidentified
attackers and a 31-year-old robber shot by police.
   Unknown assailants shot two other people, who were in serious
condition today, police said. Eight officers were injured, one
seriously, and 58 demonstrators were detained and later released,
police said.
   The capital was calm this morning after street scuffles between
roving bands of youths and police in jeeps and water trucks lasted
until midnight.
   In his first public statement since the Wednesday ballot, which
he lost by a margin of more than 11 percent, Pinochet declared
Thursday night: ``I recognize and accept the majority verdict
expressed yesterday by the citizenry.''
   According to the terms of an 8-year-old constitution, Pinochet
remains in power until March 1990, when he will be succeeded by the
winner of open elections planned for late next year.
   Pinohet is not barred from running in the election. He has not
indicated whether he plans to run.
   Reading from a text, the 72-year-old Pinochet warned the
opposition that its plans to amend the existing constitution to
speed up his departure would be in vain.
   ``No one can feel they have the mandate of the people to twist
what the people decided,'' he said, in reference to the
constitution, which was approved by voters in 1980 in a loosely
staged vote that critics complain was rife with fraud.
   Wednesday's vote was well-organized, massively attended and free
of charges of fraud or violence. Pinochet expressed ``the deep
pride I feel at the civic maturity with which each one of you faced
this act of singular importance.''
   Pinochet was dressed in his white dress general's uniform for
the taped speech, broadcast nationwide on all television and radio
stations.
   Triumphant opposition leaders Thursday vowed to press their
demands for Pinochet to allow quick elections and step down soon.
Pinochet seized power in the 1973 coup that toppled elected
President Salvador Allende, a Marxist.
   ``An authoritarian system has been overthrown,'' said Socialist
Ricardo Lagos, a director of a 16-party coalition that led the
campaign for Pinochet's defeat. ``It is indispensable now to elect,
within a short period of time, a president and a congress with
powers to modify the constitution.''
   But the opposition faces the challenge of maintaining its unity.
Potentially divisive issues such as human rights trials and the
future of the Communist Party could sow dissent while opposition
leaders negotiate with the armed forces to speed the transition to
full democracy.
   Political maneuvering by top opposition figures for nomination
to the presidency also is expected to influence relations among the
parties in the coalition.
   The constitution, drawn up by the Pinochet administration, calls
for electing a congress in a year. But its provisions leave the
legislature virtually powerless to pass amendments. It also gives
the armed forces autonomy and an influential role in national
policy-making.
   Pinochet, leader of the army, said the military ``will be the
guide in building the future Chile.''
   Early Thursday, small groups of government opponents descended
on downtown to celebrate the referendum result. They were quickly
joined by tens of thousands of others, mostly youths, who virtually
took control of many streets and some avenues in the city's center,
marching and chanting ``Pinochet, go away'' and ``He has fallen.''
   Police only occasionally broke up the early demonstrations, but
the protesters later became more strident and police began using
more force. When the demonstrators began throwing rocks, bottles
and sticks at officers, riot-control squads responded with water
cannons and tear gas in running street battles.
</TEXT>
