<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Hostages 2ndLd-Writethru a0518 10-07 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Hostages, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0518,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Newspaper Reports Deal for Hostages</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs on White House denial of sty, other
details. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``The report...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli newspaper reported today that the
United States struck a deal with Iran to free U.S. hostages in
Lebanon, including the supply of arms and spare parts to Tehran
through South Korea.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater called the
report ``not true.''
   The unattributed report in The Nation, an English-language
weekly that began publishing last month, said the U.S. government
agreed to pay $7 million in ransom to the Lebanese Shiite Moslem
extremists holding most of the hostages but refused the group's
demands for immunity from prosecution.
   The United States has denied reports it is involved in
negotiations with Iran over the release of hostages.
   Fitzwater today said he consulted with the national security
adviser, Colin Powell, about the story, and Powell said there were
no such weapons transfers.
   ``There are a lot of free-lancers, independent operators in the
region,'' the spokesman said. But he reiterated administration
statements that none of these independent parties is authorized to
speak for the U.S. government.
   The report in The Nation said the U.S. refusal to guarantee
immunity from prosecution angered the kidnappers and prompted them
to release Indian hostage Mithileshwar Singh on Monday instead of
Alann Steen, a U.S. citizen whose release had been expected.
   According to The Nation, among the steps taken to secure the
release of a foreign hostage was an agreement by South Korea to
sell millions of dollars in spare parts for U.S.-made weapons.
   The newspaper said that two weeks before the release of Singh,
who is a permanent U.S. resident, South Korean Oil Minister Lee
Bong signed an agreement in Tehran to sell the spare parts,
including those needed for the U.S.-made F-5 aircraft used in the
Iranian air force.
   The Reagan administration would have had to approve such a sale
under the standard agreement signed by countries licensed to
manufacture U.S-designed weapons, the newspaper said.
   Today's report also said U.S. citizens who hold Iranian and
Lebanese passports visited two of the hostages in January,
including Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press. Anderson, the longest held hostage, was kidnapped
March 16, 1985.
   Reporter Giora Shamis told The Associated Press the report in
The Nation was based on interviews with three of about 15 dual
passport holders involved in the contacts as well as South Korean
sources who confirmed an Iranian report about the spare parts deal.
   Shamis is an owner of the London-based news service, Depth,
which sold the story to The Nation.
   According to the report, Iran agreed to put up the $7 million
ransom for the hostages because the United States did not want to
appear to be directly purchasing their freedom.
   The newspaper said the money would be paid indirectly to the
kidnappers by Iran in the form of commissions for Iranian purchases
in the United States. These are to be channeled through Lebanese
and Iranian businessmen to Hezbollah, the radical Shiite group
believed to be holding hostages.
   Sixteen foreign hostages are believed held in Lebanon, including
nine Americans.
</TEXT>
