<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TownBequest     10-07 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Town Bequest,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sisters Leave $1 Million To Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOMERSET, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two frugal sisters who never took part in
municipal affairs and never let on how much money they had saved
have surprised the city by leaving it a $1 million trust fund.
   Frances and Elsie Hathaway had no immediate relatives to inherit
the money and wanted to do something special for the town, said
their cousin, Sidney Hathaway.
   Frances, 93, died in March, and Elsie, 94, died in February 1986.
   Hathaway described the women as a quiet, frugal, hard-working
pair who generally kept to themselves. Frances earned her money as
a stenographer and Elsie was a sales manager and worked in the
pharmaceutical industry for more than 50 years.
   ``They never left town, never got involved in local affairs,
never learned how to drive and never married,'' he said. ``They
would get off the Fall River streetcar just before the fare went up
and walk the last quarter-mile home to save a nickel.
   ``That nickel could buy a loaf of bread, they'd say.''
   The $1 million will be invested to provide income for local
educational and charitable pursuits. Roger Lamonde, vice president
of Durfee Attleboro Bank, said it could generate $75,000 a year in
interest.
   A three-member advisory board will recommend to the bank how the
interest should be spent, Lamonde said.
</TEXT>
