<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Soviets     10-07 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Soviets,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Inspect British Military Exercise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet military team said today it was generally
satisfied with its unprecedented snap inspection of a British
military exercise in southern England.
   The four Soviet inspectors scrutinized the 4,400-troop Drum's
Drake exercise for two hours today before departing for Moscow from
London's Heathrow Airport. The team leader, Col. Vladimir
Greshnikov, thanked the British army for its hospitality during
their two-day tour.
   ``The results of the inspection will have to be examined in more
detail, but I am sure they can be considered positive,'' Greshnikov
told a news conference at Heathrow, speaking through an interpreter.
   Greshnikov said his team _ including Anatoli Makhov, Yuri Leonov
and Vladimir Trofimov _ were ``generally satisfied'' with the tour,
adding that ``this kind of inspection will help to build confidence
measures in Europe.''
   The inspectors arrived Wednesday after giving Britain the
36-hour minimum notice for an inspection as required under the 1986
Stockholm Agreement for relaxing East-West tensions.
   They sought to assess the ``character and scale'' of Drake's
Drum, which Britain described as a defensive eight-day exercise to
test protection of airfields, ports and other installations.
   British army Brig. Gen. Mike Tennant, who joined Greshnikov at
the news conference, said the Soviets had seen ``a lot of nothing.''
   The Soviets spent a hectic two days in helicopters and Land
Rovers touring the 5,500-square-mile exercise area near Salisbury,
80 miles southwest of London.
   It was the first time the Soviet Union had called a snap
inspection in Britain under the 35-nation verification treaty,
though British inspectors have dropped in on Soviet maneuvers,
Royal Air Force Vice Marshal Mike Stear said.
   ``I am pleased that the inspection of each other's military
activities is becoming more commonplace, for familiarity does build
confidence and trust,'' Stear said.
   Under the Stockholm Agreement, each nation must tell the others
about major land maneuvers.
</TEXT>
