<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary-Romania     10-07 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Romania,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Foreign Minister Alleges Human-Rights Violations In
Romania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's foreign minister accused Warsaw
Pact ally Romania of violating the human rights of its Hungarian
minority and said Moscow was not taking sides in the dispute.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Peter Varkonyi
leveled the accusation against Romania by name, but in a speech
Tuesday to the U.N. General Assembly he decried ``cultural
oppression'' of minorities in ``neighboring countries.''
   ``It is clear that our problem in this regard is with Romania,''
Varkonyi told the AP Thursday.
   Hungary says Romania's Hungarian minority is being
systematically mistreated. Romania denies the accusation.
   Although both sides have publicly criticized each other numerous
times in recent months, Varkonyi's comments were unusually candid
criticism on a senior level of an ally within the Soviet bloc.
   The most recent tensions involve Romanian plans to raze up to
7,000 villages, including about 800 ethnic Hungarian communities.
   The Romanian leadership says it needs the land for development
and plans to resettle the villagers in agro-industrial centers.
Hungarian officials say, however, that the project will destroy
deep-seated traditions of the ethnic Hungarians, who became
Romanian citizens after World War II when Hungary was forced to
cede the territory to Romania.
   In the interview, Varkonyi acknowledged that the conflict was
figuring in Hungarian-Soviet discussions. But he said the Soviet
leadership would ``like us to solve the question'' directly with
Romania.
   A diplomat from a Soviet bloc country, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, suggested that Moscow was particularly reluctant to get
involved in the dispute because of its own problems with ethnic
unrest in Armenia and the Baltic republics.
   Romania denies its 1.7 million Hungarians are being mistreated
and accuses Budapest of interfering in its internal affairs.
   Attempts late Thursday for Romanian comment were unsucessful. No
one answered the telephone at Romania's U.N. mission.
   The resettlement plan touched off mass protests in Hungary,
including a demonstration in front of the Romanian Embassy in
Budapest. Police did not intervene in the protests.
   ``We are all concerned about a situation where an ethnic
minority is about to be stripped of its roots,'' said Varkonyi,
referring to the resettlement project.
   The foreign minister, who was interviewed in Hungarian, denied
that the criticism constituted interference in Romanian matters,
saying, ``We believe that the question of minority rights is not
strictly an internal affair.''
   Hungary has begun to accept refugees from Romania, the only
Soviet bloc country to give asylum to those fleeing from an allied
nation. Varkonyi said about 10,000 Romanian citizens have fled to
Hungary, most of them ethnic Hungarians.
   While there are no official figures on the number of ethnic
Romanians among the refugees, Hungarian officials estimate they
constitute between 10 percent to 15 percent of the total, most of
them fleeing economic hardships and political repression.
</TEXT>
