<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Polio     10-07 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Polio,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Starts Nationwide Polio Vaccination Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REHOVOT, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of parents lined up at clinics
to immunize their babies against polio today in the first stage of
Israel's nationwide campaign to vaccinate all residents under the
age of 40.
   The Health Ministry announced the campaign following an outbreak
of the disease that has affected at least nine people.
   About 3.2 million people will be vaccinated over the next four
weeks, according to ministry spokesman Shmuel Algrabli.
   The campaign does not include the Israeli-occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip. Algrabli said this is because Gaza residents have been
immunized with a highly effective combined Sabin-Salk vaccine. In
the West Bank, he said, officials are testing sewage to determine
whether to extend the campaign there.
   The first stage of the campaign will encompass the towns of
Rehovot near Tel Aviv and Acre in the north, where the polio virus
has been found in sewage.
   In Rehovot, large yellow posters plastered on the walls informed
residents when various age groups should report to clinics for
vaccinations.
   Meanwhile, the Tourism Ministry expressed concern that reports
of the outbreak would keep visitors away from Israel.
   Israel has already suffered a sharp drop in tourism this year as
a result of the 10-month-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied
territories.
   The immunization campaign was undertaken after health officials
received the recommendations of a team of international health
experts called to Israel after the first polio cases were
diagnosed, Algrabli said.
   No cases of polio were reported in Israel last year and only one
case was reported in 1986. The recent cases have been blamed on
overflowing sewage.
   Polio is an infectious disease that causes muscular paralysis.
</TEXT>
