<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusImpostor     10-07 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Impostor,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Accused Of Trying To Use Stolen Bus To Pick Up Load Of
Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORANGE PARK, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A transient drove a stolen church bus
to a public elementary school and tried to pick up a load of
children but was arrested after a teacher became suspicious, police
said.
   Lee Villarreal, 36, was charged with auto theft after Clay
County Sheriff's deputies arrested him Wednesday at Middleburg
Elementary School.
   Villarreal arrived at the school and tried to get in line with
other buses as children were preparing to board, Assistant
Principal Ed Clarkson said.
   A bus-duty teacher notified Clarkson when she became suspicious
because she didn't recognize the bus, said Twila Shrewsbury, the
school's principal.
   ``The assistant principal thought the driver was at the wrong
school and asked the man to come inside so he Clarkson could find
out where he the driver should be,'' Ms. Shrewsbury said.
   They called Calvary Baptist Church, which owns the bus, and
learned that the bus had been stolen. Police were called and
Villarreal was arrested.
   Authorities had no motive in the case. Villarreal was in the
county jail today on $35,002 bond.
</TEXT>
