<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0444 10-07 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,840</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with Bush on crime; pick up 6th graf pvs
bgng ``You're going...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>XENIA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush today cited crime as
the issue on which he is most at odds with Michael Dukakis, saying
his Democratic rival has ``an astounding lack of sensitivity'' to
crime victims.
   Bush said Dukakis had presided over a criminal justice system in
Massachusetts that is ``completely out of whack: a `Twilight Zone'
world where prisoners' right to privacy had more weight than the
citizen's right to safety.''
   Bush, in remarks prepared for delivery to law enforcement
officials, said Dukakis ``still clings to a discredited liberal
idology that blinds him to the true causes of crime.''
   Bush said Dukakis only amended his state's prison furlough law
this year ``under the bright spotlight of the national presidential
campaign.'' Last spring, Dukakis ended furloughs for convicted
murderers serving life without parole.
   Bush said Dukakis should have apologized to a Maryland couple
savagely attacked by convicted murderer Willie Horton, who had been
granted a weekend Massachusetts furlough in 1986. The couple, Cliff
and Angi Barnes, have agreed to tape radio ads on behalf of Bush's
campaign.
   ``As far as I know ... he has never apologized,'' Bush said.
   ``I'm not faulting the governor of Massachusetts for one error
in judgment. But it concerns me deeply that in all this time, as
far as I know, the governor has never acknowledged that his
furlough program was a mistake,'' Bush said.
   ``While the governor has shown great compassion for the
difficulties of prisoners and their families _ and no doubt their
hardships are severe _ when it comes to the plight of the victims
and their families, there is what one can only describe as an
astounding lack of sensitivity, a lack of human compassion.''
   The Bush campaign is seizing on the law and order issue as the
tight race with Dukakis nears Election Day. Another crime-oriented
speech is set for Monday in New Jersey.
   The GOP ticket was eager to move beyond reverberations from the
vice presidential debate. Though Bush praised running mate Dan
Quayle, campaign manager Lee Atwater on Thursday focused on
comparing Bush and Dukakis.
   ``You're going to see this debate won't make a difference,''
Atwater told reporters traveling with the campaign. ``The focus of
the race is going to be between two gladiators'' _ Bush and Dukakis.
   While a CBS News poll found that 50 percent of the likely voters
surveyed thought Bentsen won the debate to 27 percent for Quayle,
Atwater was claiming that Bush has solidified an Electoral College
base of 210 to 220 of the 270 votes needed to win.
   ``That gives us an opportunity to really concentrate on three or
four states in the waning days of the campaign,'' he said.
   Asked to name the states, Atwater declined, giving only a list
of what he said are competitive states, including California,
Pennsylvania, New York, Massachusetts, Illinois, Ohio, Michigan,
Wisconsin, Missouri, New Mexico, and Arkansas.
   While Bush praised his running mate immediately after the
debate, he did not mention Quayle at all in his first speech
Thursday morning in Fort Worth, Texas.
   After reporters asked his aides about the omission, Bush opened
two later rallies hailing Quayle's performance.
   At the Permian Basin Oil Museum in Midland, Bush prefaced his
energy policy speech with a lengthy ode to Texas, reciting
anecdotes about his move there from New England as a young man and
his start in the oil business painting rigs similar to the one
behind him.
   He said he was the only candidate ``who shares the values of the
people of Texas ... My values have not changed since the 1950s.''
   Bush strategists professed to be unconcerned about Bentsen's
heavy campaigning in Texas, the state he represents in the U.S.
Senate.
   ``The problem is he can't sell Michael Dukakis,'' said Bush
regional political director Jim Shearer. ``Lloyd Bentsen is a
popular Texan, there's no doubt about it. But he's selling the
wrong soap down here.''
   The Bush campaign has been using an anti-crime TV commercial in
Texas and will begin an ad focusing on defense, which as an
industry is responsible for a hefty number of jobs in Texas,
Shearer said.
   The anti-crime theme apparently will be a central one for Bush
in the waning days of the campaign, with another law-and-order
speech slated for Monday in New Jersey.
   In his Fort Worth speech, Bush proposed doubling the nation's
spending on new prison construction, with the addition of $250
million annually over the next four years. He also said he would
set up a Justice Department anti-gang unit to work with local
jurisdictions.
   He said money seized from drug busts should be used to help fund
the new prisons.
   ``I say that our society can simply not afford any more liberal
experimentation with crime. It's time to get serious about serious
crime,'' he said in a speech where he repeatedly used the word
``liberal'' to criticize failed anti-crime policies and linked them
to Dukakis.
</TEXT>
