<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru   10-07 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0440,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Explains Self Further On Qualifications</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Quayle comments today;
picks up 2nd graf pvs, bgng: Despite that...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee
Dan Quayle said today he was not worried about new television ads
aimed at him by the Dukakis campaign because ``they obviously don't
have anything bad to say about George Bush.''
   Quayle was asked by reporters as he toured a technical school
whether he had become the key issue in the campaign.
   ``We can stand the attention. We can stand the heat. We're going
to stay in the kitchen,'' Quayle said. ``George Bush is going to be
the next president of the United States. The voters will vote for
him.''
   Quayle was greeted by a group of about 75 protesters as he
toured Chattanooga State Technical Community College. Some carried
signs reading, ``We will all pray if Dan becomes president.''
   During a tour of the school's robotics lab, Quayle was asked by
reporters about ads the Dukakis campaign unveiled Thursday aimed at
driving home the idea that Bush had picked an unqualified man as
his running mate.
   ``I haven't seen them. I've heard about them. They obviously
don't have anything bad to say about George Bush and that's fine
with me,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle has shrugged off polls indicating voters believe he lost
the vice presidential debate and doubt his qualifications.
   Despite that rhetoric, Quayle acknowledged to reporters Thursday
that he could have answered more fully questions from debate
panelists about what he would do if he became president.
   But the Indiana senator focused his efforts Thursday on
attacking Democratic counterpart Lloyd Bentsen, saying he
``waffled, shuffled, ducked and dived'' questions about his
differences with ticketmate Michael Dukakis.
   Quayle was campaigning today in Chattanooga, Atlanta and
Raleigh, N.C., before returning to Washington.
   ``We're on the march toward victory,'' Quayle told reporters who
asked him upon arrival here how he felt a day after the debate. He
said he had had ``a great day.''
   ``I think you can tell the real enthusiasm that the crowds have
generated,'' Quayle said at a Pensacola, Fla., stop.
   He spent Thursday refining his answer to questions he was
repeatedly asked in Wednesday night's debate about how he would
handle the presidency.
   Polls all along have shown substantial skepticism among the
voters about Quayle's qualifications. A new CBS poll done after the
debate found 47 percent of the likely voters surveyed felt he was
qualified, compared with 78 percent for Bentsen. And both CBS and
ABC polls said a resounding majority of those who viewed the debate
thought Bentsen had won.
   Quayle said he was ``not at all worried'' about the polls,
adding ``we're still ahead.''
   ``As far as we're concerned, the important polls are those from
the key electoral states,'' said Quayle spokesman David Prosperi.
``The only poll we're interest in is on Nov. 8.''
   But the campaign was clearly concerned about the fallout from
Quayle's response to questions about what he would do if he had to
step into the presidency. He had answered that he would first pray
and then convene a Cabinet session but did not go further, electing
to talk mostly about his congressional experience and
qualifications.
   ``When I was asked that question, I made a judgment that the
people of America deserved to hear me outline the level of my
qualifications and the depth of my experience to assume the
presidency,'' Quayle said in speeches in Missouri and Florida.
   ``I responded to that point and the core of my thinking is this:
There is no question that I would maintain and build on the
excellent policies of a president George Bush.''
   Asked by reporters on his plane why he had not made that
response during the debate, Quayle said: ``It was a very narrow
hypothetical ... I hadn't had that question before.
   ``By convening a Cabinet session, that certainly implies that
you're going to continue the policies of George Bush. I did not say
that, but that's certainly implied. I think I did just fine last
night.''
   One of Quayle's defenders was former President Gerald Ford, who
told a Springfield, Mo., fund-raiser, ``I think Dan Quayle is an
outstanding young man and he will do a superb job as the next vice
president.''
   Ford, himself a former Michigan congressman, said that on the
issue of qualifications, Quayle's 12 years in Congress were more
than enough.
   ``I happen to think that people who come from the Congress are
better trained to serve in the executive branch ... than some
inexperienced governor with a wild-eyed, left-wing liberal
philosophy like the Democratic candidate's,'' Ford said.
   Quayle attacked Bentsen in strong terms, saying that he had been
unable to defend Dukakis' positions.
   ``I am proud of the man at the top of my ticket,'' Quayle said.
``I am happy to support his positions, and I won't run away from
them like Senator Bentsen did last night.''
</TEXT>
