<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-WorldCourt     10-07 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-World Court,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviets Discussing Changes In World Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diploamtic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has proposed to the Soviet
Union that it accept decisions of the World Court in
interpretations of a host of international treaties, a U.S.
official said today.
   Some of the decision deal with such technical subjects as
patents and others with diplomatic privileges. The United States is
a party to must of the treaties but the Soviets over the years have
registered ``reservations'' that exempt them from the effects of
many of the treaties, said the official who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The U.S. proposals, which also involve greater use of the court,
were conveyed to Moscow during the summer in response to hints from
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other Soviet officials in
United Nations speeches that they were prepared to consider changes.
   The United States is coordinating its approach with a number of
Western allies, the official said. He declined to provide further
details, saying it was ``a sensitive subject.''
   But the official said ``a host of multilateral treaties'' were
involved.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley stressed Thursday
that ``it's our view that issues involving the use of force and
national security do not belong in the International Court of
Justice.''
   She said further discussions would be held with the Soviets and
that she had no details of possible suggested changes in the
court's operations.
   Two years ago, in an unprecedented move, the Reagan
administration rejected the court's jurisdiction in a dispute with
Nicaragua.
   The Marxist government in Managua had sued the United States
before the court for mining its harbors and aiding Nicaraguan
rebels.
   Mrs. Oakley's statement indicated the administration held to the
view, which was developed by Abraham D. Sofaer, a former federal
judge who is the State Department chief legal counsel.
   The New York Times quoted Sofaer on Thursday as saying the
United States had responded ``in a constructive way'' to
Gorbachev's initiative.
   Sofaer said the United States had suggested the court be
permitted to arbitrate a list of specific disputes between
Washington and Moscow and agree in advance to accept its verdict,
the Times reported.
   If accepted by Moscow and the U.S. Senate, the article said, the
U.S. proposals would bind both nations to World Court verdicts in
disputes over certain treaties.
   Mrs. Oakley said ``the U.S. has made a proposal on the issue of
greater use of the ICJ (International Court of Justice) to the
Soviets this summer, which is wholly consistent with this
administration's view of the appropriate role of the Court in
resolve international disputes.''
   She said this did not involve a change in the stand the
administration took in the dispute with Nicaragua.
   Sofaer did not respond to efforts to reach him by telephone for
details.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
