<2ND_LINE>PM-Battered Wife,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Battered Wife Cleared in Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOODSTOCK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who said she shot her husband 14
times because he had beaten and abused her for years was acquitted
of murder.
   Cynthia Iandola, 36, was charged with first-degree murder after
she shot her husband, Jack, in the kitchen of their home Jan. 11.
   A McHenry County jury deliberated nine hours before reaching the
verdict, which was greeted by cheers in the courtroom when it was
announced Thursday.
   Mrs. Iandola contended the killing was in self-defense because
her husband had threatened to kill her and their two children.
   She testified that in one incident a few days before the
shooting, her husband sexually abused her with the barrel of a gun
and indicated that he might try to rape their 13-year-old daughter.
   Much of her testimony was corroborated by witnesses at her trial.
   Judge Roland Herrmann refused to allow defense attorneys to
present expert testimony indicating that Mrs. Iandola was a victim
of ``battered woman's syndrome,'' a phenomenon in which the wife
submits passively to abuse from a bullying husband.
   During the trial, State's Attorney Thomas F. Baker conceded that
Iandola was a ``bully'' who brutalized his family but said Mrs.
Iandola should have deserted him or sought protection from the
police or social agencies.
</TEXT>
