<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Scoffs at GOP Claims That Quayle Held Own in Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Bentsen comments today; pick up 3rd graf
pvs bgng ``The next couple...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd
Bentsen today made light of Republican assertions that Dan Quayle
held his own during their vice presidential debate.
   ``I was reading the paper this morning where George Bush said he
thought Dan Quayle won that, and yet every ... I'm sorry,'' Bentsen
said, breaking into laughter and drawing a roar from a crowd at a
Democratic breakfast.
   ``And yet every poll showed we won, and I'd say `George, as
President Reagan would say, facts are very troubling things,''
Bentsen said.
   The Texas senator said the Democrats were better on key issues
to his home state, including a realistic defense policy, a strong
trade policy, and help for the domestic oil industry. And he said
his debate might later be seen as ``a turning point'' in this
year's campaign.
   Bentsen ridiculed Quayle for trying to compare himself in the
debate to President Kennedy. It was an ``incredible misfit,'' he
said, ticking off Kennedy's accomplishments.
   Despite Bentsen's presence on the ticket, Bush leads Michael
Dukakis in the Lone Star state by up to 10 points, according to
recent polls. The Democrats contend the gap isn't that big, and
Bentsen is campaigning heavily in Texas during the next few days in
hopes of tightening th race for the state's 29 electoral votes.
   ``The next couple of days I think will be significant,'' said
Joe O'Neill, Bentsen's campaign chief of staff. ``We can move these
numbers in the next couple of weeks.''
   Bentsen planned to continue stumping across Texas today, with
events in Dallas, San Antonio and Houston. After a stop in New
Mexico, he planned to hit El Paso on Saturday and then return to
the state for part of his campaign trip next week.
   Bentsen studied for the debate in Texas, and he returned to the
state Thursday. He met up with Dukakis at a rally in Lone Star, in
East Texas.
   ``Last night, the eyes of Texas and the whole nation were on
you, and they liked what they saw,'' Dukakis told his running mate.
   Normally, Bentsen introduces Dukakis but their roles were
reversed as Dukakis sought to show off his running mate as a
conquering hero.
   Bentsen declined to praise himself, but he picked up on his
pre-debate pattern of criticizing Quayle.
   ``After listening to Dan Quayle last night, I can understand why
he kept talking about job training,'' he said at the rally.
   ``The polls show that those that were concerned about his
qualifications for the presidency had that buttressed by the debate
last night,'' he told reporters.
   A new CBS News poll done after the debate found 78 percent of
the 412 debate watchers surveyed felt Bentsen was qualified to be
president, if that became necessary, to 47 percent for Quayle.
   Asked who won the debate, 50 percent in the survey chose Bentsen
and 27 percent said Quayle. The result was almost precisely the
same as the 51-27 percent split in the ABC News poll done
immediately after the debate ended Wednesday night.
   The campaign hopes to take advantage of the momentum from the
perceived debate victory with the help of its new national
television ads and phone banks assembled for the final weeks of the
campaign.
   In Texas, Republicans have been hitting Dukakis hard on the
issues of crime and gun control, and the Democratic campaign was
considering running some Texas-specific ads to start fighting back,
a campaign aide said.
   President Reagan and other Republicans contended Thursday that
Bentsen's admonishing of Quayle during the debate that he was ``no
Jack Kennedy'' was a ``cheap shot'' and a planned response. Bentsen
denied both.
   ``What happened there was Quayle kept comparing himself with
Kennedy, just overreaching himself, and I got fed up with it,''
Bentsen said. ``I deeply resented him trying to put Kennedy's
mantle over himself when he didn't have a record that compared with
Kennedy.''
   Bentsen and Kennedy were elected to Congress together in 1948.
Bentsen served three terms in the House before dropping out of
politics for 16 years to pursue a business career.
</TEXT>
