<HEAD>Bookstore Explosion Injures Two; Bomb Found In A Second Store</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with bombing Thursday. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion today damaged a
bookstore in a white suburb of Durban and injured two people,
police said. Shortly afterward, a bomb was found in a downtown
branch of the store.
   The blast occurred around 2 p.m. at the Central News Agency
bookstore in suburban Pinetown, police said.
   About an hour later, police said they found a bomb at a Central
News Agency branch in downtown Durban. Police evacuated thousands
of people from surrounding office buildings and cordoned off the
area, witnesses said.
   On Thursday, six people were hurt, including one seriously, when
a bomb exploded outside the municipal offices of a mixed-race
township near Johannesburg, police said.
   A limpet mine placed in a trash bin also damaged windows and
walls of the municipal building in Tembisa, east of Johannesburg,
police added.
   The victims included three men and three women, police said. The
government-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said one of the
women was in serious condition.
   There have been almost daily bombings in recent weeks in South
Africa. The 29 bombings in September were the most ever in the
country in a single month.
   Police have blamed virtually all of the attacks on the outlawed
African National Congress, the main black guerrilla group
attempting to overthrow the white-led government.
   Police say the ANC has intensified its bombing campaign in a bid
to disrupt the nationwide municipal elections set for Oct. 26.
   There have been about 150 bombings in South Africa since the
government declared a nationwide state of emergency in June 1986.
</TEXT>
