<2ND_LINE>PM-Arson Trial,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pair Cleared In Crack House Arson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men who admitted setting fire to a house
suspected of being used to deal cocaine have been acquitted by a
jury, leading city officials to warn against vigilante action.
   Jury foreman Anthony Allen said Thursday's verdict was a way of
telling city officials more has to be done to fight drugs.
   ``I imagine the verdict does send out a message in two
directions _ to the mayor and to the Police Department that more
has to be done about crack houses,'' Allen said.
   Angelo Parisi and Perry Kent were found innocent after a two-day
trial. They admitted setting the fire, saying they feared for the
safety of children in their neighborhood.
   ``I hope this verdict sends no message,'' Presiding Judge Craig
Strong told the jurors. ``It applies to the facts only in this
case.''
   But some jurors said they cleared Parisi and Kent because
Detroit's drug problem could cause people to take extreme measures.
   ``(I) would have probably done the same thing. No. I would have
been more violent,'' juror Raymond Bandemer said.
   The charges stemmed from fires in October and November 1987 at
an abandoned house allegedly occupied by drug dealers who the
defendants testified had turned their quiet, working-class
neighborhood into a place of fear.
   ``They were laughing at the neighborhood,'' Kent testified.
   Defense attorney David Steingold said residents of the
neighborhood were continually frightened by the sound of gunfire.
   Parisi and Kent said they started the fires after police failed
to investigate complaints filed by them and other residents.
   Law enforcement authorities said they don't condone vigilantism
and will take all possible measures to prevent such activity.
   Wayne County Prosecutor John O'Hair said he ``will not permit
law-abiding citizens to break the law on the theory that they're
frustrated ... Vigilantism simply will not be tolerated.''
</TEXT>
