<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CampaignAbroad 1stLd-Writethru a0565 10-07 0883</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Abroad, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0565,0913</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen-Quayle Debate as Viewed Abroad</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, ADDS comment from Canada and Italy; switches from ``i'' to
``p'' category code.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a sampling of commentary in foreign newspapers on the
vice-presidential debate between Democrat Lloyd Bentsen and
Republican Dan Quayle in Omaha, Neb., Wednesday night:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FRANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Jan Krauze, writing from Washington in Le Monde (independent)
of Paris: ``Mastering his nerves right to the end (Quayle) avoided
the gaffe, the catastrophic error that would have sealed his fate,
but one sensed too much, during the last part of the debate, that
he was making a considerable effort to try to show he was up to the
challenge. The tension, too strong, lasted too long and, deep in
the eyes of the `handsome kid,' one perceived clearly the shadow of
a wounded, insulted pride.
   ``The essential ... was to put to the test a man whose presence
on the Republican `ticket' poses, by all the evidence, a problem.
Dan Quayle was neither brilliant nor ridiculous and, if the problem
remains, it is not necessarily as serious as the Democrats hoped.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Guardian (liberal) of London: ``Mr. Quayle managed to avoid
any gaffe which would significantly alter the course of the
election campaign. ... But his presumptuous comparison of his
congressional record with President Kennedy's, so magisterially
squashed by Mr. Bentsen, serves to reinforce existing doubts about
his maturity, intelligence and judgment. Mr. Quayle was
unconvincing, if not pathetic, when asked three times what he would
do first if he became president. His initial response _ that he
would pray _ was doubtless fervently echoed around the country. By
contrast, the suave and courtly Bentsen, seen by some as the most
convincing potential president around, remained firmly in control.
...
   ``In their television debate, it was the Democratic candidate
who showed the cool intelligence and articulacy which Europeans
find reassuring. ... His (Quayle's) view that Mikhail Gorbachev is
different only in style from Leonid Brezhnev, and that perestroika
is nothing more than refined Stalinism, suggests a shaky grasp of
international affairs. ...
   ``If the Republicans lose on 8 November, unlikely though this
may now seem, the Quayle factor will rightly be high among likely
causes.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRAZIL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Folha de S. Paulo (independent) of Sao Paulo: ``Quayle came off
much better than expected, but he has two serious problems: he's 41
but looks 21. Would the majority of voters accept such a young
president, if a tragedy struck George Bush? The second problem is
that the American media has indelibly hammered into the public
consciousness Quayle's evasion of military service in the Vietnam
War and the `string-pullers' he used to get his precarious law
degree. ...
   ``Bensten was a disappointment. He's 67 but looks older. He
began with a hoarse voice that suggested physical frailty. And he
made the same mistake that has beleaguered Michael Dukakis'
campiagn: an excess of explanations about complex subjects and an
excess of statistics, that the majority of the public doesn't
follow or understand.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CANADA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Globe and Mail (independent) of Toronto: ``In Wednesday
night's televised debate, U.S. Senator Dan Quayle proved himself to
be everything that most people who know him say he isn't. He isn't
very bright. He isn't very thoughtful. And he isn't well informed.
   Mr. Quayle is not qualified to be Vice-President of the United
States. The problem is not his age (41) or even his caricatured
conservative posturings. The problem is his intellect, which,
combined with a poor education and narrow work experience outside
politics, deprives him of the basic tools to do the job. Part of
the job, is, of course, assuming the presidency in the event of a
mid-term vacancy. Mr. Quayle will have the whole world fervently
drinking to George Bush's health if the Republicans win the White
House on Nov. 8.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ITALY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Correspondent Rodolfo Brancoli, writing in Corriere della Sera
(moderate) of Milan: ``What a mistake the young Quayle made!
Blond-tufted and arrogant, he compared himself to John Kennedy and
received one of those responses that go down in the annals of
politics. He never did recover and finished the television debate
stammering.
   ``... (Quayle's comparison) was the only memorable moment of the
1988 campaign. Until that moment, he had been able to get out of
the worst, firing off responses that were clearly preconcocted but
at any rate avoiding any trouble.''
