<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NewsweekRetirement     10-07 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newsweek Retirement,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newsweek Offer Some Staff Early Retirement Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newsweek magazine is offering early retirement
to 100 employees, or 10 percent of its work force, because of
higher costs and a shrinking advertisement base, a spokesman said
today.
   ``The program is entirely voluntary,'' said spokesman Gary
Gerard. ``It's not draconian in any way.''
   Gerard said 100 fulltime employees _ those with 25 years or more
of service or those age 55 and older with 10 years at the magazine
_ received letters detailing the offer.
   He said it includes pension enhancement and continuation of some
insurance benefits. The size of the package will vary depending on
the employees' age and length of service.
   The weekly magazine's revenues were up 1 percent during the
first half of 1988 and Gerard said domestic circulation was at an
``all time high of 3.3 million.''
   However, the number of domestic ad pages has dropped 6 percent
from a year ago.
   ``Obviously, our costs have gone up substantially, primarily
postage and paper, and the advertising environment has become
increasingly competitive,'' said Diana Pearson, a magazine
spokeswoman. ``It forces us to operate in as lean and smart a way
as we can.''
   Gerard said 60 percent of those offered early retirement were on
the business side of the magazine and the rest were editorial
employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
