<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Argentina-Bombs     10-07 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Argentina-Bombs,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Aimed At Jews And Leftists Cause Damage But No Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs, one apparently aimed
at Jewish people and the other at leftists, exploded and caused
damage but no injuries, police said.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for Thursday's
bombings.
   The first bomb exploded in the street in front of an exchange
house in the financial district, shattering windows and plaster.
   Exchange house owner Miguel Salcido said pamphlets reading
``Jews Stop Exploiting the Country'' and ``More Jews, Fewer
Australs'' were found nearby. The austral is the Argentine unit of
currency.
   The second explosion, in the working class suburb of William
Morris, destroyed a small concrete monument to two Montonero
leftist guerrillas killed in a shootout with police in 1970.
   The Montoneros, who kidnapped and killed former President Gen.
Pedro Aramburu in 1970, were virtually wiped out by security forces
by the mid-1970s.
</TEXT>
