<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Finland-Politics     10-07 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Finland-Politics,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Coalition Survives No-Confidence Motion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The four-party governing coalition
Friday survived its fourth motion of no-confidence since taking
office 17 months ago.
   Conservative Prime Minister Harri Holkeri's government, which
includes the Social Democrats, the Rural Party and the Swedish
People's Party, won the vote 123-64, with 12 members absent.
   The motion criticized the government's tax reform plans and the
1989 budget proposals, which the opposition said favored the rich.
   The main opposition Center Party, which has been gaining support
in opinion polls since the last election, charges the government
has not done enough for students and the poor.
   A survey published last month indicated growing disillusionment
with the government.
   The survey showed that the Conservatives and the Social
Democrats had only 40 percent support, down from 47 percent in the
March 1987 election.
</TEXT>
