<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HarveyTrial     10-07 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvey Trial,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunman Pleads Guilty to Kidnapping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weeping James L. Harvey pleaded guilty
today to six counts of kidnapping in the Feb. 2 takeover of a
private school and was sentenced to one life term, plus five
20-year terms.
   Harvey clutched a red-bound Bible as Circuit Judge John M. Karrh
of Tuscaloosa asked him how he pleaded to each count. Harvey nodded
and said softly, ``Guilty.''
   The pleas came in the third day of Harvey's trial on 110 counts
of kidnapping. The other counts were dropped in exchange for his
guilty pleas. He could have faced up to 10,000 years in prison.
   Karrh told Harvey his sentences would run concurrently and that
he would recommend Harvey get psychiatric treatment in the prison
system.
   ``I think you need treatment,'' the judge told Harvey, who sat
in a chair during the sentencing.
   Harvey had been charged with kidnapping 110 people at gunpoint
at the West End Christian School in Tuscaloosa. Harvey had been
defending himself in state court here as a crusader for people's
constitutional rights.
   A second man, described by police as an unwilling accomplice,
testified Thursday he was duped by Harvey into helping take over
the school and later was threatened with his life if he tried to
back out.
   Two of Harvey's sisters, Doris Elliott and Martha Gray, both of
Tuscaloosa, had met with him last night and today to try to talk
him into pleading guilty.
   ``I begged him to go to prison,'' Mrs. Gray said. ``At least he
will have part of his life.''
   She said her brother was mentally and physically exhausted. She
said he was suffering from a cold and had lost 20 pounds in the
eight months since the school takeover.
   Sheriff Joe Patterson of Tuscaloosa County, who with five of his
deputies guarded Harvey during the sentencing, said Harvey would be
returned to Tuscaloosa by Tuscaloosa County authorities for
transfer to prison.
</TEXT>
