<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Locusts     10-07 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Locusts,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudan Stops Frontier Locust-Spraying; Blames Ethiopian Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan said Friday it has stopped trying
to control a locust plague along the Ethiopian border because of
military attacks.
   The defense minister says no one has been hurt in the assaults
on villages and spray planes, but he said vehicles were burned in
an air attack on a convoy near Kassala, 260 miles east of Khartoum.
He said the government has asked the Ethiopian government to stop
the attacks.
   The episode appeared to be a major setback to Khartoum's efforts
to deal with one of Sudan's worst locust infestations in years.
   In Addis Ababa, the Ethiopian capital, officials refused comment
on the situation.
   Relations between Sudan and Ethiopia have been strained for
several years, especially since a rebellion broke out in southern
Sudan in 1983.
   Sudan accuses Ethiopia of arming, financing and harboring the
rebels. Addis Ababa alleges that Khartoum allows several
anti-Ethiopian guerrilla groups to maintain official, open presence
in the Sudanese capital.
   The official Sudan News Agency said Syd Ali Mohamed Ali,
director of the Agriculture Ministry's Plant Protection Department
in eastern Sudan, announced the decision to abandon the frontier
spraying operation.
   ``All locust control operations along the Sudanese-Ethiopian
borders were completely halted due to the shelling of the pest
control areas by the Ethiopian air force,'' the news agency said.
   It quoted Ali as saying that sprayers and others involved with
the program already were withdrawn.
   Swarms of the crop-devouring insects appeared in several African
countries in recent weeks after heavy rains created perfect
breeding conditions.
   In Sudan, swarms have occurred mainly in the eastern and western
regions, but one massive swarm hit crops in the Khartoum area and
others are expected. The government committed 22 planes to the
spraying operation, but officials say three won't fly and one
crashed in the western sector.
   Ahmed Mahmoud Issa, minister of state at the Agriculture
Ministry, told the newspaper Al-Ayam that two Ethiopian MiG jet
fighters attacked vehicles assigned to the crop-dusting operation
in villages along the border. He said spray planes had come under
fire from within Ethiopia.
   The armed forces newspaper Al-Guwat Al-Musalaha confirmed the
reports on Thursday.
   ``The Ethiopian air force intercepted a locust spray convoy last
week in the eastern region ... and hit some cars working in the
spray operation,'' the newspaper said. ``No one was hurt.''
   Defense Minister Abdel-Meguid Hamid Khalil told Al-Guwat
Al-Musalaha the Foreign Ministry had relayed Sudan's demand that
Ethiopia ``stop violating Sudanese air space'' so that ``we work
together ... to eradicate locusts, which affect all the countries
in the region including Ethiopia.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
