<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Inmates-Marijuana     10-07 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inmates-Marijuana,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates Grew Marijuana on Prison Work Detail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TILLAMOOK, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine prison inmates who grew marijuana
while on work details in a forest were caught trying to smuggle 31
pounds of pot into a state prison work camp, Oregon State Police
said today.
   The inmates had been cultivating the marijuana in an area where
they were supposed to be planting trees, state police Sgt. Michael
D. Stephenson said. A state prison work vehicle carrying the
inmates was returning from a work area near Jewell when it was
stopped late Tuesday outside the South Fork Prison Camp by state
police and Tillamook County sheriff's deputies acting on a tip.
Inside the vehicle they found two duffle bags containing 31 pounds
of marijuana.
   The inmates offered no resistance but one prisoner tried to
swallow ``his stash'' and had to be taken to Tillamook County
General Hospital for removal of marijuana that had lodged in his
throat, Stephenson said.
   The inmates were charged with manufacturing a controlled
substance, possession of more than one ounce of marijuana and
supplying contraband, he said.
</TEXT>
