<2ND_LINE>AM-People,1006</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Denver says he has until Nov. 1 to
accept a ``very serious'' invitation to fly aboard a Soviet
spacecraft.
   ``This is not a stunt to me. ... I think that it's the best
thing that I can do right now for my country, for NASA, for our
space effort, for our people and for the planet,'' the ``Rocky
Mountain High'' singer said Thursday.
   However, Denver said the Soviets' insistence that he pay $10
million for the flight would likely prompt him to drop the project.
   ``I've told them that I'm opposed to paying $10 million, that I
think it's inappropriate, that I think it's negative and that it's
not the way I want to pursue this endeavor,'' he said.
   Among the Soviet requirements that Denver said he has fulfilled
is obtaining permission from the U.S. government and passing a
physical for space flight with NASA.
   ``At this point they have a slot open for me, December of next
year,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merv Griffin, the talk show host
turned real estate tycoon, christened the newly decorated
International Ballroom of his Beverly Hilton Hotel with a celebrity
bash.
   James Stewart, Walter Matthau, Tom Selleck, Anne Bancroft and
Mel Brooks, Red Buttons, Suzanne Pleshette, Suzanne Somers, Kenny
Rogers, Carl Reiner, Dina Merrill and Cesar Romero were some of the
famous faces at Thursday night's fete.
   The crowd seemed to approve of the new, lighter decor of the
ballroom, which has held such events as the Oscar Ball and the
Directors Guild and Golden Globe awards ceremonies.
   ``I love it,'' said Lucille Ball. ``It's about time this town
had a place like this.''
   Griffin, who also owns several Resorts International hotels,
returned to his band singer roots by ascending the bandstand and
accompanying a male quartet on ``It Had To Be You,'' ``Pennies From
Heaven'' and other standards.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss America Gretchen Carlson, who has
shaken hands with President Reagan, eaten sushi with Bill Cosby and
chatted with David Letterman on his talk show, says: ``I'm still
me. I haven't changed.''
   Returning to her home state Thursday, Miss Carlson said, ``The
first thing I do when we get to the hotel room is get into my robe,
and the second thing is see what room service has.''
   Miss Carlson's schedule Thursday included a morning news
conference, a three-hour taping of two talk shows in the afternoon
and an evening reception with Gov. Rudy Perpich and four former
Miss Americas.
   She is scheduled to appear at a homecoming celebration in her
hometown of Anoka on Saturday, after which she will visit 20 cities
in 30 days.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retiring Sen. William Proxmire says he's had
some discussions with the National Taxpayers Union about continuing
his trademark Golden Fleece awards, but that their future is still
up in the air.
   The monthly awards publicize what the feisty Wisconsin Democrat
considers a waste of government money.
   ``I've talked with the National Taxpayers Union but nothing has
been decided,'' Proxmire said Thursday. ``No individual could do it
without staff help unless he spent full time on it, and I don't
want to spend all my time on Golden Fleeces.''
   Proxmire, 71, who did not seek re-election this year, said when
it comes time to clear out his office in January, he'll move over
to the Library of Congress. The library offers office space to all
retiring senators but requires that they spend at least 16 hours a
week there.
   ``I'll have a desk and a typewriter _ and access to the best
research facilities on the face of the Earth,'' said Proxmire, who
plans to write on topics such as the national debt and employment.
   The senator also noted the new space will probably be ``a
quarter of the size of my office in the Senate.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proud Prince Andrew calls his 2-month-old
daughter, Beatrice, ``quite extraordinary.''
   ``She is really very alert and does not make much noise,'' the
Duke of York said of his first child, born Aug. 8 to him and his
wife, the former Sarah Ferguson. ``She has Sarah's eyes and I am
convinced she is going to be prettier than both of us.''
   He said Beatrice's hair continually changed color, some days red
like her mother's, some days not.
   ``I don't think she is going to be as red as people think,'' he
told Press Association, the British domestic press agency, in an
interview published Thursday.
   Andrew brushed aside criticism from the Australian and British
media that he and his wife should have brought the infant on a
recent tour of Australia.
   ``If they bothered to think about it for one second, Beatrice is
much better off at home where things are stable,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James F. Neal, who successfully
prosecuted Watergate figures H.R. Haldeman, John Ehrlichman and
John Mitchell, said his first encounter with cameras in the
courtroom left him with stage fright.
   ``I was terrified,'' said Neal, but added that it took him only
a day to get comfortable with the medium.
   The attorney told the American Society of Newspaper Editors on
Thursday that his first experience with cameras in the courtroom
came in 1986, when he successfully defended film director John
Landis and four other men charged with involuntary manslaughter.
   The charges stemmed from the 1982 deaths of actor Vic Morrow and
two children who were killed on the set of ``Twilight Zone: The
Movie'' when a helicopter crashed onto them.
   ``I now have no hesitation in having a camera in the courtroom
at any time, and if you're the kind of lawyer that you should be, I
think you ignore it,'' Neal said.
</TEXT>
