<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NorthDakotaSenate Bjt   10-07 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North Dakota Senate, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>80-Year-Old Senator Says He's Fit For Another Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Quentin Burdick used to offer a
karate chop for anyone saying the 80-year-old senator was too old
to run for re-election. The karate line is gone, but Burdick still
argues he's fit despite his advancing age and a recent cancer
operation.
   The 28-year Democratic Senate veteran maintains a comfortable
lead over Republican opponent Earl Strinden, who argues that the
issue is Burdick's ``ability to be a vigorous U.S. senator for the
next six years.''
   ``I'm in good shape,'' counters Burdick. ``I'm surprising
myself.''
   A University of North Dakota poll taken in late September gave
Burdick a 57 percent to 32 percent lead over Strinden but indicated
that 35 percent of eligible voters were concerned about his mental
and physical fitness.
   Part of Strinden's problem appears to be his personality. Even
people who like the 56-year-old House majority leader say he's
abrasive. Some 37 percent of North Dakotans view Strinden
unfavorably, according to an earlier poll.
   ``I've taken many stands over the years that have at that moment
in time been unpopular,'' said Strinden. ``I'm a fighter. I've
always been a fighter.''
   A series of television commercials intended to soften Strinden's
image as an overbearing leader made little difference, and now
Burdick has started a series of attacks on the Republican's record
on farm and social service issues.
   Strinden accuses Burdick of dodging face-to-face meetings with
him and says a pair of debates later this month, when the senator
must speak extemporaneously, will demonstrate whether he has the
stamina for another six-year term.
   So far, though, Burdick has kept his distance, saying his work
in the Senate, where he is chairman of the Environment and Public
Works Committee, is taking up his time.
   ``I've got to finish my job down there,'' Burdick said in a
recent interview at the Bismarck airport. ``I can't leave.''
   Burdick has limited his campaigning primarily to television and
has turned down numerous invitations for joint appearances with his
challenger.
   When the two candidates were asked to speak at a meeting of the
state's broadcasters, Strinden showed up, but Burdick sent his
press secretary and a video-taped speech.
   Burdick has been hospitalized twice in the last year, once for a
concussion when he slipped on ice last winter and hit his head, and
again last summer when doctors removed 18 inches of his intestine
after a cancerous polyp was discovered.
   Several leading Democrats first raised the age issue last year
in an unsuccessful attempt to get him to retire, and Republicans
have picked up where Burdick's Democratic critics left off.
   Strinden is pinning his hopes on winning over Democrats and
independents who have doubts about Burdick's fitness. ``There's a
sizable number of people out there supporting him who really don't
think he should run again,'' said Strinden.
   Some 26 percent of Democrats and 34 percent of independents
polled in late September were concerned about his age.
   ``It still could be an issue, but not the kind of issue that the
Strinden campaign hoped that people would hook onto,'' said Phil
Harmeson, who conducts the UND surveys. After all, this is a state
that re-elected 77-year-old Milton Young in 1974; Young finally
retired, at 83.
   To highlight his own good health, Strinden once held a news
conference with his doctor, who told reporters that the Republican
candidate has gained a little weight and drinks too much coffee.
   Strinden has just $120,000 left in the bank after wasting, he
says, a similar amount on pre-October commercials, including an
$8,000 anti-drunken driving campaign.
   With so little money left, Strinden cannot afford to counter the
blitz of Burdick ads for which he is bracing, he said.
   Burdick has raised more than $1 million for his campaign and
still has about $400,000 left, says Carolyn Nelson, his campaign
treasurer.
   Strinden maintains that his campaign was right on track until
Burdick's surgery. The operation, from which Burdick appeared to
recover quickly, won the sympathy of voters and gave him a boost in
the polls, Strinden said.
   Burdick, who has challenged political opponents to spar with him
in a karate match if they doubt his health, started running a
vigorous media campaign soon after the 1986 election gave Democrats
control of the Senate and elevated him to the committee
chairmanship.
   Burdick says he will convince voters of his vigor when he gets
back to North Dakota. Congress was scheduled to adjourn this
weekend.
   ``They'll see me on TV, they'll see me in person. ... They can
see for themselves what shape I'm in,'' he said.
</TEXT>
