<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NeedlesAshore     10-07 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Needles Ashore,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medical Needles Wash Ashore In Palm Beach County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of unused needles in
protective plastic sheaths washed up along six`lles of beach, and
two medical waste bags were found to the north, officials said.
   The disposable needles were found Thursday from Riviera Beach to
Palm Beach but were sealed, and no syringes were found, officials
said. The waste bags were discovered the same day on Hutchinson
Island, north of Palm Beach County.
   ``We don't think the needles are any kind of public health
risk,'' said Charles Rhodes, head of the Palm Beach County Health
Departgeit's environmental health division. No beaches were closed
because of the needles.
   The one-liter bags of a type used to hold blood taken for
transfusions had no hospital markings, authorities said. The
needles were sent to a state laboratory in Jacksonville to be
analyzed for clues to their manufacturer.
   ``We can only guess the needles were dumped from a passing
vessel,'' Rhodes said. ``They could have come from some distance
through the Gulf Stream. Some of them have barnacles on them.''
</TEXT>
