<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-USBases     10-07 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-US Bases,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10th Round of Talks Wrapped Up, More Next Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators concluded another round of
talks on U.S. military bases in Greece without discussing a Greek
demand for the closure of an Air Force base at Athens Airport, a
government spokesman said Friday.
   The negotiators will meet again next month in Washington, he
said.
   The spokesman, Sotiris Kostopoulos, said American defense aid to
Greece was among issues discussed but that Greece's demand to close
the Air Force base ``wasn't especially touched upon.''
   Greece is insisting that Hellenikon base, where 1,400 Americans
are stationed, must be shut after the current bases agreement
expires in December.
   ``Different aspects were discussed, such as defense aid, ...and
the issue of principles to be included in the preamble to the
expected agreement,'' Kostopoulos said.
   Greece gets more than $430 million in U.S. military credits as a
form of rent for the bases.
   The government also is eager to maintain a longstanding
agreement under which Greece receives $7 in U.S. aid for every $10
that goes to Turkey.
   The ``issues of principle'' mentioned by Kostopoulos are
understood to involve a Greek request for the agreement to include
backing for Greek positions in disputes with fellow NATO-member
Turkey over control of the Aegean Sea.
   The United States operates four bases in Greece and about 20
smaller communications facilities around the country.
</TEXT>
