<HEAD>Fever Declines Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors used a new antibiotic Friday and Emperor
Hirohito's fever declined slightly, but reports said there was
danger that an infection in his digestive system would spread.
   Although he showed no outward signs of further internal
bleeding, the 87-year-old emperor received another transfusion to
counteract anemia and because doctors doubted the hemorrhaging had
stopped, palace officials said.
   It was the 15th day of blood transfusions.
   According to local news reports, police said the chairman of a
group sponsoring a sports festival committed suicide last week,
apparently because of conflict over whether to hold the event.
   Many autumn sports festivals, concerts and other events have
been canceled because of the illness of the world's
longest-reigning monarch, to whom some Japanese still ascribe the
divinity he renounced after World War II.
   Hirohito's temperature Friday evening was 99.5, down from 100.6
Thursday, palace spokesman Kenji Maeda told reporters.
