<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Polio     10-07 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Polio,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos TLV1, TLV2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Israel Gives Hundreds Polio Boosters After Outbreak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REHOVOT, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of children were vaccinated
against polio Friday in the first stage of a nationwide campaign to
immunize all Israelis up to the age of 40 against the disease.
   The Health Ministry ordered the campaign after nine Israelis
were infected by polio, which causes muscular paralysis.
   In the next four weeks, about 3.2 million people will be
vaccinated, said ministry spokesman Shmuel Algrabli.
   Israelis are immunized as children, and the current vaccination
is a booster.
   The first stage of the campaign centered on the Tel Aviv suburb
of Rehovot and the northern coastal town of Acco. Polio viruses
were found in the sewage systems of both areas.
   In Rehovot, hundreds of parents lined up at clinics with their
infants. Large yellow wall posters informed residents when
different age groups should report for vaccinations.
   The Tourism Ministry expressed concern that reports of the
disease would keep visitors away from Israel.
   Tourism has dropped dramatically since the Palestinian uprising
in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip began Dec. 8.
   But Health Ministry officials have stressed visitors do not need
extra vaccinations before visiting the country because the outbreak
is limited.
   No cases of polio were reported in Israel last year, and the
recent cases have been blamed on overflowing sewage.
   The government initially decided to give booster vaccinations
only to residents of affected areas, but changed its policy
Thursday following recommendations by a team of international
health experts.
   Military officials said they would decide Sunday whether to
administer booster shots to Palestinians in the West Bank. No such
program is considered in the Gaza Strip.
   Palestinians in the occupied lands have routinely received the
combined Sabin-Salk vaccine, which is more effective than the
single vaccination administered in Israel.
   The stronger vaccine was given to counter often substandard
sanitary conditions in the occupied territories, such as open
sewage systems.
   ``The general situation in the West Bank is very good, but since
the vaccinations are being done in Israel we may administer
boosters,'' said Olivier Rafowicz, a spokesman for the West Bank
military government.
</TEXT>
