<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PostalFraud     10-07 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal Fraud,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Service Suspends Indicted Contractor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service said Friday that it
has suspended Recognition Equipment Inc. from bidding on contracts,
pending outcome of a criminal case against the company and two of
its top executives.
   REI, Chairman William G. Moore Jr. and vice president Robert W.
Reedy were indicted Thursday by a federal grand jury in connection
with an unsuccessful plot to rig bids on $400 million worth of
postal automation contracts.
   Assistant Postmaster General Jack Davin, in charge of
procurement, announced the suspension, which bans the company and
its subsidiaries from bidding on postal contracts for 120 days, and
can be extended pending resolution of the charges against the
company.
   Several relatively small contracts the company and its
subsidiaries currently have with the postal service will not be
affected, but cannot be expanded or renewed.
   According to the indictment, the Texas company's unsuccessful
effort was allegedly engineered in 1986 with the help of Peter E.
Voss, vice-chairman of the Postal Service's Board of Governors.
   The indictment charged that Voss, an unindicted co-conspirator,
manipulated a Postal Service decision over procuring sophisticated
optical-character scanning equipment for sorting mail.
   After the procurement scheme came to light in 1986 with Voss'
guilty plea to kickback and embezzlement charges, the Postal
Service suspended the competition and ultimately gave the contract
to another company.
   If REI had won that contract, it would have been in a position
to obtain contracts worth $4.6 billion over five years.
</TEXT>
