<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope     10-07 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Seeks to Influence Thinking About Europe in French Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II will use the pulpit of
three international institutions to advance his view of Western
Europe at a time when the region is divided about its future
political identity.
   On a four-day trip to France that starts Saturday, the pope will
speak to the Council of Europe, the European Court of Human Rights
and the European Parliament, all in Strasbourg.
   The agreement by Common Market countries to fully integrate
their economies in 1992 has touched off widespread debate about
whether Western Europe should move toward becoming a single
political unit.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain raised a storm of
protest last month when she declared that a U.S.-style European
union would be ``highly damaging'' to the individual states.
   Several European countries and Common Market organs charged that
her comments were a roadblock to a long-desired goal of unity.
   Against the backdrop of this debate, the Polish-born pope is
expected to elaborate on his own vision of Europe _ one united by
Christianity and stretching ``from the Atlantic to the Urals.''
   A Vatican official said the pope wanted to address the three
international institutions because they pondered the direction of
Europe.
   ``I think he (the pope) feels very strongly that in the process
of reflection on the future of Europe, the church's voice should be
there,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   John Paul has expounded on the theme several times.
   In Spain in 1982, John Paul called on Europe to return to the
Christian principles that tied it together as in medieval days.
``You can still be the beacon of civilization and stimulate
progress throughout the world,'' he said.
   In Austria the next year, he said Christianity had formed the
basis for political systems built on respect for human rights.
   The pope felt so strongly about a common European heritage that
he released an encyclical in 1985 honoring two ninth century saints
who brought Christianity to the Slavs. In John Paul's view, Saints
Cyril and Methodius forged a link between the Eastern Orthodox and
Western Roman Catholic traditions.
   ``Part of his reflection on the Christian roots of Europe is to
encourage a revival of Christianity,'' the Vatican official said.
   The pope has expressed particular concern about the church in
France. Although over 80 percent of French citizens are Roman
Catholics, less than 20 percent attend Mass, according to French
public opinion polls.
   This trip, the pope's fourth to France, will include visits to
the dioceses of Metz, Nancy and Mulhouse in the northeast near West
Germany.
   In addition, John Paul will salute Strasbourg on its 2,000th
birthday.
   The city, which changed hands between France and Germany for
centuries, has a blend of cultures that has attracted groups
promoting European unity.
   The Council of Europe, composed of 21 parliamentary democracies,
aims to coordinate European legislation through accords. The
European Court of Human Rights hears alleged violations of the
Council of Europe's main treaty, the European Convention of Human
Rights.
   The European Parliament is the parliamentary assembly of the
European Economic Community.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
