<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1544EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AssemblyLine     10-07 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Assembly Line,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>75th Anniversary of What Makes Industrial World Go 'Round</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYNE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventy-five years ago Friday, in a small
factory in Highland Park, Henry Ford put in motion an industrial
revolution. On that day, the first Model T moved through an
assembly line, towed by a rope.
   Although the technology has been updated, the assembly line
lives on.
   ``Indeed, what happened in Detroit transformed the entire nature
of the 20th century, perhaps more than any other development except
the atomic bomb,'' said David Hounshell, a history professor at the
University of Delaware.
   ``The revolution was the installation and elaboration of the
moving assembly line,'' he said Friday at a ceremony at Ford's
Wayne assembly plant, 20 miles from the factory where Henry Ford
made _ and history.
   Actually, use of an assembly line began a few months before Oct.
7, 1913, Hounshell said. Someone in Ford's flywheel-magneto
assembly area decided to keep workers stationary and the product
moving. The technique spread to other component operations.
   ``This was the granddaddy of all assembly lines, the line one
imagines when one hears the words `assembly line,''' Hounshell
said. ``Its success _ raising the productivity of final assembly _
was overwhelming.
   ``By the early 1920s, many household appliances such as vacuum
cleaners and even radios were assembled on an assembly line.''
   On Friday, another Model T rolled off an assembly line, this one
with Ford's great-grandson, Edsel Ford II, at the wheel.
   ``At Ford Motor Co., many of our goals today are the same as
they were in my great-grandfather's time _ to meet consumers' needs
by producing affordable, high-quality vehicles that represent good
value for the money,'' Ford said.
   Not all workers were enamored with the assembly line in late
1913. There was high employee turnover and talk of work stoppages _
until Henry Ford in 1914 announced he would pay workers the
then-incredible sum of $5 per day.
   Within a year, the winch-and-rope system that drew the first
Model T through the plant was replaced by a chain. With other
manufacturing improvements, production time continued to drop, as
did the cost of the vehicle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881007-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1532EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-UsedOil     10-07 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Used Oil,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Strikes Down EPA Policy on Labeling of Oil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Friday struck down
an Environmental Protection Agency policy not to list used oil
collected for recyling as hazardous waste.
   At issue was EPA's decision in 1986 that a hazardous-waste
designation would only create a stigma and discourage many
locations such as gasoline stations from collecting used oil for
recycling.
   But a three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
here said that factor cannot be taken into account, particularly
when EPA had already concluded that a broad category of used oils
were hazardous wastes.
   ``The EPA erroneously based its decision not to list recycled
oils as hazardous wastes on the stigmatic effects of such a
listing, a factor not permitted by the statute,'' the court said.
   It ordered EPA to determine if recycled oils ``meet the
technical criteria for listing'' as hazardous wastes.
   ``I would consider this a major victory'' to clean up ``billions
of gallons of used oil,'' said Jane L. Bloom, an attorney for the
Natural Resources Defense Council.
   She predicted that the court's decision will force EPA to
declare broad categories of used oil hazardous wastes because the
agency's own studies have documented that it contains many toxic
chemicals.
   ``The court's action should force EPA to stop the dumping of
waste oil into municipal landfills and lead to better treatment an
reclamation of the oil,'' said David R. Case, general counsel of
the Hazardous Waste Treatment Council.
   The decision ``means EPA should be more concerned about the
stigma of harm to the environment than the stigma of calling
recycled oil a hazardous waste,'' said Case, whose organization
represents large waste-disposal companies.
   Lisa Friedman, an EPA attorney, said the court ruling ``arguably
leaves a lot of discretion to the agency to determine whether
certain oils are hazardous.'' She said the agency was studying the
ruling and had not decided how to proceed.
   In 1985, EPA proposed to list a broad category of used
automotive and industrial oils as hazardous wastes. But it backed
off in 1986, after receiving nearly 800 comments from gasoline
dealers and other recyclers.
   The agency deferred any decision on used oil generally but
decided not to list oil collected for recycling as hazardous waste.
   ``The effect of listing would create such a stigma in the used
oil recycling industry that many recycling sources woudl simply
refuse to take used oil,'' Friedman said.
   EPA decided that ``the used oil might then be diverted to less
environmentally sound management options such as throwing it down
the sewer,'' she said.
   The appeals court said ``EPA's concern over the possible adverse
environmental consequences of listing used oil may well be
warranted,'' but such views ``cannot override the intent of
Congress clearly expressed in the language and structure of the
statute.''
   ``It is the agency's obligation to comply with the dictates of
Congress and ours to enforce them,'' a three-judge panel said in an
opinion by Circuit Judge James L. Buckley that was joined by Judges
Stephen Williams and Edward D. Re.
   Congress ``carefully separated the listing decision from the
resultant regulatory decisions,'' Buckley wrote, and a 1985 law
enacted to prod EPA to take action ``simply requires the agency to
determine whether to list used oil as hazardous.''
   ``Only after the EPA decides to list does the statute permit it
to consider the effect of its regulations on recycling,'' he wrote.
   The EPA estimates that 1.2 billion gallons of used oil is
produced annually, but only half is recycled, said Jacqueline
Warren, another attorney for the Natural Resources Defense Council.
   ``The laundry list of substances that have been found in used
oil is alarming,'' she said. These include benzene, PCB and heavy
metals such as lead, cadmium and chromium.
   In a separate opinion issued Friday, the appeals court panel
upheld EPA's rules governing the burning of hazardous waste and
used oil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
