<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BiotechExhibit     10-07 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biotech Exhibit,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disney Opens Biotech Lab for Education, Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mickey Mouse wore a lab coat and
glasses Friday as Disney World dedicated the first working
plant-biotechnology lab open to the public.
   The laboratory will research and produce plants through genetic
engineering and tissue culture.
   Tourists on the boat ride through Epcot Center's Land Pavilion
will be able to observe technicians working to develop new plant
varieties and improve food crops to speed growth, increase yields
and become pest- and drought-resistant.
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture donated the equipment used in
the lab, which was financed by Kraft Inc., sponsor of the Land
Pavilion.
   ``It's a splendid educational effort,'' said Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng, who participated in dedication ceremonies.
   ``This is a small lab, an exhibit. ... We don't want to
overemphasize its importance, but it is on the cutting edge of
biotechnology and the value is in people getting a chance to see''
work carried out in this important field, Lyng said.
   Up to 25,000 people a day go through the Land Pavilion and most
take the ride that circles the lab.
   Others, such as students or workers in the field, can request a
more specialized tour through it, said Henry Robitaille,
agricultural systems manager for the pavilion.
