<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-Candidates     10-07 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Candidates,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Potential Presidential Candidates Rose Before Pinochet's Coup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veteran politicians who rose to
prominence before Gen. Augusto Pinochet seized power 15 years ago
dominate the field of potential candidates for a presidential
election next year.
   In the opposition, which includes parties from the left to the
center-right, a few younger leaders who made important
contributions to the fight against the authoritarian president also
are among possible nominees.
   Pinochet, 72, would be the top contender on the right if he
decides to run. The constitution allows him to be a candidate, but
he has not announced his plans.
   On Wednesday, Chileans voted in a referendum to reject
Pinochet's bid to extend his rule until 1997, clearing the way for
an election in December 1989.
   Patricio Aylwin and Ricardo Lagos, moderate politicians who led
the opposition campaign for the referendum, are the strongest
contenders in the opposition.
   Aylwin, president of the centrist Christian Democratic party,
the country's largest, is a seasoned politican and former senator
who played a key role in the tumultuous days before the 1973 coup
in which Pinochet toppled the elected government of Salvador
Allende.
   Aylwin was the main spokesman for the 16-party coalition that
campaigned against Pinochet in the referendum, and he received more
publicity than most of his peers. In a massively attended final
campaign rally, he delivered a forceful and eloquent speech that
showed his oratory skills.
   Aylwin, a 67-year-old law professor, is more widely accepted by
conservative sectors than Lagos and other prominent opposition
leaders.
   Lagos, 50, a moderate socialist economist and lawyer, is a
relative newcomer to politics. He was catapulted to national
prominence by his dramatic performance in a campaign television
debate.
   In the debate, the charismatic, tough-talking Lagos challenged
Pinochet personally, staring into the camera and shaking his
finger. Never before during Pinochet's rule had television shown
such a scene.
   But many consider Lagos' socialist ideas and his connections
with the Allende government offensive to center-right groups in the
opposition. Lagos was a middle-ranking official for the Allende
administration.
   Aylwin and Lagos have denied any presidential ambitions and said
the opposition needs an all-out effort to agree on a single
candidate to lead a ``government of national unity'' after Pinochet.
   ``It's too early to talk about candidates,'' Aylwin said
Thursday in his first news conference after the opposition victory.
   Lagos, asked Friday about his possible presidential candidacy,
replied: ``Is there going to be an election now? As far as I know,
Augusto Pinochet is still pretty much alive and well.''
   Many observers think Aylwin would have a better chance at
nomination, especially if the opposition succeeds with plans to
create a four-year transition government. Lagos' comparative youth
gives him the option of waiting until a later election.
   Other dissident figures mentioned as potential candidates
include Christian Democrats Gabriel Valdes, 66, and Andres
Zaldivar, 52. Both held Cabinet posts in the government of former
president Eduardo Frei in the 1960s, but they gained additional
prominence in the years of opposition to Pinochet.
   The only civilian with prominence anywhere near Pinochet's is
Sergio Onofre Jarpa, a 67-year-old landowner and former senator
with a reputation of being as fiercily anti-communist as Pinochet.
   Few doubt that Pinochet himself could be nominated. Despite his
defeat in the referendum, he still won 43 percent of the vote.
   ``He is the most important political figure in the country,''
said Interior Minister Sergio Fernandez. ``Few leaders in the world
would be able to get such an extrordinary vote after 15 years in
power.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
