<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     10-07 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10,000 March On Montenegro's Parliament; Gov't Promises Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 10,000 people chanting ``You
betrayed the people!'' demanded the resignation of local Communist
Party leaders Friday in a march on a Yugoslav republic's
parliament, Belgrade radio reported.
   In Belgrade, the ruling Politburo issued a statement promising
high-level personnel changes and the introduction of radical
market-oriented economic reform in an effort to stem three months
of unrest over economic and ethnic issues.
   The street rally in Titograd, in the republic of Montenegro,
began after 1,000 construction workers stopped work to protest low
wages and falling living standards, the radio report said. About
10,000 protesters then marched to the legislature, the radio said.
   Demonstrations also broke out in Belgrade and in the city of
Krusevac, the radio said.
   The protests came a day after an estimated 30,000 protesters
stormed a Communist Party headquarters and forced the resignation
of party leaders in the autonomous province of Vojvodina, in the
Serbian republic.
   Serbian nationalists have led most recent protests, but the
rallies are driven also by an economic crisis that has inflation at
217 percent, the foreign debt at $21 billion and unemployment at 15
percent.
   Friday's statement by the Politburo promised ``to make necessary
personnel changes'' in an Oct. 17 meeting of the policy-setting
Central Committee ``which should contribute to the more efficient
work of that organ.''
   The statement, carried by the official Tanjug news agency, also
called for the introduction of a radical market-oriented economic
reform next year.
   In a recent interview, Premier Branko Mikulic mentioned a major
reform of Yugoslavia's mixed economy. The reform, scheduled to be
adopted Nov. 29 in Parliament, will introduce more private
businesses, allow majority foreign ownership of businesses and
close or sell off money-losing state companies.
   The statement also promised a major reduction in government but
did not elaborate.
   In Krusevac, 90 miles south of Belgrade, several thousand
workers demonstrated to demand higher wages and the ouster of
Communist leaders, the radio said.
   In Belgrade, 400 high school students from Kosovo marched on the
national Parliament, chanting that the mainly Christian Serbs will
never give up power in Kosovo, an autonomous province bordering
Albania.
   Mainly Moslem ethnic Albanians now make up 90 percent of
Kosovo's population.
   The teen-agers, joined by Belgrade students, protested alleged
harassment by Albanians. They were met at Parliament by Vice
President Spasoje Medenica, who listened to their grievances before
they dispersed, Tanjug said.
   Several dozen Communist party leaders have been attacked by name
in recent rallies by Serbs.
   After the resignation of Vojvodina province's 15 Politburo
members, the largely Albanian Communist party leadership in Kosovo
is expected to come under pressure to make sweeping changes at a
meeting it holds Oct. 13.
   The resignations in Vojvodina were a major victory for Serbian
Communist Party leader Slobodan Milosevic, who wants more control
over the two provinces.
   The Serbian leader's opponents suspect he is using the mass
rallies to gain more national power for himself and for Serbia, the
largest of Yugoslavia's six republics.
   Many Serbs see Milosevic as political heir to the late President
Josip Broz Tito, who died in 1980 and left the nation with a
complex system of annual rotation in the occupants of top political
offices.
   Milosevic's advance alarms many politicians in Yugoslavia's
other republics.
</TEXT>
