<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HasenfusSuit     10-07 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hasenfus Suit,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Crash Victim Sues Secord, Hakim, Southern Air</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mercenary shot down in Nicaragua flying supplies
to the Contras is suing Iran-Contra figures Richard Secord and
Albert Hakim for $135 million, saying they misled the crew and
abandoned him during three months of captivity.
   Eugene Hasenfus of Marinette, Wis., also sued Southern Air
Transport, a shadowy, CIA-linked cargo airline, and Corporate Air
Services, which he identified as a shell company owned by Southern
Air and controlled by Secord and Hakim.
   Southern Air spokesman Jack Thale denied Friday any connection
with Hasenfus. The suit claimed the company paid his expenses.
   Hasenfus filed a similar suit in Washington federal court in
May, but jurisdiction questions are pending there because the
planes allegedly flew out of Miami, where Southern Air and
Corporate Air are based.
   Hasenfus' plane was shot down over Nicaragua in 1986. He
parachuted to safety, but three crewmen died. Hasenfus was tried by
the Sandinistas and sentenced to 30 years in prison, then sent back
to the United States after three months.
   Hasenfus and his wife, Sally, said they were told the supply
operation was a patriotic mission, but later found out Secord and
Hakim were profiting from the deal.
   He also said Secord, Hakim and the State Department promised
help when he was captured, but never delivered.
   ``This guy was captured by the Sandinistas,'' said Secord's
attorney, Thomas C. Green. ``What did he expect, that the U.S.
military would step in and save him?''
   The suit, filed Tuesday in federal court, says that Hasenfus was
recruited in 1986 through Corporate Air and William Cooper, a
Southern Air pilot.
   Cooper, who later died in the crash, led Hasenfus to believe
``the Contra resupply operation was being run `right out of the
back door of the White House''' by Oliver North, Secord, Hakim and
Southern Air, the suit said.
   Hakim and Secord, a retired Air Force major general, are accused
with former National Security Council figures Oliver North and John
Poindexter of conspiring to defraud the government by diverting
proceeds from Iran arms sales to the Contras at a time when
Congress banned U.S. military aid to the rebels.
   Thale denied any relationship between Southern Air and Corporate
Air, although Federal Aviation Administration records in 1986
listed them at the same address.
</TEXT>
