<DOCNO> AP881007-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1708EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Kurds     10-07 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Kurds,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kurds Return To Iraq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 501 Kurdish refugees returned
to Iraq voluntarily on Friday, two months after they fled and
claimed that Iraqi forces dropped chemical bombs on their
settlements.
   Regional Gov. Hayri Kozakcioglu said in a telephone interview
that the Kurdish refugees, the second group to return, were
transferred to Iraq from a southeastern border post in Habur.
   A group of 969 Kurdish refugees returned to Iraq on Wednesday.
   The two groups were among 60,000 Kurds who were settled in five
tent cities in southeastern Turkey in August after they left Iraq.
   At the urging of Turkey, Iraq proclaimed an amnesty for the
Kurds. Before the first group returned, only two Kurds had taken
advantage of the amnesty.
   The second group of Kurds was granted special status because the
amnesty expired Thursday night, a Turkish government official said
on condition of anonymity.
   Kozakcioglu said some of the refugees at Diyarbakir tent city
threw stones at the returnees Friday and tried to keep them from
leaving. He said they called the returnees traitors and ``spies of
the Iraqi regime.''
   Police fired in the air and firefighters shot water to disperse
the crowd. Kozakcioglu said two policemen and four Kurds were
slightly injured.
   The Kurds traveled for 20 hours on buses and open trucks to the
border. The government said Iraq gave assurances that the refugees
would be safely settled in their villages.
   Turkey initially asked the International Red Cross to supervise
the return, but the Red Cross declined after Iraq refused to grant
its request for further guarantees on behalf of the refugees.
   The Kurds, 20 million people living in a region where borders of
Turkey, Iran and Iraq converge, have been fighting for independence
for the past century.
   Iraq stepped up attacks on the Kurds soon after Iran agreed to a
cease-fire in their eight-year war on Aug. 20.
   Security forces in the southeastern township of Uludere killed
two Kurdish guerrillas in a clash, the regional governor's office
said.
   The statement, carried by the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency, said authorities told rebels to surrender and the
guerrillas opened fire on Thursday. It said one guerrilla was
captured.
   The suspects were responsible for killing a policeman and a
village guard and wounding three soldiers in three different
attacks.
   The guerrillas were believed to be members of the outlawed
Kurdish Labor Party, which wants to set up a Marxist state in parts
of eastern and southeastern Turkey.
   More than 900 civilians and security personnel and an equal
number of insurgents have been killed since the rebels started
hit-and-run attacks in 1984, official reports say.
   Kurds make up about one-fifth of Turkey's population of 52
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
