<2ND_LINE>AM-Myerson Trial,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Myerson Trial: Law Clerk's Testimony Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge accused in a scheme by former Miss
America Bess Myerson to fix her lover's divorce took an unusual
personal interest in the case, even after it moved to a higher
court, a witness said Friday.
   In testimony at the trial of Miss Myerson; her lover, Carl
``Andy'' Capasso, and state Supreme Court Justice Hortense Gabel,
Mrs. Gabel's former law secretary detailed how the judge deviated
from her routine in handling Capasso's divorce. Supreme Court is
New York State's trial-level court.
   But under cross examination, the former law secretary, Howard
Leventhal, conceded that while he disagreed with his boss's
handling of the Capasso case, determining support payments is ``an
art not a science.''
   Mrs. Gabel is accused of cutting Capasso's support payments to
his estranged wife, Nancy, in 1983, in exchange for Miss Myerson
giving a city job to the judge's daughter. Miss Myerson at the time
was city cultural affairs commissioner.
   When Mrs. Capasso appealed Mrs. Gabel's ruling, Leventhal said
the judge asked him to obtain copies of the appeal documents some
time before the higher court ruled. The appeals court restored the
higher payments.
   Leventhal testified that it was the first time Mrs. Gabel made
such a request even though hundreds of her decisions were appealed
during the six years he worked for her.
   Previously, Leventhal testified that in June 1983 Mrs. Gabel
ordered Capasso to pay his wife $1,850 a week but reduced that to
$680 a week in September.
   During that summer, said Leventhal, Miss Myerson _ often using
an alias _ called Mrs. Gabel many times on a private line in the
judge's chambers.
   He also said Mrs. Gabel personally drafted her ruling in the
Capasso case, one of the few times she did so in 3,700 court
motions.
</TEXT>
