<HEAD>Jewish Businessman Willing to Talk to Bakkers About Heritage
Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN_</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer_</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stephen J. Mernick, the Orthodox Jewish
businessman who wants to purchase the assets of the PTL Christian
ministry, said Friday he is keeping all options open about their
future use.
   He said he is willing to talk to Jim and Tammy Bakker about
their possible activities at Heritage USA, a Christian retreat and
theme park in York County, S.C., and the other assets to be
purchased for $115 million.
   ``I have made no decision whatsoever as to the utilization of
the Heritage assets,'' Mernick, 34, said at a news conference at
his lawyer's office in the Toronto suburb of North York.
   ``Over the next several weeks I will be engaged in an intensive
analysis of the property in order to determine their best possible
use from a business and financial standpoint,'' he said.
   Mernick said he was interested primarily in the assets for their
real estate potential _ especially the 1,700 undeveloped acres
adjacent to the 500-acre Heritage park.
   He did not rule out negotiating with the Bakkers about their
lease of any of the properties or the satellite television
facilities.
   ``I'm a very open-minded person. I'm prepared to speak to them
and anyone,'' Mernick said.
   Bakker stepped down as leader of PTL after admitting to a sexual
encounter in March 1987 but has since been trying to regain control
of the ministry.
   Mernick clarified in an opening statement that he was purchasing
only the fixed assets from the trustee in bankruptcy and not the
Heritage church itself.
   ``It is my understanding that the Heritage Church has been set
up as a separate and distinct organization which leases certain of
the facilities at Heritage USA on a month-to-month basis,'' he said.
   Mernick said he believed the 1,700 undeveloped acres have
excellent potential for condominiums, retail and office development.
   He also said a motion was filed Friday morning with the
bankruptcy court seeking approval of the purchase contract and all
deposits have been paid to the escrow agent as outlined.
   Mernick's family has roots in Toronto real estate that go back
40 years, but he was little known outside the area's Orthodox
Jewish community until March when he purchased the old Firestone
Canada Inc. tire plant in Hamilton, Ont.
   Mernick released a summary saying that in addition to the
Firestone property he owns 270 acres for mixed use development in
New York's Westchester County and about 900 acres in Ontario.
   Among his other interests are a landfill site in the Toronto
area, a 50 percent interest in a local waste disposal and recycling
company and wholesale and retail travel agencies.
   PTL stands for ``Praise The Lord,'' or ``People That Love.''
</TEXT>
