<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DesertCrash     10-07 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Desert Crash,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Bails Out Safely As Chase Jet Crashes During NASA Research
Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BORON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An experimental NASA jet crashed in the
Mojave Desert while serving as a chase plane for a research flight
Friday, but the pilot ejected safely, a spokeswoman said.
   Stephen Ishmael, 39, ``was out waving before the helicopter
picked him up'' from the crash site near here, said Nancy Lovato, a
NASA spokeswoman at Edwards Air Force Base. ``He's been checked by
a flight surgeon and he's fine.''
   Cheryl Sorensen, a dispatcher for Kern County Fire Department,
said her agency provided some type of medical aid and extinguished
a grass fire caused by the crash.
   Lovato said Ishmael was piloting a modified F-A-18 chase plane
as a safety measure. He was following another F-A-18 conducting a
research flight when he ``experienced problems with the airplane's
control system'' and bailed out, she said.
   The Navy uses similar F-18 jets as fighter-attack aircraft, but
NASA is using the modified F-A-18s in a ``high angle of attack''
program aimed at designing highly maneuverable jets, she said.
   Lovato said the F-A-18, made by McDonnell Douglas Corp., wasn't
being flown at a high angle of attack, a measurement of wing angle
relative to air flow, when Ishmael encountered trouble.
   Ishmael is chief pilot for NASA's research program on the X-29,
a jet that has its wings swept forward instead of backward as on
conventional aircraft.
   Both F-A-18s had taken off from Edwards Air Force Base. Boron is
about 10 miles east of the base and about 125 miles northeast of
Los Angeles.
   NASA spokesman Ralph Jackson said Navy F-18s cost roughly $20
million to $25 million, but the prototype F-A-18 that crashed was
worth about $5 million.
</TEXT>
