<2ND_LINE>AM-Harvey Trial,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>James Harvey Pleads Guilty In School Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clutching a Bible and wiping his eyes, a
distraught James L. Harvey was sentenced Friday to life in prison
plus 20 years for taking hostage 110 children and adults at a
church school in Tuscaloosa.
   Harvey, at the encouragement of his sisters, pleaded guilty to
six counts of kidnapping in the Feb. 2 takeover of West End
Christian School.
   Circuit Judge John M. Karrh, who moved the trial to Huntsville
because of publicity in Tuscaloosa, also recommended Harvey get
psychiatric help.
   Harvey, whose guilty plea cut short his trial after three days,
had maintained during the 12-hour siege that he was exercising his
right to bear arms and was making a statement for the nation's
homeless, poor and illiterate.
   The 43-year-old man, who had defended himself during the trial,
sat at the defense table and cried as he signed a form that said he
understood his rights.
   Gov. Guy Hunt was scheduled to testify Friday. Harvey had
summoned him as a defense witness because the governor's videotape
of a bogus pardon had persuaded Harvey to put aside his three guns
and end the takeover.
   Harvey had been charged with 110 counts of kidnapping, which
carried a maximum sentence of up to 10,000 years. The charges were
combined into six counts.
   ``He is mentally and physically exhausted,'' said an older
sister, Martha Gray. ``I've thought all along that he needed mental
help. I love him and I want him well. He's a very frightened boy.''
   Another man, John Rhodes Jr., also was charged in the takeover
but was freed after authorities determined that Harvey had tricked
him into helping.
