<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Shoreham 1stLd-Writethru a0680 10-07 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shoreham, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Overturns Licensing Board Ruling on NY Nuke Plant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs of detail on ruling after 4th graf, ``Thus,
the;'' subs pvs 7th graf, ``Francis Sheehan,'' to update with Cuomo
no-comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Atomic Safety and Licensing Appeal Board
vacated on Friday another Nuclear Regulatory Commission panel's
decision to go forward with a full-power license for the Shoreham
nuclear power plant on Long Island, N.Y.
   The appeal board found that the Atomic Safety and Licensing
Board did not have the authority to remove state and local
governments as intevenors in a case before a different panel, said
NRC spokesman John Kopeck.
   Friday's ruling ``reverses that and at the same time, says all
outstanding emergency planning issues have not been resolved,''
Kopeck said.
   ``Thus, the full-power license authorization does not exist and
that authorization must be vacated,'' he said.
   In a 20-page decision, the three-judge appeals panel agreed with
Shoreham's owners that the state and local governments had
``obstructed the discovery process and failed to obey certain
(licensing) board orders ... and that the only appropriate sanction
is dismissal ....''
   However, the licensing board only had authority to dismiss the
governments in the case it was hearing, according to the appeals
board.
   Jim Lois, a spokesman for the Long Island Lighting Co., which
owns the embattled $5.3 billion plant, said the company will fight
Friday's ruling.
   ``Today's decision by the appeals board did not overrule the ...
licensing board decision on the merits of emergency planning, nor
did the appeals court overrule the findings that the intervening
New York governments had indeed acted willfully and in bad faith by
obstructing the judicial process,'' Lois said. ``We will appeal
today's decision directly to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.''
   Francis Sheehan, a spokesman for New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, said
the governor was studying the decision and would have no immediate
comment.
   The Atomic Safety and Licensing Board, in a ruling Sept. 23,
elimiminated New York state, Suffolk County and the Town of
Southampton as intervenors in a case involving an emergency
evacuation drill conducted earlier this year. The panel also found
that there was reasonable assurance that the public's safety could
be protected in the event of an accident at the reactor.
   By a 2-1 decision, the panel agreed with Long Island Lighting's
argument that ``realism'' dictated that in case of an actual
accident, state and local authorities would, in fact, cooperate
with emergency measures planned by the company even if they didn't
have their own plan.
   Current federal regulation prevents the NRC from issuing a
full-power license to a nuclear plant unless there is an emergency
plan that gives reasonable assurance the public will be safe if an
accident occurs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
