<HEAD>Second Dukakis-Bush Debate Set for Next Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf bgng, `The commission,' to FIX name of
auditorium to Shrine Auditorium</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second debate between presidential
candidates Michael Dukakis and George Bush will take place next
week in Los Angeles, a spokesman for the Commission on Presidential
Debates said Friday.
   Robert Neuman, director of media arrangements for the
commission, said the 90-minute debate will take place in Pauley
Pavilion on the campus of UCLA.
   The status of the second and final debate between Democrat
Dukakis and Republican Bush was thrown into question last week when
the original sponsor, the League of Women Voters, abruptly
withdrew, complaining that the two candidates' campaigns were
insisting on making all important decisions.
   The commission, which sponsored the first debate, took over
sponsorship, but could not reach agreement with the League to
obtain use of Shrine Auditorium which was to have been the site.
   Neuman said final arrangements still were being made between the
commission, the university and the city.
   The debate will be Thursday or Friday, depending on whether the
American League baseball play-offs go to a seventh game.
   Neuman said the debate would begin at 9 p.m. EDT and would
follow the format of the first debate in which the candidates
responded to questions from a panel of four reporters.
   The first debate was Sept. 25, in Winston-Salem, N.C., on the
campus of Wake Forest University.
   Vice presidential nominees Lloyd Bentsen and Dan Quayle debated
Oct. 5, in Omaha, Neb.
</TEXT>
