<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-07 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fair Weather Over Middle of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fair weather settled over the middle of the nation Friday, and
cooler air was expected overnight in the middle Atlantic states and
the Ohio Valley, with frost warnings in the Carolinas.
   Temperatures were in the 50s and 60s over much of the Plains
states, the Great Lakes, the Mississippi and Ohio valleys and the
Atlantic coast. The pleasant temperatures were a result of an area
of high pressure that stretched from the middle Mississippi Valley
to New England.
   Readings were in the 70s over the southern half of Texas, the
Gulf Coast, the northern third of Florida and inland valleys of
California.
   In south central Texas, the southern two-thirds of Florida and
the desert Southwest, temperatures were in the 80s.
   In Arkansas, minor flooding of agricultural lowlands continued
along the Cache and St. Francis rivers.
   Rainshowers and fog continued over Oklahoma and western
Arkansas. Rainfall was generally light.
   Unstable air and an upper air disturbance were producing
rainshowers over the lower Great Lakes. The rain-cooled air was
holding temperatures in the 40s. Showers were also scattered over
eastern Virginia and eastern North Carolina.
   The northern Pacific Coast had temperatures in the 50s and was
shrouded by fog and drizzle.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms were widely scattered over
northern New Mexico.
   Cool air was expected overnight in the mid-Atlantic states and
the Ohio Valley. A frost warning was posted for middle and
northwest South Carolina. Frost and freeze warnings were in effect
for the mountain regions of North Carolina.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees at Bradford, Pa., to 93 degrees at Phoenix; Yuma, Ariz.;
and Williams Air Force Base in Chandler, Ariz.
   The low in the nation Friday was 21 degrees at Houlton, Maine,
and West Yellowstone, Mont.
   The National Weather Service forecast for Saturday called for
rainshowers over New England and New York state. Showers were to be
scattered over southern parts of Oklahoma. An upper air disturbance
was to produce cloudy skies over the upper Great Lakes and the
upper Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were to be in the 40s over the eastern half of
New England. A dome of high pressure was expected to keep
temperatures in the 50s over the middle Atlantic Coast, the central
and northern Appalachians, the upper Ohio Valley and the Great
Lakes.
   Readings were to reach the 80s over the south half of the
Florida peninsula, south central and southwest Texas, southern
parts of the Southern Plateau, the Great Basin, southern Idaho,
most of inland California and Oregon. Highs were expected between
90 and 105 degrees over the desert Southwest and the inland desert
valleys of California. The remainder of the nation was to have
highs in the 60s and 70s.
</TEXT>
