<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0691 10-07 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0691,800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``Dukakis adviser
...'' to UPDATE with Bush reaction.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WELLSTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis attacked the Republicans
Friday for standing by while foreigners are ``buying up America,''
but he mistakenly told workers at a plant owned by Italians that
they were ``survivors'' in the international trade battles.
   The Democratic presidential nominee used the Moog Automotive Co.
plant as the backdrop for a speech blasting GOP vice presidential
candidate Dan Quayle's statement Wednesday that he welcomed foreign
investment in U.S. factories, business and real estate.
   ``If anyone asks you what's at stake in this election, just
remind them of that moment in the debate Wednesday night when Sen.
Quayle said he's happy that foreign owners are buying up America,''
Dukakis said.
   ``Maybe the Republican ticket wants our children to work for
foreign owners, pay rent to foreign owners, and owe their future to
foreign owners _ but that's not the kind of future Lloyd Bentsen
and I and (Missouri Rep.) Dick Gephardt want for America,'' he
continued.
   Dukakis' comments caused one executive at the plant to ask
another whether the Democratic presidential candidate realized who
the plant's owners were.
   The Moog family sold the company more than 10 years ago to IFINT
USA, the American subsidiary of IFI of Turin, Italy. IFI is owned
by the Agnelli family, which also owns the automaker Fiat.
   Dukakis adviser Kirk O'Donnell said that officials at the
campaign headquarters were aware of the ownership prior to the
event. Another adviser, Thomas Herman, said that Dukakis himself
was not aware of the company's Italian owners.
   The Bush campaign took delight in what spokesman Mark Goodin
called Dukakis' gaffe.
   ``It occurs to me that that tank ride he took a few weeks ago
may have done more damage than I first suspected, even with his
protective head gear,'' Goodin said, referring to Dukakis' ride in
an army tank during a campaign visit to a defense plant.
   ``The bottom line is America is competing better overseas, we
are opening access to foreign markets, we are better controlling
the foreign trade deficit while the U.S. economy continues to
expand. As usual, the governor is out in left field somewhere,''
Goodin said.
   O'Donnell, Herman and other Dukakis aides moved quickly in an
effort to convince reporters that Dukakis was not criticizing Moog
or its owners but was opposed to the growing ``trend'' of foreign
investment in the United States.
   ``If you're going to talk about foreign invesment, that's the
kind of place to do it,'' O'Donnell said.
   But in his speech, Dukakis referred to the company as one of the
``few survivors'' of the auto parts industry's battle with foreign
competitors.
   ``Here at Moog Automotive, you know as well as anyone that
American businesses and American products and American jobs are
fighting for survival in the world marketplace,'' Dukakis said in
the speech. ``Whether or not we win that battle will determine
whether our children and grandchildren and generations to come
continue to enjoy an American standard of living.''
   Dukakis then departed from the text of his speech to tell the
workers he realized that they understood that message, telling the
workers, ``You are one of the few survivors.''
   O'Donnell said that Dukakis was not outrightly opposed to
foreign investment in the United States and noted that the company
had American management and was an exporter.
   In the speech, Dukakis told the union workers that Quayle is
``happy to hand a `For Sale' sign on America'' and that Bush ``has
spent the last eight years with a `Do Not Disturb' sign on his
office door.''
   In constrast, Dukakis said he and running mate Lloyd Bentsen
work aggressively to win access for U.S. products to foreign
markets and would offer protection to certain American industries
provided those companies agreed to modernize their plants and
retrain their workers to become more competitive.
   Dukakis denounced Reagan administration officials he said had
sought foreign help in fighting the recently passed trade bill and
also chided a former Reagan administration official who was seeking
a loobying job with Japanese auto parts manufactuers at the same
time he was representing the United States in trade negotiations
with Japanese auto parts makers.
   ``While (Bush has) been a summer soldier in the battle for
America's economic future, some of his colleagues in this
adminstration have been trying to enlist on the other side,''
Dukakis said. ``In a Dukakis White House, my friends, we're going
to fight for America's economic future. And we'll pledge allegiance
to only one flag _ Old Glory.''
   From Missouri, Dukakis was headed to North Carolina, another key
swing state where the Democratic ticket believes it has a good
chance to defeat Bush and Quayle. On Saturday the Massachusetts
governor was campaigning in Maine.
</TEXT>
