<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Greece-SpyTrial     10-07 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Spy Trial,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Acquits Greek Who Admits Giving Stinger Details to Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A felony court acquitted a Greek
businessman of espionage Friday, although he admitted giving
details of the U.S.-built Stinger anti-aircraft missile to the
Soviet Union.
   The three-member court said Michalis Megaloconomou was innocent
on the ground the material handed over was not secret.
   ``Megaloconomou took unclassified materials for a well-known
weapons system. The Soviet Union wasn't going to build anything
from material it already had obtained from other people,''
Prosecutor Constantinos Androulikakis said in his summing up.
   The 40-year-old businessman told the court he gave 400
microfiche cards to a Soviet intelligence agent in April 1984 but
didn't know they contained information on the shoulder-fired
Stinger's trigger system.
   ``I thought they contained information on a telephone system,''
he said.
   Megaloconomou also told the court he traveled to the Soviet
Union in 1984 on a false passport and was given a miniature camera,
decoding pads and a radio receiver by a Soviet agent.
   The case was linked with the May 1985 defection in Athens of
Soviet agent Sergei Bokhane, whose revelations cast doubts on
Greece's capacity to safeguard NATO secrets and delayed the sale of
40 U.S.-made jet fighters to Greece.
   Brig. Ioannis Alexakis, a former head of counter-intelligence
for the Greek Central Intelligence Service, told the court
Wednesday Megaloconomou had been a Soviet spy for 10 years when he
was arrested in September 1985.
   But the prosecutor, addressing only the Stinger case, said, ``We
can't say he gave secrets to a foreign power and endangered the
security of Greece or its allies. Espionage is taking state secrets
with the intent of harming the nation.''
   Megaloconomou is a former deputy director at Standard Electric
Hellas, or SEH, a Greek company affiliated with the American
International Telephone & Telegraph Corp., ITT.
   Also acquitted were two SEH employees, commercial director
Constantinos Libousakis and secretary Artmenis Tzirozidou, who were
tried on misdemeanor charges in the same court for violating state
secrets through negligence.
   SEH was among firms in six Western European countries that
manufactured Stinger components under license.
   Megaloconomou was arrested on the basis of information given to
the American CIA by Bokhane, who served as deputy head of the
Soviet Military Intelligence Agency, GRU, in Athens.
   Bokhane said Megaloconomou was recruited by the GRU in 1975 and
began selling them information in 1977, according to Alexakis.
   In a 1986 trial, a Greek navy officer and a Greek businessman
accused of selling information and telecommunications equipment to
Moscow were acquitted on the ground that Greek intelligence
services couldn't confirm Bokhane's allegations.
   The United States delayed approving the sale of the F-16
jetfighters to Greece until Premier Andreas Papandreou's socialist
government signed an agreement in 1986 pledging to prevent advanced
Western technology from reaching the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881007-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1842EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea-Trade 1stLd-Writethru a0591 10-07 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0591,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea Calls For Trade With North Korea</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS name in 2d graf to Rha sted Rah</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea on Friday urged North
Korea to begin trade and said it would drop trade barriers to
promote ties with its communist rival.
   If North Korea agrees, the trade will be treated as domestic
commerce with no tariffs, Rha Woong-bae, the deputy prime minister
and economic planning minister, told a news conference. He said the
trade will not include military products.
   Rha, South Korea's top economic official, called for a quick
start to trade both directly and through third nations. He also
called for talks on working out details of the commerce, which he
said would benefit both sides.
   South Korea, a U.S. ally, has improved its trade and other
relations with other communist nations, such as China.
   Rha listed coal, iron ore and corn as probable import items from
North Korea, and steel and textiles as likely South Korean exports
to the North.
   Any trade, either direct or through third nations, would depend
on North Korean consent. There are no indications the North would
accept trade with the South, and past efforts at improving
relations have had little success.
   The countries do not have any contacts or ties beyond a single
hotline. The border is sealed and both nations have been locked in
a bitter confrontation for 40 years.
   President Roh Tae-woo this week called for a major effort to end
the confrontation and work toward reunifying the Korean Peninsula.
Radical students have held violent demonstrations to press demands
for reunification.
   The countries were split at the end of World War II. North Korea
invaded the South in 1950 to start the Korean War, which ended with
an armistice in 1953. Talks on improving relations are to resume
Oct. 13 after deadlocking in August.
   The sides held five rounds of talks on economic cooperation in
1985, but the North stopped contacts in January 1986 to protest
U.S.-South Korean military training exercises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
