<DOCNO> AP881007-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1942EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WNBCGoodbye 2ndLd-Writethru a0641 10-07 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WNBC Goodbye, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0641,0671</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WNBC Signs Off after 62 Years on the Air</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY47</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 3rd graf pvs, `WNBC was...political
convention.' to UPDATE with signing off. Picks up 4th graf pvs,
`The end...'. INSERTS one graf after 7th graf pvs, `Emmis
decided...of 1050.' to UPDATE with new station broadcasting. Picks
up 8th graf pvs, `About 50...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICH MENDELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friday was the last day on the air for radio
station WNBC, for 62 years the flagship of the NBC radio network
that was home to Jack Benny, Bob Hope, Fred Allen and the NBC
Symphony conducted by Arturo Toscanini.
   Its spot at 660 on the AM dial, a clear-channel signal that
could be picked up in as many as 35 states at night, is going to an
all-sports station.
   WNBC was descended from the station that was the first to
broadcast a World Series, the first to run a commercial, the first
with a coast-to-coast hookup and the first to broadcast a national
political convention.
   At the end of the show, everyone in the studio counted down from
10, but the power was turned off before NBC's distinctive
three-gong chime could sound for the last time. The switch was
thrown at 5:30 p.m.
   The end of an era came as a result of the $6 billion deal in
1985 in which General Electric Co. bought RCA Corp., the NBC's
parent company.
   A Federal Communications Commission regulation prevents a new
owner from keeping both a TV and radio station in the same market,
so GE decided to sell its new radio properties and keep the more
profitable WNBC-TV.
   The NBC radio network went to Westwood One for $55 million, and
five stations, including WNBC, were sold to Emmis Broadcasting
Corp. for $121.5 million. GE has one station left, KNBR in San
Francisco, which is for sale.
   Emmis decided to ditch WNBC's call letters and format and move
in its WFAN, a local all-sports station that held the less
desirable frequency of 1050.
   The new station signed on from its studios in Queens at 5:30
p.m., with the words, ``Sports radio 66 W-F-A-N.''
   About 50 WNBC employees, including its on-air personalities,
have known since February they would be out of jobs, but none
jumped ship ahead of time, said general manager Peg Kelly.
   ``People sort of want to be here for the end,'' she said. ``No
one's thrilled about it; no one even likes it. But it's kind of a
piece of history, and people want to be here for it.''
   WNBC said goodbye with a 90-minute retrospective program Friday
featuring clips from programs with Benny, Hope, Allen and Fibber
McGee and Molly.
   NBC also had such classic shows as ``Amos 'n' Andy,'' ``Your Hit
Parade'' and ``Information, Please.'' There were also the original
soap operas, like ``Ma Perkins'' and ``Mary Noble, Backstage Wife.''
   The station, then owned by AT&T, went on the air in April 1922
as W2XY. It became WBAY in July that year and was changed to WEAF
the next month.
   RCA bought the station from AT&T for $1 million in 1926 when it
formed NBC to help sell the radios it was making, but it didn't
change the call letters to WNBC until 1946.
   The first radio commercial was broadcast on WEAF on Aug. 28,
1922, when a real estate developer paid $100 for a 10-minute
announcement to advertise apartments.
   ``Up to that point radio was for experimenters and people were
still thinking of ways to make money with it,'' said WNBC program
director Dale Parsons, one of those losing a job.
   WEAF's other firsts included the first World Series broadcast,
Yankees vs. Giants, in 1923; the first coast-to-coast hookup, in
1924, and the first broadcast of the national political
conventions, in 1924. In 1925, it broadcast a presidential
inaugural address _ Calvin Coolidge's _ for the first time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
