<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0692 10-07 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0692,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Defends Quayle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs bgng, `Late Friday,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with additional Reagan quotes on Quayle; INSERTS 3 grafs after 10th
graf pvs bgng, `And you,' to UPDATE with man disrupting Reagan
appearance</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan came to Dan Quayle's defense on
Friday, portraying the embattled vice presidential candidate as a
man who shares Reagan's conservative beliefs and should help carry
on his policies.
   In a series of speeches designed to win support for Vice
President George Bush and his running mate among middle-class and
blue-collar voters, Reagan mentioned Quayle more than he usually
does on campaign trips.
   He praised Quayle's performance in his face-off against the
Democratic vice presidential candidate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas.
   ``One thing's even clearer to me after watching the debate
Wednesday night _ the Bush-Quayle ticket will continue the policies
of peace and prosperity that have, as Dan said, made this great
nation `the envy of the world,''' Reagan told a cheering group of
several hundred business leaders.
   To a screaming, flag-waving crowd of 10,000 students and
residents in nearby Sterling Heights earlier in the day, Reagan
said with a grin, ``America's economy is a Grand Prix racer, and
the way to keep it on track is to give George Bush and Dan Quayle a
checkered flag in their race in November.''
   Late Friday, the president spoke at a $1,000-per-plate GOP
fund-raiser and attempted to counter the idea that Quayle's
performance had cost votes.
   ``The other night ... the Washington establishment was betting
against him,'' Reagan said. ``But I tell you, the smart money was
riding on a great senator, by the name of Dan Quayle. He got my
vote. How about yours?''
   Reagan then predicted that in November, ``the American people
will be investing in a new option for the American engine _ I call
it the George Bush turbocharger. And when that happens, all I can
say is, Put the pedal to the metal and watch America go.''
   Reagan's references to Quayle came amid an apparent Republican
damage-control effort to blunt criticism of Quayle's performance in
the Omaha, Neb., debate. Instant polls conducted after the event
showed the public, by a wide margin, believed Bentsen had handily
beaten Quayle in the debate.
   The president said, ``The liberals are saying they want to help
the American middle class. And what they're planning to do ... is
to tax them and tax them and tax them some more. If you ask me, the
liberals are selling the middle class short.''
   He said the nation had enjoyed economic good times during his
eight years in office and suggested that the economic hardship the
state endured as the auto industry suffered might return under a
Democratic administration.
   ``And you may have heard that I kind of like what George Bush
said about this election _ `when you have to change horses in
midstream, doesn't it make sense to switch to one who's going the
same way,''' he said.
   After Reagan ended his speech, a man claiming he had been the
subject of government mind control experiments disrupted the event,
making a long and rambling argument that he had been mistreated.
   Secret Service agents, apparently determining that he was not a
physical threat to Reagan, made no attempt to approach the man, who
identified himself as William McKnight, 58. He gave no address or
hometown.
   Reagan, angered by what he called an ``unfair'' disruption of
the dinner guests, finally shouted into the microphone that if the
man had a complaint, he should ``put it in a letter and send it to
me.''
   Reagan's visit was a homecoming of sorts, since it was in
Detroit's Joe Louis Arena in July 1980 that the former California
governor accepted his party's nomination for the first time _ and
chose Bush to be his running mate.
   Reagan recalled the time as ``a magical moment'' and ``one of
the proudest moments of my life.''
   Most experts rate Michigan a tossup, though Bush campaign
adviser Lee Atwater said earlier this week that Bush campaign
figures showed the vice president ahead in the state by seven to
eight points. The state went to Reagan, 59 percent to 40 percent,
in 1984.
</TEXT>
