<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WaukeganHarbor     10-07 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waukegan Harbor,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outboard Marine Agrees to Pay Clean-up Costs, Ending Decade of
Litigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH NORDGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outboard-motor manufacturer has agreed to pay
for a $20 million cleanup of toxic PCBs in Lake Michigan's Waukegan
Harbor, ending years of bitter haggling over the Superfund site,
officials announced Friday.
   Under a consent decree signed by Outboard Marine Corp. and
federal and state officials, thousands of pounds of toxic
polychlorinated biphenyls will be removed, treated and safely
stored, state Attorney General Neil Hartigan said.
   ``This is a major environmental victory,'' Hartigan said, noting
that no taxpayer dollars will be used in the cleanup.
   Waukegan Harbor, an important Great Lakes port at Waukegan, 25
miles north of Chicago, has been listed on the federal Superfund
list of environmental hazards and at one time was considered
Illinois' worst pollution problem.
   Contamination of the harbor began in 1961, when hydraulic fluid
containing PCBs leaked from the hydraulic systems at the company's
Waukegan plant into waste waters, which were dumped into Lake
Michigan and onto plant property.
   Public health officials have advised against eating fish from
the harbor. PCBs have been shown to cause tumors in laboratory
animals and are suspected to cause cancer in humans.
   ``We obviously believe that it's time to get this matter
resolved,'' said company spokesman Laurin Baker in a telephone
interview from Outboard Marine's Waukegan headquarters.
   While saying it is ``hard to be happy over spending $20 million
in company assets,'' Baker called the decree ``the best settlement
possible.''
   The case became entangled in the legal system as company
officials first argued PCBs posed no threat to humans, then barred
from their facilities federal environmental officials seeking to
determine the extent of the pollution, said U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency spokesman John Perrecone.
   After changes in the federal Superfund law in 1986 allowed the
EPA such access, the company agreed to negotiate with state and
federal authorities, Perrecone said.
   Under terms of Friday's consent decree, Outboard Marine will
begin cleaning up the PCBs next spring and should complete the task
by 1992. The company will remove and treat contaminated material
from both the harbor and its property.
   ``The agreement called for us to remove and treat sediments and
soils that have the highest levels of contamination and encapsulate
the remaining low-level soils and sediments in three areas,'' Baker
said.
   Outboard Marine is a $1.3 billion manufacturer of recreational
marine products and other recreational materials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
