<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Explosion     10-07 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Explosion,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Explode in Two Bookstores; Two Minor Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firebombs exploded at
bookstores in downtown Durban and a white suburb Friday afternoon,
slightly injuring two people and causing minor damage, police
reported.
   The first blast occurred at about 2 p.m. in the Central News
Agency bookstore in suburban Pinetown, police said, and two people
suffered minor cuts. They said another about two hours later
damaged a Central News Agency branch in the city.
   Police initially said they had found a bomb at the downtown
store and did not mention an explosion until hours later.
   Six people were hurt Thursday, one seriously, when a bomb
exploded outside municipal offices of a mixed-race township near
Johannesburg, police reported. They said the bomb, placed in a
trash bin, damaged windows and walls of the municipal building in
Tembisa township.
   Three men and three women were wounded, police said. The
government-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said one woman was
in serious condition.
   Bombings have occurred almost daily in recent weeks and the 29
in September were the most ever in a single month.
   Police blame virtually all of them on the African National
Congress, the main black guerrilla group fighting to bring down the
white-minority government.
   They say the ANC has intensified bombing in an attempt to
disrupt nationwide municipal elections scheduled for Oct. 26.
   About 150 bombings have been reported since President P.W.
Botha's government declared a state of emergency June 12, 1986.
</TEXT>
