<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 2129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Fashion     10-07 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Fashion,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Fashions Have a Relaxed Style for Summer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The curtain has come down on Milan's fashion
runways with audiences confident that spring-summer 1989 will be a
good year for Italy's designers.
   After the shock treatment of last year's miniskirts, intended to
revive exports that slipped about 2 percent from 1986 to 1987, it
appeared time to relax.
   For the moment, Paris fashion seems to have the lead on
creativity, riding in the wake of Christian LaCroix's vivid
imagination, but buyers still look to Italy for well-tailored
clothes.
   ``These collections are very saleable,'' said Elin Saltzman,
fashion director at Saks Fifth Avenue, of the five-day Italian
ready-to-wear showings that ended Thursday.
   The look for next summer is soft and serene. Gone is the
aggressiveness of a bold hemline, a hugged hip or a bulky padded
shoulder.
   Instead the accent is on a rounded silhouette with small
shoulders, tapered waistline and long loose hemlines. There is
frequent use of rose and cream-colored shades.
   Pants, out during the miniskirt craze but reinstated in March as
the dominant winter look, continued their popularity. Mainly they
are ample and often cropped at the calf. Another favorite is the
high-waisted sailor pant.
   Nautical themes pop up throughout the collections from the
profuse use of navy blue and blue and white striping to sailor-suit
collars on white blouses and jackets.
   The lore of the exotic influenced the collections with
low-waisted sarong skirts and pants, bolero jackets, Chinese prints
and Indian embroidery.
   Laura Biagiotti brought 20 Chinese models to Milan from Beijing
for her collection.
   Following in alphabetical order are glimpses of who offers what
for spring and summer:
   Armani _ Soft daytime suits in silk tweeds and evening wear in
diaphanous chiffon and embroidered silk.
   Basile _ Feminine blazers and long pants or skirts by day,
strapless chiffon gowns by night.
   Byblos _ Carioca skirts, calypso pants and tropical wrap around
skirts.
   Fendi _ A schoolgirl look in pleated linen carried into the
night by demure touches such as lace collars and floral embroidery.
   Ferre _ Nautical in an almost exclusive preference for navy blue
or blue and white stripes.
   Genny _ Tightest and shortest look on the runway with toreador
pants and short-skirted black suits.
   Gigli _ Waif-like with knotted hemlines and long sleeves.
   Krizia _ Sporty jackets and jumpers for daytime and Milan's
prettiest evening gown in tea rose silk organza.
   Missoni _ Back to his artistry in Murano glass and Gustav Klimt
designs for sumptuous knitwear.
   Mario Valentino _ Leather patchworked or embroidered to look
like fabric in bright citrus shades or muted tones.
   Versace _ High waists on pants and skirts with a preference for
black and white, a night-look in transparent chiffon tops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881007-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 2129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     10-07 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Adopts Report To Continue Controversial Dam Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament adopted a government report
Friday recommending continuation of a controversial dam project on
the Danube River, following a heated eight-hour debate broadcast
live on Hungarian television.
   The vote to adopt was 317 for, 19 against, with 31 abstaining.
   Hungary is building the Gabcikovo-Nagymaros hydroelectric power
plant and dam jointly with Czechoslovakia, with Austria financing
part of the Hungarian side of the project in return for electric
power.
   The project has run into heavy opposition in Hungary. Dozens of
independent environmental interest groups and others are demanding
construction be halted, claiming it will cause irreparable
ecological damage to wetland and wildlife along the Danube and
pollute large drinking water reserves.
   Environment Minister Laszlo Marothy argued Thursday that halting
the project would put a burden of $140 million to $200 milliion a
year on the economy until the mid-1990s. He said that would include
investing in substitute energy sources, restoring the landscape,
and compensation payments to Austria and Czechoslovakia.
   Officials estimated this year that the cost of completing the
dam would be about $1.08 billion while stopping construction would
cost about $1.1 billion. Environmentalists contend inflation will
push costs to $2.6 billion.
   Janos Szentagothai, former president of the Academy of Sciences,
on Friday told Parliament the academy adopted a unanimous decision
in 1983 proposing the government halt work on the project but this
was never made public.
   The deputies argued at length over conflicting motions _ one for
a roll-call vote and the other for a vote behind closed doors.
   Istvan Avar, a prominent actor and member of Parliament, broke
the deadlock finally by proposing that both groups withdraw their
motions and that the vote be taken by standing up.
   A roll-call vote is rare in Communist Hungary's legislature,
traditionally accustomed to giving rubber-stamp approval to
government decisions by a show of hands. The public wrangle was
another indication of the increasing openness in Hungary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
