<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says He's Delighted to Take the Heat for Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf pvs, bgng: ``That is ...'' to
UPDATE with later Quayle comments.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential candidate Dan
Quayle, reacting to television ads aimed at him by the Dukakis
campaign, said Friday his new role was to ``take all the heat and
the criticism'' from the Democrats and he would do it ``very
energetically.''
   ``We're delighted to be the lightning rod for the campaign,''
Quayle said, ``instead of have the heat and the target be George
Bush.''
   ``I've taken heat before and I'll stay in the kitchen, as they
say,'' Quayle said.
   The Indiana senator spoke with reporters as he left fund-raisers
in Atlanta and a rally at a high school in Woodstock, Ga. He then
traveled to Raleigh, N.C. for a rally.
   Since his debate with Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd
Bentsen, Quayle has shrugged off polls suggesting many voters still
doubt his qualifications and think he lost the confrontation with
the Texas senator.
   At one point Friday, Quayle was asked to justify his post-debate
assertions this week that Michael Dukakis, the Democratic
presidential nominee, ``looks down on America.''
   ``He does look down on America; he's got an idea that America
somehow is not a growth-oriented country,'' Quayle said. ``The
governor himself looks down and takes a very liberal viewpoint
towards America and that is looking down on America.''
   Quayle earlier said he was not concerned about the new Dukakis
ads, one of which notes that Bush had chosen Quayle to replace him
should tragedy occur and says, ``Hopefully we will never know how
great a lapse of judgment that really was.''
   ``I haven't seen them. I've heard about them. They obviously
don't have anything bad to say about George Bush and that's fine
with me,'' Quayle told reporters as he toured a Chattanooga, Tenn.,
technical school.
   When he was asked at the Atlanta appearance to elaborate, Quayle
said, ``I think that is the new role _ that I'm going to take all
the heat and the criticism.''
   ``That is my new assignment and I am willing to take it on very
energetically,'' Quayle said.
   Later, Quayle told reporters on his campaign plane that it was
his decision to take on the role of ``lightning rod.''
   ``I assigned the role to myself. ... I'm going to be taking all
the heat and that's just fine. We'll let George Bush have a free
ride,'' he said.
   Quayle asserted that Dukakis was pulling much of his
organization out of the South because ``they've lost the South.''
Dukakis campaign officials have denied any such pullout.
   At Etowah High School in Woodstock, Quayle was greeted by
students waving small U.S. flags and cheering. The school presented
him with a ceramic quail.
   He took questions from the students, who wanted to know how he
would safeguard women's rights, Social Security and care for the
elderly.
   Jan Lee, a Spanish teacher, said Quayle was ``a real charismatic
type of person.'' However, his comments, all from his stump
campaign speeches, didn't satisfy everybody.
   ``He avoided the questions, all of them,'' said Carrie Amerson,
17. Another student, Kelly Helms, 15, also thought he went ``around
the questions.''
   At the tour of the Chattanooga technical school, Quayle helped
demonstrate a computer-controlled robot paint sprayer. The sprayer
doused a blackboard with water and then Quayle aimed it in the
direction of the press corps.
   ``That's for all those articles you've written about me,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
