<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Clash 1stLd-Writethru a0619 10-07 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Clash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0619,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Killed In Clash Between Officials And Reform Demonstrators</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Two grafs SUB for 3d graf pvs, Radio Haiti-Inter ... YPDATING
with other, unrelated unreleated deaths. Picks up 4th graf, The
Tonton ... with minor editing to trim; ADDS 5 grafs on feuding
families</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Officials in a small town clashed
with citizens demanding their ouster and a soldier guarding the
officials shot and killed one of the demonstrators, an independent
radio station reported Friday.
   Some Haitians said Thursday's confrontation in Desdunes, 150
miles north of the capital, was one of several indicating the
military government is clamping down on the reform movement
launched by a Sept. 17 soldiers' rebellion.
   In unrelated fighting about 50 miles south of Desdunes, two
people were killed Friday in a feud between members of two families
over land and hundreds of people fled their homes fearing a
massacre, according to Radio Haiti-Inter.
   Radio Haiti-Inter said the fight in Desdunes began after groups
representing youths, peasants and planters met to formulate demands
for disarming members of the Tonton Macoutes and repressive
government officials.
   The Tonton Macoutes were the private militia that supported the
29-year dictatorship of the Duvalier family.
   The demonstrators took to the streets intending to shut down
government offices, the broadcast said. Before they got to the
courthouse they were blocked by ``The Steamroller,'' a group of
henchmen and city officials led by Mayor Anthenor Mercius, the
radio said.
   The mayor's group, guarded by soldiers, threw rocks at the
protesters, and four soldiers protecting the demonstrators withdrew
to their barracks, the broadcast said.
   It said a soldier in the mayor's group, Sgt. Detroit Valco,
killed a youth identified as Evarol Racine and wounded another man
in the foot. Four other demonstrators were injured by rocks, the
radio said.
   Paul Latortue, an economist who ran for the region's Senate seat
in November's violently aborted national elections, said the town
is a stronghold of the Tonton Macoutes.
   Latortue noted that on Sunday, the government said it was
temporarily suspending the search for Tonton Macoutes. On
Wednesday, soldiers killed a squatter in the capital, and on
Thursday they dispersed a demonstration in the town of
Port-de-Paix, he said.
   The government believes ``the social potential of the soldiers'
reform movement is too high, it must be reduced and checked,''
Latortue said.
   The enlisted men of the Presidential Guard overthrew the
military government of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy in a bloodless coup on
Sept. 17 and named Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril to replace him.
   The soldiers demanded an improvement in living conditions for
themselves, the ouster of unpopular military and government
officials, and a return to the 1987 Constitution, which Namphy
suspended.
   In the initial reaction to the coup, people across the country
chased down, killed and burned several Tonton Macoutes.
   Latortue said Avril has consolidated his power and promoted
non-commissioned officers to bring them into line.
   ``Avril is successfully bringing off a vast seduction campaign
on behalf of American aid,'' Latortue said. ``But the fist in the
velvet glove is iron.''
   Radio-Metropole reported Friday that Haitian employees of the
U.S. Agency for International Development petitioned for immediate
resumption of U.S. assistance to Haiti.
   Two-thirds of the $90 million U.S. aid package was cut off last
year when November's elections were canceled. Thugs supported by
the army attacked and killed 34 people at the polls.
   Namphy took over after dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to
exile in France in February 1986. Duvalier ruled after the 1971
death of his father, Francois Duvalier, who took over in 1957.
   Radio Haiti-Inter said its reporter in Estere, 100 miles north
of Port-au-Prince, said one person was was shot to death, another
was killed by machete blows and ``many people'' were clubbed or
stoned in fighting Friday in the fertile Artibonite Valley.
   It said the feud involves members of the Hatier and Bercourt
families who have had violent disputes for years over land
ownership.
   The report said that after a fatal shooting, Hatier property
near Estere was invaded by members of the Desdunes-based Bercourt
and in the fighting, hundreds of residents fled the area in panic.
   It said police made one arrest and called for reinforcements to
help restore calm.
   In July 1987, more than 250 people were killed near the town of
Jean Rabel in Artibonite province in battles involving a dispute
between an association of landless peasants and a coalition of
landowners and sharecroppers.
</TEXT>
