<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 2159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GunFactoryFire     10-07 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gun Factory Fire,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Killed In Gun Factory Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire at a rural gun factory Friday killed
four people, destroyed the building and forced firefighters to
retreat as bullets whizzed by them, authorities said.
   The bodies of four people were recovered from the rubble of the
Buffalo Rock Shooters Supply, which makes ammunition and machine
guns for police departments around the country, authorities said.
   ``It was a big ball of fire with a couple of explosions. There
were a lot of bullets flying,'' said Vince Dettore, fire chief of
Naplate, a town about four miles east of the factory.
   Dettore said workers were believed to have been making bullets
when the first explosion hit about 11:30 a.m. in the main building,
which also housed the company's general offices and gun shop.
   The official cause was unknown, but fire investigators suspect a
spark may have ignited gunpowder used to make bullets, he said.
Ottawa is about 70 miles southwest of Chicago.
   ``It started in the main bulding where they make ammunition and
sell guns,'' Dettore said. ``A place like that with all that black
powder _ just the dust, if you get a spark in there that's all it's
going to take. They had cases and cases and cases of all kinds of
ammunition, all kinds of guns.''
   The victims had not been positively identified Friday night and
La Salle County Coroner Marion Osborne said through a spokesman
that the process wouldn't be finished until Saturday.
   Jody Bernard, the coroner's secretary, said a forensic dentist
was summoned to help identify the bodies.
   When firefighters arrived at the company's complex, they began
battling the blaze as bullets whizzed through the air, Dettore said.
   ``It's not as dangerous as if it was shot out of a gun itself,''
the fire chief said. ``It gets a little scary when you get a big
explosion.''
   But Dettore said that when he found out the buildings contained
substantial amounts of gunpowder, he ordered the 40 firefighters to
retreat about a half mile.
   They stayed away for about 45 minutes and resumed fighting the
fire about 1 p.m., Dettore said. They had most of the fire put out
in about an hour, though small fires still flared.
   More than 120 firefighters battled the blaze.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
