<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WHO-AIDSFigures     10-07 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WHO-AIDS Figures,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>African Countries Cause 7 Percent Rise In AIDS Totals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of AIDS cases registered by the World
Health Organization increased 7 percent to 120,000 during September
with Malawi, Tanzania and Kenya accounting for much of the rise, a
WHO report said Friday.
   The actual total is estimated by the WHO to be double the
officially reported number. Jonathan Mann, head of the Global
Program on AIDS, estimates up to 10 million people may be infected
with the deadly virus that causes AIDS. Mann expects at least 1
million new cases of the disease by 1993.
   Malawi had a 400 percent rise in cases since its last report of
Oct. 31, with 2,586 cases reported. Tanzania reported 3,055 cases,
or almost twice the total it gave lact Oct. 17.
   The aggregate AIDS total for the 45 African countries rose from
14,818 to 19,034, with Kenya's 2,732 cases up more than 33 percent
since March 31.
   Among other countries also reporting an increase in victims was
the United States, up 3 percent to 73,394; Brazil, up 24 percent to
3,687; and Mexico, up 16 percent to 1,502.
</TEXT>
