<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JudgeReprimanded 1stLd-Writethru   10-07 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge Reprimanded, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0646,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Judge Reprimanded By State Supreme Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to CORRECT to included, sted including.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida's Supreme Court, for only the
second time in its history, publicly reprimanded a judge Friday,
rebuking him for 14 judicial indiscretions that included waving a
gun from the bench.
   Circuit Judge Wallace E. Sturgis Jr. of Marion County was
summoned before the court and accused by Chief Justice Raymond
Ehrlich of sullying his reputation and his family name.
   ``This is probably one of the most distateful chores that I have
had to perform,'' Ehrlich told Sturgis and a courtroom audience of
about 50 people.
   The Judicial Qualifications Commission found Sturgis guilty of
the 14 counts of misconduct.
   The commission said that besides waving a handgun twice in
hearings, Sturgis failed for 19 years to keep adequate records of a
$20,000 estate he managed for a blind and incompetent family friend.
   It said he should have transferred the account when he became a
judge in 1973.
   Sturgis, whose father, Wallace Edwin Sturgis, was Senate
president in 1951-53 and an appeals judge, listened with downcast
eyes to the reprimand.
   ``For more than 15 years you in the exercise of your judicial
duties have stood in judgment of others. Today, you are the one
being judged,'' said Ehrlich, adding that it was a ``lack of
corrupt motives and the absence of moral turpitude'' that kept the
commission from recommending Sturgis' removal.
   Sturgis said nothing to the court and left without comment.
   In earlier hearings, an attorney for Sturgis said he pulled the
gun because of a ``startle reflex.'' He said the judge had been the
victim of an attack and was nervous about courthouse security.
   The last judge ordered to appear before the court for reprimand
was Circuit Judge Jack Block of Miami, who was rebuked two years
ago for violating legal ethics before he joined the bench, said Sid
White, clerk of the court.
   Usually, the court issues reprimands in writing.
</TEXT>
