<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PLOSued     10-07 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO Sued,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Terrorized in Achille Lauro Hijacking Sues PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New Jersey couple, caught in the 1985
terrorist hijacking of the Mediteranean cruise ship Achille Lauro,
sued the Palestine Liberation Organization on Friday for more than
$11 million.
   The lawsuit, filed at U.S. District Court in Manhattan, accused
the PLO of false imprisonment, assault and battery and
intentionally inflicting emotional distress on Frank R. Hodes and
his wife, Mildred, both of Springfield, N.J.
   The Achille Lauro, a 24,000-ton Italian liner, was seized Oct.
7, 1983, off Egypt by terrorists identifying themselves as members
of a PLO splinter group, the Palestine Liberation Front.
   The terrorists demanded the release of 50 Palestinians held in
Israel.
   One wheelchair-bound American passenger, Leon Klinghoffer, 69,
of New York, was killed by the terrorists before they left the
vessel Oct. 9.
   The lawsuit described the Hodeses as ``long-standing friends''
of Klinghoffer and his wife, Marilyn.
   After the hijackers left the ship, the lawsuit said, Mrs. Hodes
learned ``from the captain that she was to be the next victim,'' if
the ordeal had continued.
   According to the lawsuit, the acts of terrorism on the Achille
Lauro were directed by the PLO ``to terrorize American citizens,
especially those such as the Hodeses of Jewish faith.''
   According to the lawsuit, Hodes was off the vessel with 600
other passengers for a one-day excursion to see the Egyptian
pyramids when the terrorists seized the ship, and the remaining
passengers _ including his wife and 11 other Americans.
</TEXT>
