<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile 2ndLd-Writethru a0745 10-07 0797</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0745,0819</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Wants Pinochet Out Before 1990</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-14 UPDATE with six journalists injured, other
details. Picks up 11th graf pvs, Opposition leaders ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SCL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders said Friday that they
want President Augusto Pinochet out of office before 1990, despite
his vow to complete his term after losing a referendum. Hundreds of
thousands celebrated the ``no'' vote.
   Ten people were wounded, two seriously, when soldiers fired on
celebrants in passing cars, a radio station reported.
   Six journalists in Chile to cover the referendum also were
slightly injured when they were caught between riot police and
demonstrators Friday night near the national palace. Four of the
injured required treatment at Santa Maria Clinic for head wounds.
   Ricardo Lagos, a moderate Socialist prominent in the 16-party
opposition alliance, said the president, who is also army
commander, has ``too great an ambition for power'' and should heed
the message this week by voters ``who said `No more.' ''
   Hundreds of thousands of Chileans swayed and sang along with
some of the country's most popular music groups in a park Friday in
an opposition celebration. No politicians spoke and the music was
pointedly non-political, but people chanted on their own: ``Chi Chi
Chi, Le Le Le, Get Out Pinochet!'' and ``He's Going to Fall!''
   People bound for the park in buses and packed automobiles
chanted anti-government slogans and waved anti-Pinochet banners.
Police estimated the crowd at up to 350,000.
   A free presidential election is to be held late next year
because of Pinochet's loss in the yes-or-no referendum Wednesday on
whether he should remain in office until 1997. He can run in that
election if he chooses.
   The winner takes office in March 1990 and Pinochet said Thursday
night he will not permit changes in the election schedule and he
vowed not to leave office early. Pinochet took power in a September
1973 coup that ousted Marxist President Salvador Allende.
   While there was a peaceful gathering in the capital's biggest
park on a warm hazy afternoon, there was violence elsewhere later.
   Radio Cooperativa, an independent news station, reported
soldiers outside an army barracks near the park fired buckshot and
pellets at people in passing cars who flashed the V sign for
victory.
   It said two people were seriously wounded and eight were treated
at Santiago Central Emergency Hospital. A hospital spokesman told
The Associated Press nine people were treated for gunshot wounds
and a 10th was taken to a neurological hospital.
   Several hundred youths leaving the rally behind the national
palace tried to stage a demonstration. Police, anticipating
trouble, blocked the street off to traffic, then scattered the
youths with water cannon and tear gas.
   The demonstrators regrouped, however. During the charge, riot
police kicked and lashed with nightsticks at newsmen.
   ``We were crouched behind a fruit stand _ not in the way and
trying to get out of the way,'' Associated Press photographer John
Hopper said. ``It happened so quick, nobody flashed (photographed)
them. We did nothing to draw attention to us.''
   Opposition leaders have requested talks with the government on
amending the constitution and speeding Pinochet's departure. Lagos
said the administration might become more flexible later.
   ``You have to give the defeated a couple of days to recover from
the shock,'' he said. ``Let's talk more seriously about it next
week.''
   He said the opposition should unify in its bid for an earlier
election, declaring: ``If we join together with more force, I think
the situation will change.''
   Interior Minister Sergio Fernandez said the government would
negotiate with the opposition only ``if it was necessary.''
   Alfonso Marquez de la Plata, the labor minister, said: ``These
people participated in the referendum and have to abide by the
rules of the game.''
   Lagos spoke to reporters outside a federal prison where he
visited a more radical Socialist, Clodomiro Aylmeda, who is serving
a 541-day term on charges of promoting political violence through
public anti-government statements.
   Whether Pinochet can resist opposition pressure is expected to
depend on support from his army, and no splits in the ranks were
evident Friday.
   Gen. Eduardo Ibanez, governor of the southern Eighth Region, was
quoted Friday by La Epoca, a moderate Santiago daily, as saying:
``We have lost a battle, but not the war. This is an electoral
defeat for the governent, but from the military point of view it's
no more than a battle.''
   He accused voters of ``ingratitude,'' the report said.
   The navy, air force and national police are generally seen as
more willing to negotiate with the opposition but lack the army's
size and political clout.
   Pinochet's 1980 constitution gives the military autonomy and an
influential role in national policy under a democratic government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
