<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DukakisFurlough     10-07 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis Furlough,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Campaign Sponsors Attack on Dukakis' Furlough Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose brother's killer escaped from
Massachusetts' prison furlough program and attacked a couple in
Maryland took her criticism of Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
to California on Friday in a trip financed by George Bush
supporters.
   ``I think it's at a point in this country where the prisoners'
rights have superseded and taken over,'' said Donna Fournier Cuomo
of Lawrence, Mass., whose 17-year-old brother, Joey Fournier, was
murdered in 1974 by Willie Horton.
   ``The victims are not heard,'' she added, saying, ``Gov.
Dukakis, I don't feel, would address this issue.''
   Mrs. Cuomo endorsed Republican Vice President Bush for the
presidency, but the Maryland man who was attacked by Horton after
his escape, refused to endorse anyone at the news conference.
   ``This isn't political to my wife and I,'' said Cliff Barnes, a
former resident of Oxon Hill, Md., explaining his non-partisan
position.
   Both Barnes and Mrs. Cuomo said their expenses for their trip to
Los Angeles and Sacramento on Friday and to Texas next week were
being paid by the Committee for the Presidency, a group formed to
support Bush's candidacy.
   But Barnes said he wanted to address only the Massachusetts'
furlough program, saying, ``It's not a successful program.''
   Horton had been serving a life sentence without parole in
Massachusetts for Fournier's murder when he walked away from his
10th release on weekend furlough.
   He broke into the Barnes' home in April 1987. Cliff Barnes was
slashed 22 times and then tied up by Horton. His then-fiancee and
now wife, Angi, was beaten and raped twice.
   The Democrats' response to Republican attacks on the program
have consisted of ``a bunch of misleading statistics that hide the
faces and the lives of the real victims,'' said Barnes.
   ``I will never understand it,'' Mrs. Cuomo said of a program
allowing the weekend furlough of a first-degree murderer. ``To me,
it does not make sense.''
   Barnes and Mrs. Cuomo also said that as governor, Dukakis has
refused to meet with them about crimes committed by Massachusetts
convicts while on weekend furloughs or work-release programs.
   They also asserted that Dukakis resisted efforts to prohibit
first-degree murderers from participating in the state furlough
program.
   In April, Dukakis signed legislation to enact just such a change
in the Massachusetts program.
   When Bush began pressing the furlough issue, the Dukakis
campaign fired back with statistics showing that the furlough
escape rate in Massachusetts has been below the national average.
   Dukakis officials also contend that more than 40 states have
furlough programs for convicted felons, and at least 23 states make
first-degree murderers eligible for furloughs.
   The Democrats also invoked the record of Ronald Reagan, who
supported the furlough program in California _ even after two
convicts killed people while on furlough in late 1971 and early
1972.
   At the time of the murders in California, former Los Angeles
Police Chief Ed Davis, now a Republican state senator, complained
to then-Gov. Reagan that ``about 40 percent of our serious and
violent offenders are on active parole from your Department of
Corrections.''
   Both Reagan and Dukakis inherited their respective state
furlough programs, and both defended the programs from political
attacks that arose following crimes committed by convicts on
furlough.
</TEXT>
