<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Cyprus     10-07 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Cyprus,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cypriot President Calls For Demilitarization Of Island Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Vassiliou of Cyprus on
Thursday called for demilitarization of his Mediterranean island
nation, where a U.N. peacekeeping force separates the hostile
Turkish and Greek Cypriot communities.
   ``We propose to dismantle the military forces of the Republic
(of Cyprus) if all Turkish troops and settlers withdraw and if the
armed elements they have fostered are disbanded,'' Vassiliou told
delegates to the 43rd General Assembly.
   In 1974, Greece's military junta sponsored a coup on Cyprus that
failed. Turkey invaded to protect the Turkish Cypriot minority, and
still occupies about 40 percent of the northern part of Cyprus.
   The northern part of Cyprus declared itself to be the ``Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus'' in 1975, a breakaway state recognized
only by Turkey. About 200,000 Greek Cypriots fled the northern
section during the invasion and tens of thousands of Turks have
since come to Cyprus to settle there.
   ``We undertake to use the funds which will be saved through
demilitarization for the development of areas of Cyprus which have
fallen behind economically and primarily for projects which will
benefit mainly the Turkish Cypriots,'' Vassiliou proposed.
   ``Part of the savings could also be used for financing the
international peace force to be established,'' he added. The
current 2,300-member U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus is funded by
voluntary contributions of U.N. members.
   Vassiliou first suggested this plan in June at the General
Assembly's Special Session on Disarmament.
   He said the solution of the Cyprus problem is defined in U.N.
resolutions that call for all foreign troops and settlers to leave
the island; that call for respect for human rights; and that say no
other nation has a right to intervene in Cypriot internal affairs.
   ``We believe that in the future federal Republic of Cyprus that
we envision all Cypriots, whether Greek or Turkish, should enjoy
equality of opportunity and fundamental freedoms including the
right to develop their distinctive cultural heritages,'' he said.
   Vassiliou has met with Rauf Denktash, president of the breakaway
Turkish republic on northen Cyprus, to discuss reunification of the
island. The talks were held at the invitation of Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   ``The target is to achieve a just and lasting solution of the
Cyprus problem by June 1989,'' Vassiliou said.
   In his speech to the General Asssembly, Vassiliou also called
for worldwide military cutbacks, with the major lending nations
using the savings to establish national funds to buy at the present
discounted market rates the outstanding loans owed to their
commercial banks by developing nations.
   ``The cost of these national debt relief programs would be
minimal if they are coupled with an imaginative use of tax
credits,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
