<DOCNO> AP881007-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv10   10-07 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 10,0620</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday, Oct. 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Best Investment of All</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whenever homeowners feel frustrated by tales of
huge profits in the stock market they should remind themselves that
they have the best investment of all.
   Securities prices collapse every now and then, but housing
prices generally hold their own. You store stocks in a safe-deposit
box but you can live in a house. You pay big taxes on securities
gains; on houses, you can defer them.
   The advantages don't end there. You may pay for your house in
easy monthly installments, but payments for stocks are up front.
You can fix up your house and increase the value, but you have
little say in a corporate investment.
   But perhaps the greatest security of a housing investment _
after providing shelter for a family _ is the stability of the
investment. Year in and year out, houses generally appreciate, even
when you think they're not.
   In 1981, the median sale price of existing single-family homes,
measured by the National Association of Realtors, was $66,400. In
1987, the figure was $85,400, and through August of this year it
had risen to $91,300.
   National figures can hide regional discrepancies, of course, but
all four sections of the country participated in the the
housing-price advance.
   From 1981 through August, prices in the Northeast jumped from
$63,700 to $144,800. In spite of a manufacturing recession and
various farm problems, they rose in the Midwest from $54,300 to
$70,500; in the South from $64,400 to $84,300, and in the West,
from $96,200 to $122,000.
   In no year since 1981 has the median price failed to gain in the
Midwest and South. The price did fall in the Northeast from 1981 to
1982, but by only $200. In the West it declined in both 1982 and
1985 _ but quickly recovered.
   Such stability is unknown in most other markets. True, the stock
market may have risen at a sharper rate, but the comparison isn't
entirely valid. You can have 50 percent margin in stocks _ but in
housing you might have 90 percent.
   In effect, a homeowner who puts up 10 percent of a home's price
_ the rest coming from the bank _ participates in any price
increase as if he or she owned 100 percent. It is a degree of
leverage almost unknown in securities.
   Leverage and compounding produce financial miracles. An owner
who makes a $10,000 downpayment on a $100,000 house earns 50
percent if that house rises 5 percent to $105,000 in one year.
   As with the purchase of anything, there may be drawbacks in
owning a house. Generally, housing is less liquid than stocks.
While prices might not collapse, markets become inactive every few
years. Selling means legal expenses too.
   But if you do sell and buy a more expensive dwelling you
generally can defer capital gains taxes. Your entire housing equity
can be protected from any taxes so long as the more recently
acquired house remains your property.
   If you attempt to do that with your stock profits you'll invite
the Internal Revenue Service into your affairs. When you sell
stocks you pay taxes on the profits; even if you reinvest in other
stocks there is no deferment.
   Whenever you have the feeling that your pals are making a
killing in the securities markets, therefore, you should sit back
and count your blessings.
   And dwell on the very real probability that their latest winning
effort in the market didn't even offset their losses.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday, Oct. 10.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881007-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-TickerTalk Adv10   10-07 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 10,0731</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Oct. 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mixed Reviews for Market `Circuit Breakers' Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If all goes as expected, the nation's stock
markets will soon embark on an experiment they hope never gets put
to the test.
   The plan, now awaiting approval by the Securities and Exchange
Commission, calls for ``circuit breakers'' that would halt all
trading for set periods of time if stock prices fall by specified
amounts on any given day.
   For example, the New York Stock Exchange would stop trading for
one hour if the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 250 points.
   After that, if the Dow fell 150 points more in the same session,
trading would be halted for two hours.
   The system, developed by the NYSE and the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, would also provide that the prices of stock index futures
traded on the Merc would be effectively frozen for 30 minutes if
they declined by an amount roughly equivalent to 100 Dow points.
   The proposal was made ``contingent on adoption by all domestic
markets.'' NYSE officials have said the plan might hit a snag
because of opposition from the National Association of Securities
Dealers, which operates the over-the-counter market.
   The NASD does indeed regard the plan as ``a bad solution'' to
the issues raised by the market crash last October, Joseph
Hardiman, the organization's president, said in an interview.
   But he indicated his group would go along with whatever the SEC
decides, and said he would be surprised if the commission did not
approve the circuit-breaker plan in some form soon.
   The circuit breakers, along with a series of other measures
proposed by the NYSE and the Merc, are designed to supersede the
``collar'' adopted by the Big Board early this year.
   The collar closed the exchange's main computer trading
facilities to orders from professionals engaged in multiple
transactions known as index arbitrage whenever the Dow rose or fell
50 points in a day.
   Other trading, including ``manual'' index arbitrage, was not
affected by the collar.
   In its brief existence, the collar has drawn mixed reviews. And
the circuit breaker system has attracted divergent comments as well.
   To its proponents, it provides a system for everyone involved in
the trading process to stop and evaluate the situation if a selling
panic hits.
   Also, they say, it helps answer the call from the presidential
commission headed by Nicholas Brady, now secretary of the Treasury,
for a recognition that activity in stocks and stock-index options
and futures be recognized as ``one market.''
   Of course, the hope is that the system will help restore
investor confidence to the extent that the circuit breakers never
actually have to be activated.
   On the other side of the debate, Hardiman says: ``Circuit
breakers are likely to increase market volatility rather than curb
it. The closer a market gets to a circuit breaker level, the more
likely it is to reach it as sellers rush to execute orders under
the wire.''
   A similar contention, that the limit would tend to become a
magnet, was made when the collar was adopted. Experience with the
collar has neither proved nor refuted that point.
   Hardiman also cites academic studies that show markets as most
volatile when a security is opening or reopening after a trading
halt.
   Industry organizations ``should be striving to keep the markets
open,'' he maintains.
   If the circuit breakers as proposed by the Big Board had been in
effect for 50 years, they never would have been activated until
last fall.
   So the statistical chances are not great that the system will be
tested during the one-year ``pilot program'' the exchange is
calling for.
   Presumably, the plan's workability would be demonstrated by a
healthier performance by stock prices and increases in measures of
investor confidence such as price-earnings ratios.
   But some Wall Streeters do not buy that idea. ``The proposed
circuit breakers are no protection at all,'' says Raymond F. DeVoe
Jr., an analyst at Legg Mason Wood Walker Inc.
   ``Stopping trading for an hour when the Dow industrials are down
250 points means you've done nothing until the market's plunged 12
percent. Thanks a lot.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon Oct 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
