<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Kenya'sMoi-10Years ADV16   10-07 1144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kenya's Moi-10 Years, ADV 16,1174</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sun Oct. 16 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Kenya's President Observes 10 Years of Rule</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lower-case arap correct for middle name 1st graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During 11 years as vice president to Jomo
Kenyatta, Daniel arap Moi says, his job was to ``sing the tune'' of
Kenya's first president.
   A decade after Kenyatta's death and Moi's emergence from an
understudy to the ``Mzee'' (Old Man) to the starring role in Kenyan
politics, the schoolteacher-turned-president has taught all
would-be challengers to dance to his drums.
   Through shrewd political maneuvering, the church-going,
teetotaling Moi, a member of the minority Kalengin tribe, has
amassed power that rivals even the lionized Kenyatta's.
   Kenya is by law a one-party state and Moi is boss of the ruling
Kenyan African National Union, a body he says is supreme to the
government.
   Parliament is essentially a rubber stamp to the president's
wishes, and recent constitutional changes have brought the
judiciary more under the executive's control.
   Kenyatta, too, ran Kenya with a tight rein and tolerated no
dissent. So pervasive was his rule that many doomsayers predicted
Kenya would be torn apart by tribal warfare after the death of
Kenyatta, who was a member of the predominant Kikuyu tribe.
   But when the Mzee died on Aug. 22, 1978, Moi, the third and
longest-serving of Kenyatta's vice presidents, peacefully succeeded
him. Within 90 days, as specified by the constitution, Moi called a
presidential election. He won it unopposed and was sworn in as
Kenya's second president Oct. 14, 1978, the date he observes as the
beginning of his presidency.
   In the following months, government officials released details
of what they said had been a plot during Kenyatta's waning days to
kill Moi rather than allow the presidency to fall into the hands of
a non-Kikuyu.
   Though there were no arrests, officials privately linked the
plot to unidentified Kenyatta aides and relatives who months before
had tried unsuccessfully to thwart the constitutional transfer of
power to Moi.
   Moi retained many of Kenyatta's political allies, although some
were his political enemies. It was only in September that he
succeeded in ridding the party of the last vestiges of Kenyatta's
power clique.
   In a week of party elections _ beginning with grassroots
balloting and ending with selection of national officers _ Moi
retained the party presidency, Kenya's supreme political job, but
the eight officers under him changed, cementing Moi's power base.
   During his 15 years of rule after independence from Britain,
Kenyatta would wave a flywisk, his symbol of office, and lead
cheering crowds in Kiswahili chants of ``Harambee'' (Let's pull
together).
   Moi, saying he and the nation would be guided by the course
Kenyatta had charted, adopted as his symbol of office and Poer a
gold and ivory baton and proclaimed a new slogan: ``Nayo''
(FootstEp).
   In his first days in office, Moi emptied the jails of political
detainees, but began his own detentions after junior officers of
the air force unsuccessfully tried to overthrow him on Aug. 1, 1982.
   Five people are now detained under a security law that allows
the government to jail people indefinitely without trial. About 100
other people _ including journalists, lawyers, academics and civil
servants _ have been jailed in the past 30 months after confessing
links with several groups accused of plotting to overthrow Moi.
   The campaign against purported dissidents brought unaccustomed
criticism of Moi and Kenya from human rights groups and others who
charged confessions were coerced and that civil liberties were
being trampled.
   ``President Moi has presided over a steady deteroriation of the
rule of law,'' Rose Styron, chairwoman of the judge's panel of the
Robert F. Kennedy Human Rights Award, said in September when
announcing that the Kenyan lawyer and former political detainee
Gibson Kamau Kuria was the 1988 winner.
   ``Kenya today is a land where only the animals are truly free,''
she said.
   Moi is popular with Kenya's masses and enjoys the reputaton with
Western governments as a moderate. He has cordial ties with most of
his African peers, but is cool to military rulers.
   He has made Kenya the West's best friend in Africa. Western
governments, in turn, hold Kenya up to other African nations as an
example, citing its robust capitalist economy and cooperation among
the races.
   Moi's Kenya remains a mecca for tourists. It's able to feed
itself, a rarity in Africa, and is one of the few countries in the
region not troubled with civil war.
   Kenya's economy is one of Africa's success stories, but has
started to stagger under the burden of the world's fastest-growning
population _ a nearly 4 percent pace that is expected to double the
22 million population by the beginning of the century.
   The population includes 300,000 non-blacks, most of them
``Asians,'' the collective name for people from the Indian
subcontinent. There are about 60,000 ``Europeans,'' the name
Africans assign to all whites.
   On the eve of Kenya's independence in 1963 and despite his armed
Mau-Mau revolt in 1952-56 against British rule, Kenyatta appealed
to whites and other non-Africans to stay put and to help build
black-led Kenya. Most did and many continue to prosper under Moi.
   Minorities, especially the Asians, still control a
disproportionate amount of Kenya's economy _ from groceries and
clothing stores to major factories.
   But whites have no political clout.
   Philip Leakey, son of anthropologists Louis and Mary Leakey, is
the only non-black member of Parliament and serves as an assistant
minister of tourism and wildlife. His brother, Richard, is director
of Kenya's museums.
   Moi, 64 years old and divorced, is a private person. He does not
give interviews. Most of his comments are gleaned from his frequent
appearances at public rallies where he staunchly defends Kenya and
his government.
   ``We are a sovereign state and can stand on our feet,'' he said
recently in at attack on foreign critics. ``We are not under
anyone's feet.''
   The Kenyan press, one of the most sophisticated in Africa, is
assailed by a chorus of protests, often led by Moi, when it
publishes stories that are not to the government's liking. A
church-run magazine, Beyond, was banned earlier this year after
publishing an article alleging fraud during primary elections.
   Nowadays, clergymen and the Law Society of Kenya are the only
public critics of government and even their protests are presented
so as not to offend or even mention the head of state.
   ``We are conscious of a certain inadequacy of dialogue in the
country,'' the Roman Catholic bishops of Kenya said in a letter to
Moi in November 1986.
   ``At present, discussion is precluded by allegation of powerful
party officials that any questioning of the system is tantamout to
disloyalty,'' the bishops added. ``Already the party is assuming a
totalitarian role.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Oct. 16</NOTE>
