<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Burnley-Aviation     10-07 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Burnley-Aviation,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transportation Secretary Calls For FAA Overhaul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration
should be freed of bureaucratic red tape and made an independent
government corporation, similar to Amtrak, U.S. Secretary of
Transportation James Burnley said Thursday.
   Burnley said regulation of aviation safety should remain in the
Transportation Department. But he told the Aircraft Owners and
Pilots Association the FAA needs independence to ``do a much better
job of modernizing air traffic control and keeping pace with
growth.''
   The AOPA represents private aircraft owners and pilots.
   ``The FAA is a unique federal agency because it combines three
distinct and somewhat contradictory missions,'' Burnley said. He
said the FAA is charged with establishing and enforcing aviation
safety regulations, providing air traffic control service and
encouraging development of civil aeronautics and air commerce.
   Burnley said he wanted to retain control of aircraft safety
because ``aviation will do much better in the annual budget battles
with the Office of Management and Budget and Congress with a
cabinet secretary as its spokesman.''
   Burnley also called on Congress to act on a ``tort liability
crisis in general aviation manufacturing'' that has resulted in
insurance costs rising fivefold since 1981, while sales have
dropped from 17,000 planes in 1979 to 1,500 in 1986.
   ``While Congress procrastinates on the resolution of this urgent
issue, general aviation manufacturers in Europe are poised to
invade U.S. markets,'' Burnley said.
   Burnley also said:
   _He was concerned by alcohol and drug abuse among pilots, noting
that indictments were handed down in Tampa, Fla., last week
``against some two dozen pilots for failing to disclose convictions
for drug and alcohol related offenses on the Airman Medical
Certificates they provided to the FAA.''
   _Nationally, there is ``a dire need for airport expansion and
improvement. A major airport has not been constructed in the United
States since Dallas-Fort Worth opened in the mid-70s,'' although he
noted that Adams County, Colo., residents voted in May to permit
Denver to annex land for a new hub airport.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
