<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     10-07 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Unable To Sustain Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have wilted following a
technical rally that failed to shake off market concerns about
Saudi Arabia's threats to overproduce crude.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate rose 6 cents to settle at $12.66 a barrel
on Thursday, but other contract months settled as much as 15 cents
lower. The near-term contract had been up as much as 30 cents
during the session.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the November
contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline rose .06 cent to settle at
39.50 cents a gallon, while home heating oil slipped 0.52 cent to
37.24 cents a gallon. Other contract months finished lower.
   Traders said a technical rally gripped the market, pushing
prices higher by midday, but broke down shortly thereafter on a
dearth of encouraging news.
   ``The market still looks sick,'' said Chris McCormack, a trader
at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. He said participants were continuing
to focus on Saudi Arabia's production levels.
   Earlier this week Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil
exporter, threatened not to restrain its own production if other
members of the 13-nation OPEC cartel continued to pump beyond their
quotas.
   ``That's old news, but it's still the focus of the market, and
there's a feeling that Saudi Arabia has not yet achieved its goals
and will continue to pressure prices,'' McCormack said.
   The Saudis have indicated they want to punish other members of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries for overproducing
and driving down the price of oil.
   Traders also remained concerned about a report that surfaced
Wednesday that said Exxon Corp. chartered a number of tankers to
transport a substantial amount of oil out of the Persian Gulf,
presumably from Saudi Arabia.
   The market interpreted the report as further ``confirmation that
Saudi Arabia has increased production,'' said Andrew Lebow, a
trader at E.D.& F. Man International Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881007-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 0142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   10-07 0812</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0837</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retail Sales Improve From August, But Sluggish Trend Remains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   September reports from the nation's largest general retailers
have given no indication that the companies' 19-month-old sales
slump will end soon, but industry analysts say storeowners have
taken steps to protect their profits.
   ``Sales for the early part of the month through mid-month
recorded a nice uptick,'' but retailers were unable to sustain that
improvement the rest of September, Jeffrey Edelman, an analyst with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., said after reviewing Thursday's
reports.
   Retailers hoped September would end the sluggish sales trend
that began a year and a half ago, but last month's numbers
``weren't quite as good as expected,'' said Karen Sack, an analyst
with Standard & Poor's Corp.
   ``It doesn't look like the turnaround that people expected will
be here,'' Ms. Sack said, predicting retailers would see only
modest sales increases for the rest of 1988.
   But retailers have kept inventories lean and pared expenses,
steps that should help their third-quarter earnings, said Jeffrey
Feiner, an analyst with Merrill Lynch & Co.
   Ms. Sack agreed, saying, ``We're not going to see the kind of
pressure on their margins,'' as in recent quarters.
   ``I think it's safe to say the worst is over for retailers,''
she said.
   The analysts said softness in retail sales was not necessarily a
sign of weakness in consumer spending, which is watched closely as
an economic indicator because it accounts for two-thirds of the
gross national product.
   ``Consumers are spending at a very high rate _ they've just been
moving to other areas like durables,'' said Monroe H. Greenstein,
an analyst with the investment firm Bear, Stearns & Co. Inc.
   Ms. Sack noted consumers also have been spending more for
services _ such as utilities and medical care _ leaving them less
money for general merchandise and apparel.
   Apparel sales, which have been in a year-long slump of their
own, improved slightly last month, but analysts still described
them as weak.
   Several retailers recorded sales increases of 3 percent or less
_ meaning they continued to lose ground to inflation, which has run
at an annual rate of 4.6 percent so far this year.
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., the nation's largest retailer, said its
overall sales rose 6.6 percent in September and 5.7 percent for the
first 35 weeks of the fiscal year. Sales from Sears stores open at
least a year _ known in the trade as same-store or comparable sales
_ were up 1.6 percent last month and 2 percent for the year to date.
   Retailers and industry analysts believe same-store sales are a
more accurate yardstick of a company's performance than figures
which include sales from new stores. But not all retailers report
both overall and same-store results.
   K mart Corp. said its overall sales rose 7.1 percent last month
and 5.6 percent for the cumulative 35-week period. Same-store sales
were up 3 percent for September and 2 percent for the year to date.
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. said its sales were up 25 percent overall
last month, while climbing 30 percent so far this year. Same-store
sales, meanwhile, were up 10 percent in September and 11 percent
for the year to date.
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. said its overall sales rose 1.3 percent in
September, and 1.7 percent for the year to date. Penney's
same-store sales were up 0.7 percent for the month and 0.6 percent
so far this year.
   Dayton Hudson Corp. said its overall sales rose 15.1 percent
last month, and 16.9 percent for the year to date. Same-store sales
picked up 2.9 percent in September and 1.7 percent so far this year.
   May Department Stores Co. said its overall sales rose 21 percent
in September while picking up 14.6 percent so far this year.
Same-store sales were up 3 percent for the month and 1.6 percent
for the year to date.
   F.W. Woolworth Co. said its September sales rose 13.7 percent,
while year-to-date sales rose 12.2 percent. Same-store sales rose
7.2 percent for the month and 5.9 percent for the first 35 weeks.
   Montgomery Ward & Co. said its sales were up 3.5 percent in
September and 3.1 percent so far this year.
   Limited Inc., the nation's largest specialty apparel retailer,
said its overall sales rose 11 percent last month and 6 percent for
the year to date. Limited's same-store sales were up 7 percent in
September _ an improvement over the company's performance in recent
months _ while falling 1 percent over the cumulative 35-week period.
   Apparel sales began slumping in August 1987, when many women
turned away from shorter skirts and fashions they considered boring.
   The results reported Thursday were from general merchandise and
apparel retailers. Unlike monthly retail sales figures released by
the federal government, they do not include sales at auto dealers,
supermarkets or restaurants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
