<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ToyotaDedication     10-07 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toyota Dedication,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toyota Officially Dedicates $800 Million Scott County Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LH1</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp. and state officially
embraced each other during a dedication ceremony of the Japanese
automaker's $800 million plant in rural Kentucky.
   Nearly 1,700 Toyota employees, government officials and
community leaders attended the 1{-hour ceremony Thursday inside the
mammoth Scott County facility that has been in production of
four-door Camry sedans since mid-July.
   The Lexington Philharmonic provided an assortment of classical
pieces and a composition dedicated to Toyota. The ceremony's theme,
``Toyota ... Moving Forward With America'' was placed in white
two-foot letters on the blue curtain behind the podium.
   ``The world has watched while Kentucky and Toyota have worked to
make this plant a reality,'' Kentucky Gov. Wallace Wilkinson said.
   Several speakers repeated the theme of cooperation between the
United States and Japan.
   ``(Thursday's) ceremony represents a new spirit, one of
pioneering new economic, cultural and manufacturing ideals,'' said
Shoichiro Toyoda, president of Toyota Motor Corp. ``A spirit of
successfully merging the manufacturing ideals and practices of two
nations in order to bring a new tradition of success.''
   ``This is a historic moment for Kentucky, for America, for Japan
and for Toyota,'' said Kaneyoshi Kusunoki, president of Toyota
Motor Manufacturing, U.S.A., Inc. ``This event will represent a
small step that will continue to advance growing U.S.-Japan
relations.''
   The plant is Toyota's first wholly owned automobile
manufacturing complex in the United States. By the end of 1989, it
is expected to be producing 200,000 Camrys annually.
</TEXT>
