<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SovietSuit     10-07 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Suit,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Dept. Attorney Says US-Soviet Relations Will Suffer Under
Suit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Justice Department attorney, siding
with the Soviet Union, told a federal appeals court that
U.S.-Soviet relations will suffer unless an American businessman's
unusual lawsuit is dismissed.
   Douglas Letter said Thursday that the government takes no
position on whether Raphael Gregorian is right or wrong in his
contention that the Soviets libeled him. But he joined an attorney
for the Soviets in arguing that the case should not be tried in
U.S. courts.
   Gregorian, a Palo Alto, Calif., businessman, sued the Soviets
after they revoked his license to do business in Moscow, where he
had been selling medical equipment for 14 years. He was expelled
and branded a spy in an article in the official Soviet newspaper
Izvestia.
   His attorney, Gerald Kroll, told a panel of the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in the one-day hearing that Gregorian deserves a
trial.
   However, Letter argued: ``We have been working very closely with
the Soviets and we have made wonderful progress. It's important
that this progress not be set back.
   ``It is our position that under the Foreign Sovereign Immunities
Act, you cannot sue a foreign entity for libel,'' Letter said.
``And even if you can, you can't do it on the facts of this case.''
   Kroll ridiculed Letter's contention that the fate of U.S.-Soviet
relations depends on Gregorian.
   ``I personally think they have bigger people to fry than my
client,'' he told the court.
   Reached by telephone, Gregorian expressed amazement at the
statements about his role in international affairs.
   ``If being fair to me affects our relations with the Soviet
Union, then we don't have any relations,'' he said. ``The question
is why have they (the U.S. government) turned against me? I'm
really too small a guy. ... We're talking about two superpowers.
This is infantile, sophomoric and unfair.''
   One of the appellate judges, Stephen Reinhardt, bristled at the
mention of foreign relations, saying, ``Isn't that something we're
supposed to ignore _ the political considerations _ in reaching our
decision?''
   John Mage, a New York attorney representing the Soviets,
insisted that U.S. courts do not have jurisdiction because the
incidents in question did not occur in the United States. He also
said the Soviet Union is immune from a lawsuit as a foreign
sovereign.
   Kroll argued that the Soviets libeled Gregorian in connection
with a commercial enterprise and that such an action is exempt from
the immunities act.
   Gregorian's problems date back to 1984 when the Soviets said he
could no longer sell medical equipment such as kidney dialysis and
heart-lung machines. The Soviet newspaper then printed a story
denouncing Gregorian as a ``duplicitous negotiator,'' accusing him
of bribery and smuggling and intimating that he was a U.S. spy.
   Gregorian, adamant about his innocence, sued for libel and
demanded payment for medical equipment still in Moscow. The Soviets
dispute his contention that he still has equipment there.
   The Soviet defendants ignored the suit until 1985, when U.S.
District Judge David Kenyon entered a default judgment against
them, awarding Gregorian total damages of $413,000. Of that amount,
$250,000 was for libel.
   The Soviets refused to pay. Kroll said he would seize Soviet
assets and even took custody of a typewriter at an Izvestia
correspondent's Washington, D.C. home as partial payment.
   The Soviets and the U.S. State Department went to court and
asserted immunity from suit under the immunities act.
   Last year Kenyon reversed his own libel judgment, ruling that he
did not have jurisdiction because of immunity considerations. But
he let stand his ruling the Soviets should pay for the medical
supplies.
   Kroll appealed the libel ruling to the 9th Circuit. The Soviets
appealed the contractual award as well as disputing the libel claim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881007-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Unemployment 3rdLd-Writethru f0046 10-07 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Unemployment, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0046,0886</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs Reagan comment after 18th graf pvs, Vice
President</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civilian unemployment fell 0.2 percentage
point to 5.4 percent last month as payrolls grew by 255,000 jobs,
100,000 of them in education with the opening of the fall school
term, the government said today.
   The decline erased an August gain and returned joblessness to
July's level.
   With only one more jobless rate to come before the Nov. 8
election, economists said they did not expect the reports for
September and October to help Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis. The October jobless figures will be reported only
four days before the election.
   Across private industry, the job gain was just 142,000. It was
the second straight month of little expansion after average monthly
increases of 300,000 over the first seven months of 1988, the Labor
Department said.
   Assembly-line manufacturing jobs fell by 19,000 atop a loss of
18,000 jobs in August. That reversed an upward trend that had
persisted for 1{ years. Oil and gas industry employment also fell
for the second month in a row after edging up gradually across the
previous 12 months.
   Together, those industries had averaged a monthly job gain of
65,000 from January through July.
   Adult men accounted for nearly all of the decline in the overall
rate last month, with joblessness falling from 4.9 percent in
August to 4.5 percent last month.
   Except for Hispanics, whose rate fell from 8.4 percent to 7.4
percent, there was little change among the various population
groups tracked.
   The September figures show that the number of unemployed
Americans fell by 255,000 to 6.6 million.
   The number of ``discouraged workers,'' those who have given up
the hunt for a job in the belief that they could not find one, rose
from 910,000 to 930,000 in the third quarter of 1988. More than
half of the discouraged workers were women and one-third were
blacks.
   ``Monthly increases in total payroll employment have slowed in
the third quarter, averaging only a little more than 200,000 per
month compared with 340,000 in the first half of the year,'' said
Janet L. Norwood, the commissioner of labor statistics, in
congressional testimony.
   Excluding teachers and other government workers, health services
was the biggest source of new jobs last month, with such payrolls
growing by 62,000. In contrast, the government said, business
services, one of the strongest job sources across the six-year
expansion, showed little growth.
   Wholesale trade added 25,000 jobs in September, continuing a
pattern of consistent growth brought about largely through rising
exports caused by the fallen value of the dollar.
   On the eve of today's report, economists said they had expected
the rate to decline last month.
   ``Even if the unemployment rate went up, Dukakis would not get
any help because the financial markets would react positively,''
said Allen Sinai, chief economist for the Boston Co., a private
consulting house.
   Lawrence Chimerine, chairman of the WEFA Group, a consulting
firm based in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., predicted that employment,
inflation and trade figures between now and the election all will
paint a rosy economy.
   ``He's not going to get any help from the raw employment
figures,'' Chimerine said of Dukakis. ``If he's going to win on
economics, it's going to have to come from convincing people
there's a problem ahead of us.''
   Vice President and Republican presidential nominee George Bush
has repeatedly focused on the creation of some 15 million new jobs
under the Reagan administration since the end of the 1981-82
recession, which had sent the jobless rate into double digits.
   Making much the same point, President Reagan told reporters this
morning:
   ``We talk about the record 70 months of economic expansion but
these figures tell the real story that people can understand. They
mean paychecks, school clothes and families that can plan a
brighter future.
   ``That's what George Bush and Dan Quayle stand for and that's
what the administration has worked for in the last eight years.''
   Dukakis has countered that the issue is not the number of new
jobs being created, but the quality of those jobs, saying hourly
wages after adjustments for inflation have fallen since President
Reagan assumed office in 1981.
   August figures on inflation and average wages bolstered that
argument. The Labor Department reported that real hourly earnings
in terms of purchasing power dropped 1.3 percent during the month,
the worst decline since the government began collecting figures on
them in 1964.
   The Labor Department said today that average hourly wages rose
0.5 percentage point last month to $9.37 after declining by two
cents an hour from May through August.
   Chimerine said private surveys show wages beginning to
accelerate, ``but very, very slowly'' at an annual rate of between
3.5 percent to 4 percent.
   ``There have be some large increases for entry-level jobs, but
they have not spread throughout the society,'' he said. ``Large
companies, in particular, have been successful in resisting them.''
   An alternate jobless rate, including the 1.7 million members of
the armed forces stationed in the United States, also fell 0.2
percentage point last month _ to 5.3 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
