<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Pillsbury 1stLd-Writethru f0033 10-07 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0033,0816</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Steps Up Its Criticism Of Grand Met</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDs 6 new grafs after 5th graf pvs with new information;
picks up 6th graf pvs, ``Smith made ..''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Pillsbury Co. has not rejected Grand
Metropolitan PLC's $5.2 billion takeover offer, it has become
increasingly hostile toward the British company, warning
shareholders not to be fooled by its ``blitz campaign.''
   In his first major public response to the unsolicited
$60-a-share bid launched Tuesday, Pillsbury Chairman Philip Smith
Grand Met was trying to ``stampede'' shareholders and others into
believing the offer was ``good for all our constituents.''
   ``We should not accept Grand Met's words at face value,'' he
said Thursday.
   Smith also told Pillsbury employees to treat the British food
and liquor conglomerate with skepticism when it claims that a
successful takeover would not result in major job cuts.
   Separately, Pillsbury said late Thursday that a Michigan state
judge had upheld a restraining order barring Grand Metropolitan
from buying any Pillsbury stock because of questions over whether a
buyout would violate liquor laws in a number of states.
   Smith and two other Pillsbury officials met privately late in
the day with Gov. Rudy Perpich at the Capitol to brief the governor
on the takeover ``in terms of Pillsbury's perspective,'' Ray Bohn,
Perpich's communications director, confirmed today.
   Bohn said the Pillsbury officials requested the meeting and
spent between 30 and 45 minutes with the governor.
   ``They know that, in terms of legislative prerogatives, there's
not much that can be done because they're a Delaware corporation,''
Bohn said.
   He said the Pillsbury officials asked the governor to check
whether Grand Metropolitan may be violating an old state law
prohibiting companies which produce or distill liquor from owning
retail liquor outlets such as Pillsbury's Steak and Ale restaurants.
   Bohn said Perpich agreed to check with the attorney general's
office and with state Public Safety Commissioner Paul Tschida and
expects to have a response within a few days.
   The Chicago Tribune, in its editions today, quoted Smith as
saying Thursday, ``We're not going to be taken over'' by Grand
Metropolitan. The newspaper said Smith made the comment to the
Tribune ``after a hastily arranged meeting'' with Perpich.
   Smith made his remarks in a letter to employees of the
Minneapolis-based food and restaurant business. The letter also was
distributed to the news media.
   Pillsbury's board of directors is studying the $5.23 billion
buyout offer to shareholders and will make a recommendation ``in
due course,'' Smith said.
   Larry Haeg, a Pillsbury spokesman, said Pillsbury has not
discussed the takeover bid with Grand Met, a major wine and spirits
maker which also owns hotels, betting offices in England and
Ireland, Alpo pet food and Pearle vision centers.
   Grand Met officials have indicated they would not engage in
wholesale job reductions at Pillsbury, but ``Grand Met's history is
filled with just the opposite kind of corporate behavior,'' Smith
said in his letter, which did not cite examples.
   Walter Montgomery, a spokesman for Grand Met in New York,
disputed Smith's remark about job reductions.
   ``The letter is what it is,'' Montgomery said. ``It has a
purpose. You figure it out.''
   Smith also disputed assertions by security analysts, Grand Met
and some newspapers that Pillsbury has few choices in dealing with
the takeover bid.
   ``... They have no idea what programs I've been working on to
add value to this company,'' Smith said. ``But I think there are
significant opportunities to improve the value.''
   Some analysts have said Pillsbury shareholders might have a hard
time rejecting the all-cash offer. Before Grand Met offered $60 a
share, the stock was trading in the range of $39.
   Pillsbury's stock closed down 25 cents to $57.87{ Thursday on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   The Michigan court ruling stemmed from Pillsbury's attempt to
block Grand met by suing the company in 14 states on the grounds a
takeover would violate ``tied-house'' statutes prohibiting liquor
manufacturers from owning retail liquor outlets.
   The decision by Judge Frederick Zeim in Oakland County Circuit
Court marked the second time that such a restraining order has
withstood a challenge by Grand Met, said Johnny Thompson, a
Pillsbury spokesman.
   Of the 14 lawsuits filed, seven have resulted in restraining
orders against Grand Met, Thompson said.
   Grand Met wants an exemption from the statutes, saying it would
sell the Pillsbury's retail liquor outlets if it bought the company.
   Grand Met also announced Thursday that it had lined up an
additional $2.25 billion in financing for the proposed buyout.
   Combined with $3.75 billion in financing already in place, the
revolving line of credit supplied by six European banks gives Grand
Met $6 billion in available funds, Montgomery said.
</TEXT>
