<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices dipped in early
trading today at the Chicago Board of Trade, pressured by
expectations of bearish crop production reports and good harvesting
weather.
   Updated estimates on grain and soybean harvest yields to be
released by the U.S. Department of Agriculture next Wednesday are
expected to show larger amounts than previous figures, and that led
traders to sell, analysts said.
   Dry weather forecast for much of the Midwest over the weekend
was expected to allow active harvesting in both corn and soybeans,
which helped keep the lid on prices.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 2} cents lower, with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.30 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1} cents lower, with December at $2.96\ a bushel; oats
were 3\ cents lower to { cent higher, with December at $2.44 a
bushel; and soybeans were 4} cents lower to 2\ cents higher, with
November at $8.08 a bushel.
   Cattle and hog futures prices opened mixed at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, live cattle were .12 cent to .32 cent lower,
with the contract for delivery in October at 72.15 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were unchanged to .32 cent higher, with October at
81.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .28 cent lower to .20 cent
higher, with October at 40.05 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .0 cent to .65 cent lower, with February at 8.60 cents
a pound.
   Cattle prices were mostly higher, hog prices were mostly lower
and pork bellies declined in trading Thursday.
