<HEAD>London Shares Rise 5.8 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange closed
higher Friday in active trading.
   Mining giant RTZ Corp.'s 260 million-pound ($442 million) sale
of its 28 percent holding in London and Scottish Marine Oil was the
main feature of the day.
   However, interest later dried up as the market paused to catch
its breath and consolidate after advancing sharply over the course
of the week, dealers said.
   Trading volume in Lasmo amounted to 113 million shares Friday,
or about 20 percent of the total shares traded on London's Stock
Exchange, as RTZ's 52 million shares were placed with various
institutions by brokers Cazenove and Co. at 500 pence each ($8.50).
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index rose 5.8
points, or 0.3 percent, to close at 1,844.7.
   The index dropped to a session low of 6.1 points soon after the
market's official 9 a.m. opening.
   Lasmo shares ended 20 pence (34 cents) lower at 531 pence
($9.03).
   Trading volume amounted to 583 million shares, up slightly from
Thursday's volume of 577 million shares.
   Traders said London players also derived some support from a
healthy start on Wall Street. The Dow Jones industrial average was
up 22.23 points at 2,129.98 during the London afternoon.
