<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1509EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv08-09   10-07 0928</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 08-09,0955</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 8-9</NOTE>
<HEAD>Corn, Hog Markets Keep Watchful Eye On Aflatoxin Spread</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers across the Midwest are examining their corn while
traders keep a watchful eye on the market as the discovery of a
cancer-causing toxic mold _ a by-product of this summer's drought _
threatens to curb an already reduced crop.
   Early indications are that aflatoxin, though found already in
several states, will not pose a serious problem, experts say. But
concerns that the progressing harvest will reveal the mold is
widespread have lent support to corn prices at the Chicago Board of
Trade, analysts say.
   And aflatoxin is in the back of the minds of traders at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, where prices of hogs _ a major corn
consumer and especially vulnerable to the toxin _ would feel the
effects of an outbreak.
   ``One thought is that it's going to reduce the corn supply,''
said Thomas Morgan, a livestock analyst and president of Sterling
Research Corp. in Arlington Heights, Ill.
   ``The other concern is that if the contamination becomes too
widespread it will hurt our exports _ countries would not want to
buy'' U.S. corn out of fear of contamination. ``So it could have a
bullish or bearish impact,'' Morgan said.
   But with only about one-third of the nation's corn crop in the
bin, it's too soon to tell, he said.
   The toxin is a metabolic by-product of the fungus Aspergillus
flavus, which primarily affects corn and peanut crops, said Walker
Kirby, a plant pathologist at the University of Illinois.
   The fungus appears on corn kernels in hot, dry weather and
thrives in conditions like this past summer's drought, followed by
the wet fall.
   Ordinarily, the fungus can only be detected through a series of
tests. But on a severely affected ear of corn, it shows up as an
olive-green colored mold, visible to the naked eye, he said.
   After tainted corn is harvested, the fungus will spread in
storage unless the crop is kept cool and dry, Kirby said. Neither
heat treatment nor fungicides destroy the toxin.
   Animals generally begin showing symptoms such as loss of
appetite and weight if fed corn tainted with about 200 to 300 parts
per billion for a period of two months or more, Kirby said.
   In extremely large doses, the toxin can cause liver cancer in
humans. But it is ``highly unlikely'' that humans will be affected
by the outbreak, said Dan Faulkner, an animal sciences professor at
the University of Illinois.
   This year _ like the last aflatoxin outbreak in 1983, another
drought year _ the toxin has been discovered in corn crops
throughout the Midwest.
   A statewide survey in Illinois of 327 corn samples has found
35.8 percent contained toxin levels of above 20 parts per billion,
the state agriculture department said.
   Under U.S. Food and Drug Administration guidelines, corn
destined for humans or dairy cattle must contain less than 20 parts
per billion of the toxin. Corn for breeding cattle or swine must
contain below 100 parts per billion.
   The FDA this past week revised its standards for corn shipped
interstate, allowing up to 100 parts per billion if the feed is
given only to mature animals.
   The Board of Trade recently announced that ``no corn could be
delivered on our contracts that contained more than the 20
parts-per-billion limit from the FDA guidelines,'' said spokesman
Mark Prout.
   Despite the FDA revision, ``Our limit stays the same, to assure
the users of our markets of the quality of the grain being
traded,'' Prout said.
   Indiana officials estimate that 10 percent to 14 percent of
Indiana corn contains some amounts of the toxin.
   Milk containing unacceptable levels of aflatoxin has been traced
to several Texas dairies.
   The toxin has appeared in Iowa and South Dakota, and testing is
being done in those states as well as in Minnesota and Wisconsin.
   ``If we find out that a lot of the corn is affected and is toxic
... it will affect our costs of production down the road,'' said
livestock analyst Chuck Levitt of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
Chicago.
   ``We're not feeding a lot of the new crop corn yet, we're still
feeding a lot of the old crop corn. But if it really cuts into the
availabilty of corn supplies next year ... it could stimulate some
liquidation of hogs,'' Levitt said. The near-term effect would
likely be a decline in hog futures prices, but the long-term impact
of a diminished corn supply would be bullish.
   ``Tight corn supplies will eventually lead to tighter meat
supplies, you can bet your bottom dollar,'' Levitt said.
   Since the 1983 drought, rapid screening tests have been devised
that can detect the toxin in minutes, Kirby said. At grain
elevators, inspectors first put corn samples under an ultra-violet
light. If kernels glow, the fungus is present, and a rapid
antibody-antigen test is then performed to determine presence and
amount of toxin.
   ``The elevators tell me they're turning away about 5 to 10
percent average corn for having more than 20 parts per billion,''
Kirby said.
   ``If I were a farmer,'' he said, ``I would be sampling my grain,
purchasing a rapid-screening test kit ... I would screen my grain
and I would also be sure that I was storing my grain at a
low-moisture level'' at lower than 70 degrees.
   ``I would definitely be concerned,'' Kirby said, ``but not be
overly concerned. It's a management problem that can be dealt
with.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
