<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-China-Utah     10-07 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Utah,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Delegation Learns Management At Geneva Steel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OREM, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 43-member Chinese delegation came away from
its tour of Geneva Steel of Utah this week so impressed that
members said they intend to borrow some of the management ideas
they found at the central Utah plant.
   ``I think we have already learned valuable management
practices,'' said Cai Zhe Shi, deputy director of the Liaoning
Provincial Department of Metallurgical Industry. ``There are some
steel factories in China whose production is not good. We are very
interested in how to effectively manage factories.''
   The delegation, made up of steel industry and government
officials from the People's Republic of China, were in Utah for
management and operational training at Geneva Steel.
   The group plans to spend two months in the United States to take
a closer look at American steel operations. On Saturday, the
delegation was scheduled to fly to New York City.
   Geneva spokesman Barry Bartlett said Geneva _ originally built
during World War II to supplement military steel production _ was
of special interest to the Chinese.
   ``Geneva Steel has a unique distinction of being an older
integrated steel mill that is continually upgraded with new
technology,'' Bartlett said. ``The Chinese have a similar situation
with older steel plants and older manufacturing that they need to
upgrade rather than replace.
   Bartlett said the Chinese are interested in learning how to stay
competitive without investing in brand new technology.
   Chen Shihuan, senior engineer and vice chief of the works at
Chengdu Iron and Steel Works in Sichuan, China, said the Utah plant
is similar to those in China.
   ``We have learned more here about how to use modernization in
the controls of a plant, which allows a plant that is relatively
old with out-of-date equipment to be very productive,'' he
explained.
   Chen operates a steel plant in the southwest region of China
with 7,000 employees who produce 300,000 tons of steel a year. All
steel plants in China are government-owned.
   Bartlett said Utah stands to benefit from the visit as well.
   ``Exporting to China is certainly another possible outcome in
this interaction. In some regions there is a deficit of the steel
industry,'' Bartlett said.
   China Hua-Yang Technology and Trade Corp. is the delegation's
sponsoring agency host from China.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
