<2ND_LINE>PM-WNBC Goodbye, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0086,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WNBC Signs Off After 62 Years On The Air</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to DELETE incorrect reference to election
returns; SUBS 11th graf, `WEAF had ...' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICH MENDELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   WNBC, NBC's radio flagship for 62 years and once
home to Jack Benny, Bob Hope, Fred Allen and the NBC Symphony
conducted by Arturo Toscanini, goes off the air today as a result
of a corporate takeover.
   The new owner is changing the talk and music station, a
clear-channel spot on the dial at 660 that can be heard in 35
states at night, to an all-sports format.
   The station's forerunner was a pioneer with a string of firsts
including such things as the first broadcast of a World Series and
the first broadcast of the national political conventions. It also
had the first broadcast commercial.
   WNBC's signoff, announced Feb. 18, is the result of a $6 billion
deal in 1985 in which General Electric Co. bought RCA Corp., the
parent company of NBC.
   A Federal Communications Commission regulation prevents a new
owner from keeping both a television and a radio station in the
same market. GE decided to sell its new radio properties and keep
the more profitable WNBC-TV.
   GE sold the NBC radio network to Westwood One for $55 million
and sold five stations to Emmis Broadcasting Corp. for $121.5
million. One station is still up for sale, KNBR in San Francisco.
   WNBC signs off at 5:30 p.m. today and turns into WFAN, Emmis'
sports format station, previously heard at 1050 on the dial. WNBC's
frequency, 660, is more desirable from an engineering standpoint.
   The change means about 50 WNBC employees are out of jobs.
   The station went on the air in April 1922 as W2XY, then owned by
AT&T. It became WBAY in July that year and changed to WEAF in
August. RCA bought the station from AT&T for $1 million in 1926
when it formed NBC to help sell the radios it was building. But the
call letters weren't changed to WNBC until 1946.
   ``The format has changed, the personalities have changed, the
call letters have changed, change is inevitable,'' said WNBC
program director Dale Parsons, one of those losing a job.
   WEAF had the first World Series broadcast, Yankees vs. Giants,
in 1923; the first coast-to-coast hookup in 1924; and the first
broadcast of the national political conventions in 1924. In 1925,
it broadcast a presidential inaugural address _ by Calvin Coolidge
_ for the first time.
   The first radio commercial was aired on WEAF on Aug. 28, 1922,
when a real estate developer from across the East River in Queens
paid $100 for a 10-minute announcement to advertise apartments.
   ``Up to that point radio was for experimenters and people were
still thinking of ways to make money with it,'' Parsons said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
