<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankBid     10-07 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Board Authorizes Bank of NY Merger</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: will be led with closing stock price.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp.'s board of directors approved
Friday a management-backed $1.48 billion merger with hostile suitor
Bank of New York Co., ending one of the nation's lengthiest and
most bitter takeover battles.
   The merger will nearly double Bank of New York's size, vaulting
it close to the top 10 of the nation's largest banking companies.
The two had a combined $47.8 billion in assets as of June 30.
   The board vote Friday came two days after Irving Chairman Joseph
A. Rice announced he would abandon his year-long resistance to the
proposed acquisition and drop all pending lawsuits and
anti-takeover defenses aimed at stopping Bank of New York.
   Rice also promised to move up his retirement plans and leave
after the deal was completed.
   In return, Bank of New York sweetened its previous hostile offer
by about $200 million by slightly increasing the stock portion of
the bid and adding stock warrants.
   Bank of New York has a tender offer, scheduled to expire Oct.
21, under way for Irving shares. As of Sept. 30, nearly 10.46
million of Irving's 18.9 million outstanding shares had been
tendered to Bank of New York, said Owen Brady, a Bank of New York
spokesman.
   Neither side has commented publicly on the turn of events
leading to the tentative pact. But banking analysts agreed Irving
was forced to negotiate in the absence of any ``white knight''
takeover partner and after an appeals court invalidated Irving's
anti-takeover ``poison pill'' defense.
   The Appellate Division of New York State Supreme Court on
Tuesday struck down a provision allowing all Irving shareholders _
except a hostile suitor _ to buy $400 worth of Irving shares for
$200 if any suitor bought more than 20 percent of Irving stock
without Irving management support. Such devices are intended to
make unsolicited takeover bids prohibitively expensive.
   Irving had vowed to appeal the ruling to the state's highest
court, the Court of Appeals. But some legal experts questioned
whether that court would have considered the case since the
Appellate Division's decision was unanimous.
   Last spring, Milan-based Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, offered
to merge with Irving as part of a major restructuring of the New
York bank. But it recently withdrew the bid after the Federal
Reserve Board ruled the Italian government agency that owned most
of Banca Commerciale had to supply separate financial imformation.
   The Fed already has given conditional approval for an
Irving-Bank of New York merger.
   Under its revised bid, Bank of New York, which owns 4.9 percent
of Irving, would pay $15 in cash and 1.675 shares of its own stock
for each of Irving's common shares outstanding. It also included
warrants valued at $5 toward the purchase of Bank of New York stock.
   The entire deal was worth about $78.42 a share, or about $1.48
billion, according to Bank of New York figures.
   Irving stock was trading at $74.75 a share on the New York Stock
Exchange Friday afternoon, up $1.12{ from late Thursday.
   All present directors of Irving would be invited to join Bank of
New York's board of directors under the proposed plan, and all key
personnel decisions would be made by a committee of directors made
up of three directors of the Bank of New York and two current
Irving directors.
   When Bank of New York first made its bid on Sept. 25, 1987, it
had the distinction of being the first-ever hostile takeover fight
between two big American banks. It then became the lengthiest such
battle among major U.S. corporations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
