<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-07 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0191</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices plunged Friday at the
Chicago Board of Trade, pressured by a lack of export business and
expections of higher government crop estimates.
   The negative sentiment spilled over into the corn pit, sparking
a selling wave that kept prices down, analysts said. Wheat prices
rallied on ongoing expectations that China and the Soviet Union
plan big purchases, said analyst Joel Karlin of Research Department
Inc.
   Anticipation that updated U.S. Department of Agriculture
estimates to be released next Wednesday will show higher soybean
harvest yields helped trigger the sell-off in beans, he said.
   Good harvesting weather forecast for the weekend also added a
negative tone to corn and soybean prices, analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 2\ cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in December $4.35; corn was 1 cent to 3}
cents lower, with December at $2.94\ a bushel; oats were 1{ cents
to 3 cents lower, with December at $2.43{ a bushel; and soybeans
were 1 cent to 23} cents lower, with November at $7.89 a bushel.
</TEXT>
