<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1550EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EgoTrio Bjt   10-07 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ego Trio, Bjt,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>From Queens and With King-Sized Egos, Trio Tries To Negotiate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They all hail from Queens, and their egos are
king-sized.
   Corporate raider Carl Icahn, airline cost-slasher Frank Lorenzo
and glitzy real estate mogul Donald Trump speak the language of the
working-class New York borough.
   They have made millions from their brash mega-deals. They live
in luxury. Now each is keenly interested in Eastern Airlines.
   The similarities are startling, but their unyielding tycoon
styles raise the question of whether this ego trio ultimately can
agree on a way to divvy up financially troubled Eastern, part of
Lorenzo's Texas Air Corp.
   Lorenzo is believed to be looking to sell parts or all of
Miami-based Eastern, which has been fraught with labor conflict and
staggering losses before and since he took over.
   ``The question is whether there's a (negotiating) table big
enough to get all three around,'' chuckled one Wall Street
investment banker who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``It's very
difficult to do any three-party deal, and when you have the likes
of those three, it increases the degree of difficulty
exponentially.''
   Icahn, who heads Trans World Airlines Inc., has met with Lorenzo
in the past to discuss the possibility of buying some Eastern
assets. But he re-emerged this week, reportedly interested in
acquiring all of Eastern except for its lucrative shuttle service.
   Enter Trump, of Atlantic City, N.J., hotel and casino fame. He
has his eye on the shuttle, which serves New York, Boston and
Washington.
   Despite the trading floor jokes, one Wall Street source noted
that ``what you've got is three very sharp deal people, and there's
a feeling they can probably come up with something very creative if
they want to achieve the end result.''
   Icahn has retained the quick reflexes of his trader days. In
typical raider fashion, Icahn buys into companies whose assets are
worth more than their stock price, and then makes money selling the
companies later _ whole or in pieces _ unless the companies offer
to buy him out at a premium.
   His target list ranges from USX Corp. to Texaco Inc. The only
deterrent, Icahn has said, is a company's stock price, a most
telling ``report card.''
   A Princeton University graduate and medical school dropout,
Icahn resides in a verdant New York suburb and has designed the
gardens that skirt his mansion. But he is said to be more intensely
interested in business than in indulging in the pleasures of wealth.
   Posing beside him in a photograph that appeared in Business Week
magazine recently was a majestic German shepherd. But his interest
in animals doesn't stop there. Within his business empire are
partnerships that bear the names Gnu Corp., Buffalo Investors
Corp., Wolf Investors and Stork Associates.
   Francisco Lorenzo is a Harvard man. His parents emigrated from
Spain and ran a hairdressing salon in midtown Manhattan, but their
business, he once said, was hit hard by the advent of the
do-it-at-home permanent wave.
   His goal has been to run businesses that are as lean as his
distance-runner's frame. He shocked the industry in 1983 by filing
to reorganize Continental Airlines under federal bankruptcy laws,
firing all 12,000 employees in the process. He hired back only
4,000 at tremendous wage cuts.
   Often projecting a cold, tough-guy persona, Lorenzo threatened
several times to have beefy security guards eject shareholders from
the Texas Air annual meeting in June because they continued their
questioning after he had asked them to refrain.
   Beaming proudly this week when Lorenzo announced a $50 million
deal with Scandinavian Airlines System was his neatly coiffed
mother, who often attends his business functions.
   Trump, a product of military school and the Wharton School,
followed in his father's footsteps when he embarked upon a career
as a developer. But he made his bailiwick Manhattan, rather than
the less tony outer boroughs.
   Success came before he was even 30, and Trump was eager to
accumulate the riches his money could provide. He seems driven to
have his name emblazoned on high-profile properties like
skyscrapers, million-dollar condos, casinos and helicopters.
   In the 1970s he offered to build a $170 million convention
center for the city of New York if his father's name could appear
on it. The city declined.
   Among his recent purchases is the Plaza Hotel, a French
Renaissance landmark adjacent to Central Park, which he purchased
for about $400 million. The 808-room hotel is being run by his
Czech-born wife, Ivana, for ``$1 a year and all the dresses she can
buy.'' Under her tutelage, employees have been instructed to
regularly stamp the sand in the hotel's ashtrays with the Plaza
logo.
</TEXT>
