<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 2217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv08-09   10-07 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 08-09,0691</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct 8-9</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bond Market Cheered by September Employment Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Fridays are proving to be full of mostly
pleasant surprises for the bond market. But some analysts see
turbulence ahead.
   For the past two months, the first Friday has meant reassurance
for bondholders worried that the economy may be growing so fast
that inflation will accelerate and take a heavy toll on the value
of their fixed-income securities.
   The first Friday of each month is when the government reports on
the employment situation in the previous month, providing the most
current official glimpse of the state of the economy.
   The reports for August and September have indicated to many
analysts that the economy is growing at a moderate yet still
healthy pace.
   More important, each of the reports was viewed as reducing
chances that the Federal Reserve would feel compelled to encourage
higher interest rates.
   This past Friday, the government reported that the September
unemployment rate slipped to 5.4 percent from 5.6 percent the
previous month. Most bond traders focused on payroll employment
growth, though, and the September increase of 255,000 jobs fell
45,000 short of expectations.
   The reaction was immediate. Prices jumped and trading volume
swelled after slowing to a trickle in the past few days in
anticipation of the report.
   By midafternoon, the price of the 30-year Treasury bond was up
more than $15 for every $1,000 in face value and its yield was at
8.80 percent, its lowest level since mid-April.
   The rally was not quite as strong as the one that followed the
release of the August unemployment figures, which saw the
unemployment rate rise to 5.6 percent from 5.4 percent in July and
payroll growth of 219,000.
   Bonds staged one of their biggest advances of the year that day,
with some 30-year Treasury issues rising more than $25 for every
$1,000 in face value.
   Some analysts said the latest report confirmed the conclusion
suggested by the unemployment report a month ago that the economy
was moderating.
   ``It belied the notion that the August figures were an
aberration,'' said Elliott Platt, fixed-income research director
for the investment firm Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette Securities
Corp. ``It appears they were the beginning of a new moderate growth
trend for the economy.''
   But other analysts said economy continues to grow at a fairly
strong pace and warned that higher interest rates may lie ahead.
   Leonard Santow, managing director for Griggs & Santow Inc., a
financial consulting firm, said, ``The market was so fearful of
huge increases that the number was greeted with a sigh of relief.''
   He said the market's sharp rise Friday may also have reflected a
delayed response to sharp declines in oil prices earlier in the
week.
   Crude oil prices plunged below $13 a barrel to two-year lows at
midweek, a plus for the inflation outlook, but the bond market
barely moved as traders refused to budge before the unemployment
report.
   On the other hand, some economists said the market may have
ignored in its euphoria the wage data released with the
unemployment report.
   It said, for instance, that real hourly earnings dropped 1.3
percent during the month while average hourly wages rose 0.5
percentage point.
   William V. Sullivan Jr., director of money market research for
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said the wage measurements ``provide a
modest hint that there could be some pickup in wage inflation.''
   Can the bond market extend Friday's advance?
   Steven A. Wood, money market economist for BankAmerica Capital
Markets Group in San Francisco, noted that the big rally following
the August unemployment report lasted only a day.
   ``It wouldn't surprise me to see the same kind of reaction this
go around,'' he said, noting that the market runs into some
important producer price and trade balance reports due to be
released in the coming week.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Oct. 8-9</NOTE>
