<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DowName     10-07 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dow Name,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemical May Vanish From Dow Company Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chemical may be its middle name, but Dow
Chemical Co. is thinking of dropping the word to reflect the
increasing breadth of its business, a company official said Friday.
   A consultant and a small study group at Dow are reviewing the
idea, but have reached no conclusions, said Tom Henderson, manager
of public communications.
   Henderson said if there is a change, it will be to show that
Dow's business has expanded beyond basic chemicals to include
products as diverse as insulation and household goods, such as food
wrap and bathroom cleaner.
   The move would follow a trend of several years at Dow, said Mary
O'Neill, chemical industry analyst at Duff & Phelps Inc. in Chicago.
   ``Their strategy over the last seven years has been focused on
diversifying out of commodity chemicals,'' to help lure investors
wary of the cyclical nature of the basic chemical industry, O'Neill
said.
   ``They want to show that they are not cyclical, they're
diversified,'' she said.
   Dow sales comprise about 55 percent basic chemicals and 45
percent specialty goods such as its Styrofoam building insulation
and its household products, O'Neill said.
   Chemical is part of the name, but to describe the business,
Henderson said, ``The word doesn't do anybody much good these days.
We are trying to tell the public that we are more than just a
chemical company.''
   Henderson said no recommendations have been made to top
management. ``If we make a change it's going to be months and
months away,'' he said.
</TEXT>
