<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-07 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Price Plunge Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices plunged for the second consecutive day
Friday at the Chicago Board of Trade, pressured by a lack of export
business, expectations of higher government crop estimates and good
harvesting weather.
   In other markets, wheat prices rallied, corn prices dipped,
cocoa prices surged, oil prices advanced, gold declined, silver
prices were higher, cattle and hog prices were mixed, and frozen
pork bellies were sharply lower,
   Anticipation that updated U.S. Department of Agriculture
estimates to be released next Wednesday will show higher soybean
harvest yields helped trigger the sell-off in beans, said analyst
Joel Karlin of Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   The November contract fell 22} cents and settled at $7.90 a
bushel, the lowest level since late July.
   The negative sentiment spilled over into the corn pit, sparking
a selling wave that kept prices down, analysts said. Wheat prices
rallied on ongoing expectations that China and the Soviet Union
plan big purchases,
   Good harvesting weather forecast for the weekend also added a
negative tone to corn and soybean prices, analysts said.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 1} cents higher, with December at
$4.34{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 4 cents lower, with December at
$2.94\ a bushel; oats were { cent to 3{ cents lower, with December
at $2.44\ a bushel; and soybeans were 7 cents to 22} cents lower,
with November at $7.90 a bushel.
   Cocoa prices advanced at the Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange in
New York on the Ivory Coast's announcement that it will not cut the
price it pays cocoa farmers.
   The news Thursday from the world's largest cocoa producer
indicates that the Ivory Coast likely will try to ``keep prices
very highly valued into the season,'' said analyst Sandra Kaul of
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Cocoa prices settled $18 to $39 higher, with the contract for
delivery in December at $1,278 a ton.
   The rally in oil prices after a week-long slide was due mostly
to technical factors, as traders squared their positions before the
weekend, analysts said.
   But overproduction, which has sparked strong declines in recent
days, remained the underlying influence on the market, they said.
   Crude oil was 25 cents to 28 cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in November at $12.94 a barrel; heating oil was .22 cent
to .57 cent higher, with November at 37.46 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .21 cent to .80 cent higher, with November at 40.13
cents a gallon.
   Trading was quiet in the gold and silver pits at the New York
Commodity Exchange, where stronger oil prices and a softer U.S.
dollar encouraged some buying. But gains were offset by strong
treasury bond prices, analysts said.
   Gold prices settled 60 cents to $1.80 lower, with the October
contract at $403.20 a troy ounce; silver was 2.5 cents to 3.7 cents
higher, with October at $6.325 a troy ounce.
   Light boxed-beef sales kept the lid on live cattle prices at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while cheaper corn prices buoyed
feeder cattle prices, said Tom Morgan, president of Sterling
Research Corp. in Arlington Heights, Ill.
   Pork belly prices were down on mostly technical factors, and the
negative sentiment spilled over into the hog pit, he said.
   Live cattled settled .15 cent lower to .05 cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in October at 72.32 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .20 cent to .55 cent higher, with October at 82.30
cents a pound; live hogs were .25 cent lower to .43 cent higher,
with October at 40.45 cents a pound; and pork bellies were 1.35
cents to 1.70 cents lower, with February at 47.52 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
