<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-07 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls On U.S. Unemployment Report; Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed narrowly lower Friday after it
skidded and then regained some ground in response to the Labor
Department's release of September unemployment figures.
   Gold prices were little changed. Republic National Bank of New
York quoted a late bid of $403.30 for a troy ounce of gold, down 20
cents from late Thursday's $403.50.
   Analysts said the dollar fell after the government report, which
included news that the nation's non-farm payroll grew by 255,000
jobs last month. The Labor Department said the unemployment rate
fell 0.2 percent to 5.4 percent.
   Foreign exchange traders had expected a payroll increase of
about 300,000, so the Labor Department's numbers came as a
disappointment.
   Investors interpreted the payroll figures as a sign of weakness
in the economy. But after further consideration, they ``realized
the economy is growing steadily,'' said Peter Frick, foreign
exchange economist at Union Bank of Switzerland in New York.
   In addition, dollar traders seeing the stock and bond markets
improve on the unemployment data were heartened by the demand for
U.S. investments, said Ronald Holzer, chief dealer with Harris
Trust & Co. in Chicago.
   As a result, the dollar regained some of the ground it lost
earlier.
   Dealers expected Monday's Columbus Day bank holiday in New York
and a holiday in Japan to produce quiet trading early next week.
The dollar faces another test next Thursday, when the Commerce
Department issues its report on the nation's trade deficit for
August.
   In Tokyo, where trading ended before the unemployment report
came out, the dollar edged up to 133.50 Japanese yen Friday from
133.30 yen at Thursday's close. Later, in London, it was quoted at
133.55 yen, and in New York, it slipped to 133.37 yen from late
Thursday's 133.645 yen.
   In London, the dollar slipped against the British pound. It cost
$1.6985 to buy one pound, more costly than $1.6935 late Thursday.
Sterling also gained in New York, where it was quoted at $1.69795,
compared with late Thursday's $1.6927.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's prices, included: 1.86285 West German marks, down from
1.86585; 1.58115 Swiss francs, down from 1.5847; 6.3460 French
francs, down from 6.3570; 1,388.50 Italian lire, down from
1,391.75; and 1.20845 Canadian dollars, down from 1.20995.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8608 West German marks, down from 1.8641; 1.5795
Swiss francs, down from 1.5830; 6.3420 French francs, down from
6.3475; 2.0988 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1000; 1,387.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,388.75; and 1.2116 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   Gold prices went nowhere in what a Zurich bullion dealer termed
a ``non-day and a non-event.'' Investor demand for gold remains
low, with fund and portfolio managers spurning it, dealers said.
   Gold edged lower in London to a late bid price of $403.05 a troy
ounce, compared with late Thursday's $403.35.
   In Zurich, gold inched higher, closing at a bid $404.25 compared
with $403.90 late Thursday. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 49
cents to close at a bid $406.22.
   Gold also marked time in New York trading, where it slipped to
$403.20 on the Commodity Exchange from late Thursday's $403.80.
   Silver bullion prices dipped on the London market where the
metal was trading at a late bid price of $6.33 a troy ounce,
compared with Thursday's $6.34. However, silver rose on the
Commodity Exchange in New York to $6.325 from late Thursday's
$6.888.
</TEXT>
