<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Cola-PriceFixing     10-07 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cola-Price Fixing,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Reconsider Price-Fixing Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Robert G. Doumar, who
was told by the Justice Department he illegally sentenced a
Pepsi-Cola bottling company to prison for price fixing, refused
Friday to reconsider his sentence.
   In a six-page opinion, Doumar said he derived his sentence
against Allegheny Pepsi-Cola Bottling Co. ``from the basic
principle that, to the extent possible, the law treats all persons
_ whether natural or corporate _ equally.
   ``Any other treatment would belie that basic principle and
create a special class of persons which this Court is unwilling to
foster,'' he wrote.
   In a Sept. 30 letter, the Justice Department asked Doumar to
reconsider his novel sentence because prosecutors would be unable
to defend the sentence on appeal.
   Last month, Doumar sentenced Allegheny to three years in prison
and fined the company $1 million for fixing its soft drink prices
in collusion with Mid-Atlantic Coca-Cola Bottling Co. The scheme
cost customers in Norfolk, Richmond and Baltimore more than $10
million.
   Doumar warned attorneys and executives of the Pepsi bottler that
the corporation was treated as an individual under the law, and he
would not hesitate to have federal marshals shut down the plant.
   He then suspended the sentence and $50,000 of the fine on the
condition that the company provide four high-ranking executives to
perform one year each of full-time, free community service in each
of the three cities victimized.
   Doumar said a $1 million fine, the maximum penalty for antitrust
violations, was no deterrent since the scheme netted the company
more than $10 million. ``It's just considered a cost of doing
business,'' he said.
   David C. Jordan, a Justice Department attorney who prosecuted
the case, agreed with Doumar's reasoning, but said in his letter
the Sherman antitrust law allows only the imprisonment of
executives, not corporations.
   ``We are not persuaded that Congress intended to authorize
courts to imprison corporations,'' Jordan wrote. ``Indeed,
imprisoning a corporation by having a marshal seize its assets or
otherwise limit its operations could adversely affect competition
and further injure consumers.''
   In response, Doumar said, ``this Court cannot ascribe to
Congress an intent to incur the costs asociated with effectively
enforcing the Sherman Act when violated by individuals but not when
violated by corporations.''
   When told of Doumar's opinion, James H. Walsh, defense attorney
for Alleghany, said he would proceed with his appeal to the 4th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals and use the Justice Department letter
to bolster his case.
   ``I certainly would hope that the letter is beneficial,'' he
said.
   Mid-Atlantic and Allegheny conspired to set prices from 1982 to
1984. Wholesale prices were inflated 25 percent and the cost was
passed on to consumers, according to court records.
   Mid-Atlantic pleaded guilty to the charge and paid fines of $1
million in both Richmond and Washington, D.C. Six top officials of
the two companies received fines and prison terms.
   The Justice Department has said 14 grand juries in 12 states are
continuing their investigation of price fixing in the soft drink
industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
