<2ND_LINE>AM-MCorp-FDIC, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0153,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Big Texas Bank To Seek Federal Help</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 1 graf after 6th graf pvs, ``MCorp also ...''; picks up
7th graf pvs, ``MCorp's stock ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCorp, Texas' second-largest bank-holding company
and the last of the state's major banks to avoid seeking outside
help, said Friday it is seeking a federal bailout in its proposed
recapitalization.
   The bank said it could not predict when or how much aid it would
request.
   ``At this time it is not possible to determine the ultimate
likelihood, amount, nature or timing of any FDIC (Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp.) assistance for any recapitalization, nor is it
possible to predict the impact of the transaction on MCorp's
stockholders and creditors,'' the bank said in a statement
attributed to Gene H. Bishop, chairman and chief executive officer,
and John T. Cater, president and chief operating officer.
   Steve Katsanos, a spokesman for the FDIC in Washington, said the
agency would not have any comment on the matter.
   ``Our standard practice is that we don't comment on requests for
assistance,'' he said.
   The bank's third-quarter results, due out by Tuesday, are
expected to show a bigger jump in non-performing assets than the
$158 million increase posted in the second quarter, according to a
report in the Wall Street Journal.
   MCorp also said it expects to have a net loss of $525 million
for the third period, compared with a net loss of $73.7 million in
the year-ago quarter. The company said it expects to record a
provision for possible loan losses of about $370 million, making
its allowance for bad loans approximately $690 million.
   MCorp's stock had dropped a half dollar to hit a new low of 75
cents a share Tuesday, but bounced back to $1.12{ on Wednesday and
Thursday. Friday's announcement pushed it down to 87{ cents.
   The request to be filed with the FDIC will suggest that MCorp
raise new capital from private investors, including current
stockholders, to accompany the FDIC assistance, the statement said.
   ``MCorp continues to maintain adequate funding to meet the needs
of its customers even though the recent economic challenges in our
region have put enormous pressures on our situation,'' Bishop said.
``We believe that an early resolution by the FDIC of our assistance
proposal will be the most cost-effective alternative for the FDIC.''
   MCorp has 26 banks and 86 banking offices throughout the state.
The company had assets of $20.1 billion as of June 30. Total
deposits were $16.1 billion and total loans were $12.2 billion _ 36
percent of that in real estate loans.
   It was the only major Texas bank not to have resorted to a
federal bailout or purchase by an out-of-state banking company.
   Earlier this year, Dallas-based First RepublicBank Corp., the
state's largest bank-holding company, sought federal assistance and
ultimately was acquired by NCNB Corp. of Charlotte, N.C.
Houston-based First City Bancorporation of Texas was rescued by the
FDIC and Chicago banker A. Robert Abboud.
   A federal review of MCorp's loan portfolio is expected to be
made public soon. Observers have been saying the review by U.S.
Comptroller of the Currency examiners will force MCorp to
significantly increase reserves for loan losses in the third
quarter.
   J. Michael Shepherd, a senior deputy comptroller, said the
report is complete, but he has declined to elaborate on its
findings.
   The Journal reported that the government's examination
discovered worse-than-expected weakness in MCorp's loan portfolio.
   Quoting unidentified regulators and officials close to the
company, the Journal said the review apparently had turned up more
shaky real estate and commercial loans.
   MCorp's third-quarter financial results are expected to show a
bigger jump in non-performing assets than the $158 million increase
it posted in the second quarter, the newspaper said.
   MCorp was formed in October 1984 by the merger of Mercantile
Texas Corp. of Dallas and Southwest Bancshares Inc. of Houston.
MCorp had 69 member banks and total assets of $20 billion.
   Since its formation, it raised $247 million of private capital
in 1985, has raised $653 million in cash and securities through the
sale of its MNet and MTech subsidiaries, and has cut costs.
   MCorp ranked 35th among the nation's largest banking
organizations in terms of total assets on June 30.
</TEXT>
