<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-AMD,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third-Quarter Profit In Contrast To Year-Earlier Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advanced Micro Devices Inc. said it
earned $7.1 million in the third quarter in contrast to a loss of
$70 million in the same period a year earlier.
   However, results were not as strong as in this year's second
quarter, when the company made $26.1 million.
   Revenue in the third quarter was $285.5 million, up from $261
million a year earlier but down from $308 million in this year's
second quarter.
   Chairman and Chief Executive Officer W.J. Sanders III blamed the
decline from the spring figures on a drop in orders for
microprocessors from personal computer manufacturers. He predicted
a continued slump.
   ``We believe that a period of digestion of component inventories
on the part of our customers will keep a lid on new orders and
hence our sales growth for the next several quarters,'' Sanders
continued.
   AMD announced it will continue with plans to close its oldest
operating silicon wafer factory in December and reduce its
workforce in Malaysia and the Philippines by 1,400. The company
said it plans to take a charge against fourth-quarter earnings as a
result of those plans.
   Sanders said he remains ``very positive'' on the longer-term
prospects of AMD's future.
