<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs; retransmitting to fix cycle designator</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have risen in what analysts
said was a technical rally inspired by the expiration of November
options and efforts to square trading positions before the weekend.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate rose 28 cents Friday to settle at $12.94 a
barrel.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the November
contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 0.63 cent to settle
at 40.13 cents a gallon, while home heating oil rose 0.22 cent to
37.46 cents a gallon.
   Prices moved erratically in a narrow range during the day, said
William Byers of the oil futures research department at Bear,
Stearns & Co.
   But he said short-covering, in which traders who have sold
borrowed contracts buy contracts to square their positions, drove
prices higher.
   Richard Redoglia, vice president at Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures, said there was also some buying connected with the
expiration of November options.
   ``The pressure on the market is still there. Overproduction is
still there,'' he said.
   Earlier in the week, crude oil prices tumbled below $13 a barrel
to their lowest level in two years as Saudi Arabia, the world's
largest oil exporter, threatened to produce more than its quota if
other members of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries continued to pump beyond their quotas.
   The Saudis have indicated they want to punish other OPEC members
for overproducing and driving down the price of oil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
